            {
              "id": "CWE-234",
              "name": "FailureToHandleMissingParameter",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "If too few arguments are sent to a function, the function will still pop the expected number of arguments from the stack."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "If too few arguments are sent to a function, the function will still pop the expected number of arguments from the stack. Potentially, a variable number of arguments could be exhausted in a function as well.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIf too few arguments are sent to a function, the function will still pop the expected number of arguments from the stack. Potentially, a variable number of arguments could be exhausted in a function as well.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Confidentiality, Availability, Access Control. **Impact**: Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands, Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n  - There is the potential for arbitrary code execution with privileges of the vulnerable program if function parameter list is exhausted.\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart.\n  - Potentially a program could fail if it needs more arguments then are available.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Build and Compilation*. This issue can be simply combated with the use of proper build process.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Forward declare all functions. This is the recommended solution. Properly forward declaration of all used functions will result in a compiler error if too few arguments are sent to a function."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/234.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Failure to Handle Missing Parameter",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-233"
              }
            },
