                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-330"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-345",
              "name": "InsufficientVerificationOfDataAuthenticity",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not sufficiently verify the origin or authenticity of data, in a way that causes it to accept invalid data."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not sufficiently verify the origin or authenticity of data, in a way that causes it to accept invalid data.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not sufficiently verify the origin or authenticity of data, in a way that causes it to accept invalid data.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Varies by Context, Unexpected State."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/345.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Insufficient Verification of Data Authenticity",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-693"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-346",
              "name": "OriginValidationError",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not properly verify that the source of data or communication is valid."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not properly verify that the source of data or communication is valid.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not properly verify that the source of data or communication is valid.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control, Other. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity, Varies by Context.\n  - An attacker can access any functionality that is inadvertently accessible to the source."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/346.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Origin Validation Error",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-345"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-347",
              "name": "ImproperVerificationOfCryptographicSignature",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not verify, or incorrectly verifies, the cryptographic signature for data."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not verify, or incorrectly verifies, the cryptographic signature for data.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not verify, or incorrectly verifies, the cryptographic signature for data.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control, Integrity, Confidentiality. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity, Modify Application Data, Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands.\n  - An attacker could gain access to sensitive data and possibly execute unauthorized code."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/347.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Improper Verification of Cryptographic Signature",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-345"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-348",
              "name": "UseOfLessTrustedSource",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product has two different sources of the same data or information, but it uses the source that has less support for verification, is less trusted, or is less resistant to attack."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product has two different sources of the same data or information, but it uses the source that has less support for verification, is less trusted, or is less resistant to attack.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product has two different sources of the same data or information, but it uses the source that has less support for verification, is less trusted, or is less resistant to attack.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism, Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n  - An attacker could utilize the untrusted data source to bypass protection mechanisms and gain access to sensitive data."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/348.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Use of Less Trusted Source",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-345"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-349",
              "name": "AcceptanceOfExtraneousUntrustedDataWithTrustedData",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product, when processing trusted data, accepts any untrusted data that is also included with the trusted data, treating the untrusted data as if it were trusted."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product, when processing trusted data, accepts any untrusted data that is also included with the trusted data, treating the untrusted data as if it were trusted.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product, when processing trusted data, accepts any untrusted data that is also included with the trusted data, treating the untrusted data as if it were trusted.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control, Integrity. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism, Modify Application Data.\n  - An attacker could package untrusted data with trusted data to bypass protection mechanisms to gain access to and possibly modify sensitive data."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/349.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Acceptance of Extraneous Untrusted Data With Trusted Data",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-345"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-350",
              "name": "RelianceOnReverseDnsResolutionForASecurityCriticalAction",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product performs reverse DNS resolution on an IP address to obtain the hostname and make a security decision, but it does not properly ensure that the IP address is truly associated with the hostname."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Since DNS names can be easily spoofed or misreported, and it may be difficult for the product to detect if a trusted DNS server has been compromised, DNS names do not constitute a valid authentication mechanism. When the product performs a reverse DNS resolution for an IP address, if an attacker controls the DNS server for that IP address, then the attacker can cause the server to return an arbitrary hostname. As a result, the attacker may be able to bypass authentication, cause the wrong hostname to be recorded in log files to hide activities, or perform other attacks. Attackers can spoof DNS names by either (1) compromising a DNS server and modifying its records (sometimes called DNS cache poisoning), or (2) having legitimate control over a DNS server associated with their IP address."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product performs reverse DNS resolution on an IP address to obtain the hostname and make a security decision, but it does not properly ensure that the IP address is truly associated with the hostname.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product performs reverse DNS resolution on an IP address to obtain the hostname and make a security decision, but it does not properly ensure that the IP address is truly associated with the hostname.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nSince DNS names can be easily spoofed or misreported, and it may be difficult for the product to detect if a trusted DNS server has been compromised, DNS names do not constitute a valid authentication mechanism. When the product performs a reverse DNS resolution for an IP address, if an attacker controls the DNS server for that IP address, then the attacker can cause the server to return an arbitrary hostname. As a result, the attacker may be able to bypass authentication, cause the wrong hostname to be recorded in log files to hide activities, or perform other attacks. Attackers can spoof DNS names by either (1) compromising a DNS server and modifying its records (sometimes called DNS cache poisoning), or (2) having legitimate control over a DNS server associated with their IP address.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity, Bypass Protection Mechanism.\n  - Malicious users can fake authentication information by providing false DNS information.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Use other means of identity verification that cannot be simply spoofed. Possibilities include a username/password or certificate.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Perform proper forward and reverse DNS lookups to detect DNS spoofing."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/350.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Reliance on Reverse DNS Resolution for a Security-Critical Action",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-290"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-351",
              "name": "InsufficientTypeDistinction",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not properly distinguish between different types of elements in a way that leads to insecure behavior."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not properly distinguish between different types of elements in a way that leads to insecure behavior.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not properly distinguish between different types of elements in a way that leads to insecure behavior.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Other."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/351.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Insufficient Type Distinction",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-345"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-352",
              "name": "CrossSiteRequestForgeryCsrf",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The web application does not, or cannot, sufficiently verify whether a request was intentionally provided by the user who sent the request, which could have originated from an unauthorized actor."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The web application does not, or cannot, sufficiently verify whether a request was intentionally provided by the user who sent the request, which could have originated from an unauthorized actor.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe web application does not, or cannot, sufficiently verify whether a request was intentionally provided by the user who sent the request, which could have originated from an unauthorized actor.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability, Non-Repudiation, Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity, Bypass Protection Mechanism, Read Application Data, Modify Application Data, DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart.\n  - The consequences will vary depending on the nature of the functionality that is vulnerable to CSRF. An attacker could trick a client into making an unintentional request to the web server via a URL, image load, XMLHttpRequest, etc., which would then be treated as an authentic request from the client - effectively performing any operations as the victim, leading to an exposure of data, unintended code execution, etc. If the victim is an administrator or privileged user, the consequences may include obtaining complete control over the web application - deleting or stealing data, uninstalling the product, or using it to launch other attacks against all of the product's users. Because the attacker has the identity of the victim, the scope of CSRF is limited only by the victim's privileges.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design; Strategy: Libraries or Frameworks*. Use a vetted library or framework that does not allow this weakness to occur or provides constructs that make this weakness easier to avoid [REF-1482]. For example, use anti-CSRF packages such as the OWASP CSRFGuard. [REF-330] Another example is the ESAPI Session Management control, which includes a component for CSRF. [REF-45]\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Ensure that the application is free of cross-site scripting issues (CWE-79), because most CSRF defenses can be bypassed using attacker-controlled script.\n3. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Generate a unique nonce for each form, place the nonce into the form, and verify the nonce upon receipt of the form. Be sure that the nonce is not predictable (CWE-330). [REF-332]\n4. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Identify especially dangerous operations. When the user performs a dangerous operation, send a separate confirmation request to ensure that the user intended to perform that operation.\n5. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Use the \"double-submitted cookie\" method as described by Felten and Zeller: When a user visits a site, the site should generate a pseudorandom value and set it as a cookie on the user's machine. The site should require every form submission to include this value as a form value and also as a cookie value. When a POST request is sent to the site, the request should only be considered valid if the form value and the cookie value are the same. Because of the same-origin policy, an attacker cannot read or modify the value stored in the cookie. To successfully submit a form on behalf of the user, the attacker would have to correctly guess the pseudorandom value. If the pseudorandom value is cryptographically strong, this will be prohibitively difficult. This technique requires Javascript, so it may not work for browsers that have Javascript disabled. [REF-331]\n6. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Do not use the GET method for any request that triggers a state change.\n7. *Phase: Implementation*. Check the HTTP Referer header to see if the request originated from an expected page. This could break legitimate functionality, because users or proxies may have disabled sending the Referer for privacy reasons."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)",
                "cwe/status": "Stable",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Compound",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-345"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-353",
              "name": "MissingSupportForIntegrityCheck",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses a transmission protocol that does not include a mechanism for verifying the integrity of the data during transmission, such as a checksum."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "If integrity check values or \"checksums\" are omitted from a protocol, there is no way of determining if data has been corrupted in transmission. The lack of checksum functionality in a protocol removes the first application-level check of data that can be used. The end-to-end philosophy of checks states that integrity checks should be performed at the lowest level that they can be completely implemented. Excluding further sanity checks and input validation performed by applications, the protocol's checksum is the most important level of checksum, since it can be performed more completely than at any previous level and takes into account entire messages, as opposed to single packets."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses a transmission protocol that does not include a mechanism for verifying the integrity of the data during transmission, such as a checksum.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses a transmission protocol that does not include a mechanism for verifying the integrity of the data during transmission, such as a checksum.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIf integrity check values or \"checksums\" are omitted from a protocol, there is no way of determining if data has been corrupted in transmission. The lack of checksum functionality in a protocol removes the first application-level check of data that can be used. The end-to-end philosophy of checks states that integrity checks should be performed at the lowest level that they can be completely implemented. Excluding further sanity checks and input validation performed by applications, the protocol's checksum is the most important level of checksum, since it can be performed more completely than at any previous level and takes into account entire messages, as opposed to single packets.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Other.\n  - Data that is parsed and used may be corrupted.\n- **Scope**: Non-Repudiation, Other. **Impact**: Hide Activities, Other.\n  - Without a checksum it is impossible to determine if any changes have been made to the data after it was sent.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Add an appropriately sized checksum to the protocol, ensuring that data received may be simply validated before it is parsed and used.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Ensure that the checksums present in the protocol design are properly implemented and added to each message before it is sent."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/353.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Missing Support for Integrity Check",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-345"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-354",
              "name": "ImproperValidationOfIntegrityCheckValue",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not validate or incorrectly validates the integrity check values or \"checksums\" of a message."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Improper validation of checksums before use results in an unnecessary risk that can easily be mitigated. The protocol specification describes the algorithm used for calculating the checksum. It is then a simple matter of implementing the calculation and verifying that the calculated checksum and the received checksum match. Improper verification of the calculated checksum and the received checksum can lead to far greater consequences."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not validate or incorrectly validates the integrity check values or \"checksums\" of a message. This may prevent it from detecting if the data has been modified or corrupted in transmission.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not validate or incorrectly validates the integrity check values or \"checksums\" of a message. This may prevent it from detecting if the data has been modified or corrupted in transmission.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nImproper validation of checksums before use results in an unnecessary risk that can easily be mitigated. The protocol specification describes the algorithm used for calculating the checksum. It is then a simple matter of implementing the calculation and verifying that the calculated checksum and the received checksum match. Improper verification of the calculated checksum and the received checksum can lead to far greater consequences.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Modify Application Data, Other.\n  - Integrity checks usually use a secret key that helps authenticate the data origin. Skipping integrity checking generally opens up the possibility that new data from an invalid source can be injected.\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Other.\n  - Data that is parsed and used may be corrupted.\n- **Scope**: Non-Repudiation, Other. **Impact**: Hide Activities, Other.\n  - Without a checksum check, it is impossible to determine if any changes have been made to the data after it was sent.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Ensure that the checksums present in messages are properly checked in accordance with the protocol specification before they are parsed and used."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/354.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Improper Validation of Integrity Check Value",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-345"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-356",
              "name": "ProductUiDoesNotWarnUserOfUnsafeActions",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product's user interface does not warn the user before undertaking an unsafe action on behalf of that user."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Product systems should warn users that a potentially dangerous action may occur if the user proceeds. For example, if the user downloads a file from an unknown source and attempts to execute the file on their machine, then the application's GUI can indicate that the file is unsafe."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product's user interface does not warn the user before undertaking an unsafe action on behalf of that user. This makes it easier for attackers to trick users into inflicting damage to their system.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product's user interface does not warn the user before undertaking an unsafe action on behalf of that user. This makes it easier for attackers to trick users into inflicting damage to their system.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nProduct systems should warn users that a potentially dangerous action may occur if the user proceeds. For example, if the user downloads a file from an unknown source and attempts to execute the file on their machine, then the application's GUI can indicate that the file is unsafe.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Non-Repudiation. **Impact**: Hide Activities."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/356.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Product UI does not Warn User of Unsafe Actions",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-221"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-357",
              "name": "InsufficientUiWarningOfDangerousOperations",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The user interface provides a warning to a user regarding dangerous or sensitive operations, but the warning is not noticeable enough to warrant attention."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The user interface provides a warning to a user regarding dangerous or sensitive operations, but the warning is not noticeable enough to warrant attention.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe user interface provides a warning to a user regarding dangerous or sensitive operations, but the warning is not noticeable enough to warrant attention.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Non-Repudiation. **Impact**: Hide Activities."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/357.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Insufficient UI Warning of Dangerous Operations",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-693"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-358",
              "name": "ImproperlyImplementedSecurityCheckForStandard",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not implement or incorrectly implements one or more security-relevant checks as specified by the design of a standardized algorithm, protocol, or technique."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not implement or incorrectly implements one or more security-relevant checks as specified by the design of a standardized algorithm, protocol, or technique.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not implement or incorrectly implements one or more security-relevant checks as specified by the design of a standardized algorithm, protocol, or technique.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/358.html",
