                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-573"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-359",
              "name": "ExposureOfPrivatePersonalInformationToAnUnauthorizedActor",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not properly prevent a person's private, personal information from being accessed by actors who either (1) are not explicitly authorized to access the information or (2) do not have the implicit consent of the person about whom the information is collected."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not properly prevent a person's private, personal information from being accessed by actors who either (1) are not explicitly authorized to access the information or (2) do not have the implicit consent of the person about whom the information is collected.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not properly prevent a person's private, personal information from being accessed by actors who either (1) are not explicitly authorized to access the information or (2) do not have the implicit consent of the person about whom the information is collected.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Requirements*. Identify and consult all relevant regulations for personal privacy. An organization may be required to comply with certain federal and state regulations, depending on its location, the type of business it conducts, and the nature of any private data it handles. Regulations may include Safe Harbor Privacy Framework [REF-340], Gramm-Leach Bliley Act (GLBA) [REF-341], Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) [REF-342], General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) [REF-1047], California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA) [REF-1048], and others.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Carefully evaluate how secure design may interfere with privacy, and vice versa. Security and privacy concerns often seem to compete with each other. From a security perspective, all important operations should be recorded so that any anomalous activity can later be identified. However, when private data is involved, this practice can in fact create risk. Although there are many ways in which private data can be handled unsafely, a common risk stems from misplaced trust. Programmers often trust the operating environment in which a program runs, and therefore believe that it is acceptable store private information on the file system, in the registry, or in other locally-controlled resources. However, even if access to certain resources is restricted, this does not guarantee that the individuals who do have access can be trusted.\n3. *Phase: Implementation, Operation; Strategy: Attack Surface Reduction*. Some tools can automatically analyze documents to redact, strip, or \"sanitize\" private information, although some human review might be necessary. Tools may vary in terms of which document formats can be processed. When calling an external program to automatically generate or convert documents, invoke the program with any available options that avoid generating sensitive metadata. Some formats have well-defined fields that could contain private data, such as Exchangeable image file format (Exif), which can contain potentially sensitive metadata such as geolocation, date, and time [REF-1515] [REF-1516]."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/359.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Exposure of Private Personal Information to an Unauthorized Actor",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-200"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-360",
              "name": "TrustOfSystemEventData",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Security based on event locations are insecure and can be spoofed."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Events are a messaging system which may provide control data to programs listening for events. Events often do not have any type of authentication framework to allow them to be verified from a trusted source. Any application, in Windows, on a given desktop can send a message to any window on the same desktop. There is no authentication framework for these messages. Therefore, any message can be used to manipulate any process on the desktop if the process does not check the validity and safeness of those messages."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Security based on event locations are insecure and can be spoofed.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSecurity based on event locations are insecure and can be spoofed.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nEvents are a messaging system which may provide control data to programs listening for events. Events often do not have any type of authentication framework to allow them to be verified from a trusted source. Any application, in Windows, on a given desktop can send a message to any window on the same desktop. There is no authentication framework for these messages. Therefore, any message can be used to manipulate any process on the desktop if the process does not check the validity and safeness of those messages.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Confidentiality, Availability, Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity, Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands.\n  - If one trusts the system-event information and executes commands based on it, one could potentially take actions based on a spoofed identity.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Never trust or rely any of the information in an Event for security."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/360.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Trust of System Event Data",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-345"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-362",
              "name": "RaceCondition",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product contains a concurrent code sequence that requires temporary, exclusive access to a shared resource, but a timing window exists in which the shared resource can be modified by another code sequence operating concurrently."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "A race condition occurs within concurrent environments, and it is effectively a property of a code sequence. Depending on the context, a code sequence may be in the form of a function call, a small number of instructions, a series of program invocations, etc. A race condition violates these properties, which are closely related: Exclusivity - the code sequence is given exclusive access to the shared resource, i.e., no other code sequence can modify properties of the shared resource before the original sequence has completed execution. Atomicity - the code sequence is behaviorally atomic, i.e., no other thread or process can concurrently execute the same sequence of instructions (or a subset) against the same resource. A race condition exists when an \"interfering code sequence\" can still access the shared resource, violating exclusivity. The interfering code sequence could be \"trusted\" or \"untrusted.\" A trusted interfering code sequence occurs within the product; it cannot be modified by the attacker, and it can only be invoked indirectly. An untrusted interfering code sequence can be authored directly by the attacker, and typically it is external to the vulnerable product."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product contains a concurrent code sequence that requires temporary, exclusive access to a shared resource, but a timing window exists in which the shared resource can be modified by another code sequence operating concurrently.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product contains a concurrent code sequence that requires temporary, exclusive access to a shared resource, but a timing window exists in which the shared resource can be modified by another code sequence operating concurrently.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nA race condition occurs within concurrent environments, and it is effectively a property of a code sequence. Depending on the context, a code sequence may be in the form of a function call, a small number of instructions, a series of program invocations, etc. A race condition violates these properties, which are closely related: Exclusivity - the code sequence is given exclusive access to the shared resource, i.e., no other code sequence can modify properties of the shared resource before the original sequence has completed execution. Atomicity - the code sequence is behaviorally atomic, i.e., no other thread or process can concurrently execute the same sequence of instructions (or a subset) against the same resource. A race condition exists when an \"interfering code sequence\" can still access the shared resource, violating exclusivity. The interfering code sequence could be \"trusted\" or \"untrusted.\" A trusted interfering code sequence occurs within the product; it cannot be modified by the attacker, and it can only be invoked indirectly. An untrusted interfering code sequence can be authored directly by the attacker, and typically it is external to the vulnerable product.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Resource Consumption (CPU), DoS: Resource Consumption (Memory), DoS: Resource Consumption (Other).\n  - When a race condition makes it possible to bypass a resource cleanup routine or trigger multiple initialization routines, it may lead to resource exhaustion.\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart, DoS: Instability.\n  - When a race condition allows multiple control flows to access a resource simultaneously, it might lead the product(s) into unexpected states, possibly resulting in a crash.\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity. **Impact**: Read Files or Directories, Read Application Data.\n  - When a race condition is combined with predictable resource names and loose permissions, it may be possible for an attacker to overwrite or access confidential data (CWE-59).\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands, Gain Privileges or Assume Identity, Bypass Protection Mechanism.\n  - This can have security implications when the expected synchronization is in security-critical code, such as recording whether a user is authenticated or modifying important state information that should not be influenced by an outsider.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. In languages that support it, use synchronization primitives. Only wrap these around critical code to minimize the impact on performance.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Use thread-safe capabilities such as the data access abstraction in Spring.\n3. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Minimize the usage of shared resources in order to remove as much complexity as possible from the control flow and to reduce the likelihood of unexpected conditions occurring. Additionally, this will minimize the amount of synchronization necessary and may even help to reduce the likelihood of a denial of service where an attacker may be able to repeatedly trigger a critical section (CWE-400).\n4. *Phase: Implementation*. When using multithreading and operating on shared variables, only use thread-safe functions.\n5. *Phase: Implementation*. Use atomic operations on shared variables. Be wary of innocent-looking constructs such as \"x++\". This may appear atomic at the code layer, but it is actually non-atomic at the instruction layer, since it involves a read, followed by a computation, followed by a write.\n6. *Phase: Implementation*. Use a mutex if available, but be sure to avoid related weaknesses such as CWE-412.\n7. *Phase: Implementation*. Avoid double-checked locking (CWE-609) and other implementation errors that arise when trying to avoid the overhead of synchronization.\n8. *Phase: Implementation*. Disable interrupts or signals over critical parts of the code, but also make sure that the code does not go into a large or infinite loop.\n9. *Phase: Implementation*. Use the volatile type modifier for critical variables to avoid unexpected compiler optimization or reordering. This does not necessarily solve the synchronization problem, but it can help.\n10. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Operation; Strategy: Environment Hardening*. Run your code using the lowest privileges that are required to accomplish the necessary tasks [REF-76]. If possible, create isolated accounts with limited privileges that are only used for a single task. That way, a successful attack will not immediately give the attacker access to the rest of the software or its environment. For example, database applications rarely need to run as the database administrator, especially in day-to-day operations."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/362.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Concurrent Execution using Shared Resource with Improper Synchronization ('Race Condition')",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-662"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-363",
              "name": "RaceConditionEnablingLinkFollowing",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product checks the status of a file or directory before accessing it, which produces a race condition in which the file can be replaced with a link before the access is performed, causing the product to access the wrong file."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "While developers might expect that there is a very narrow time window between the time of check and time of use, there is still a race condition. An attacker could cause the product to slow down (e.g. with memory consumption), causing the time window to become larger. Alternately, in some situations, the attacker could win the race by performing a large number of attacks."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product checks the status of a file or directory before accessing it, which produces a race condition in which the file can be replaced with a link before the access is performed, causing the product to access the wrong file.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product checks the status of a file or directory before accessing it, which produces a race condition in which the file can be replaced with a link before the access is performed, causing the product to access the wrong file.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nWhile developers might expect that there is a very narrow time window between the time of check and time of use, there is still a race condition. An attacker could cause the product to slow down (e.g. with memory consumption), causing the time window to become larger. Alternately, in some situations, the attacker could win the race by performing a large number of attacks.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity. **Impact**: Read Files or Directories, Modify Files or Directories."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/363.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Race Condition Enabling Link Following",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-367"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-364",
              "name": "SignalHandlerRaceCondition",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses a signal handler that introduces a race condition."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Race conditions frequently occur in signal handlers, since signal handlers support asynchronous actions. These race conditions have a variety of root causes and symptoms. Attackers may be able to exploit a signal handler race condition to cause the product state to be corrupted, possibly leading to a denial of service or even code execution. These issues occur when non-reentrant functions, or state-sensitive actions occur in the signal handler, where they may be called at any time. These behaviors can violate assumptions being made by the \"regular\" code that is interrupted, or by other signal handlers that may also be invoked. If these functions are called at an inopportune moment - such as while a non-reentrant function is already running - memory corruption could occur that may be exploitable for code execution. Another signal race condition commonly found occurs when free is called within a signal handler, resulting in a double free and therefore a write-what-where condition. Even if a given pointer is set to NULL after it has been freed, a race condition still exists between the time the memory was freed and the pointer was set to NULL. This is especially problematic if the same signal handler has been set for more than one signal -- since it means that the signal handler itself may be reentered. There are several known behaviors related to signal handlers that have received the label of \"signal handler race condition\": Shared state (e.g. global data or static variables) that are accessible to both a signal handler and \"regular\" code Shared state between a signal handler and other signal handlers Use of non-reentrant functionality within a signal handler - which generally implies that shared state is being used. For example, malloc() and free() are non-reentrant because they may use global or static data structures for managing memory, and they are indirectly used by innocent-seeming functions such as syslog(); these functions could be exploited for memory corruption and, possibly, code execution. Association of the same signal handler function with multiple signals - which might imply shared state, since the same code and resources are accessed. For example, this can be a source of double-free and use-after-free weaknesses. Use of setjmp and longjmp, or other mechanisms that prevent a signal handler from returning control back to the original functionality While not technically a race condition, some signal handlers are designed to be called at most once, and being called more than once can introduce security problems, even when there are not any concurrent calls to the signal handler. This can be a source of double-free and use-after-free weaknesses. Signal handler vulnerabilities are often classified based on the absence of a specific protection mechanism, although this style of classification is discouraged in CWE because programmers often have a choice of several different mechanisms for addressing the weakness. Such protection mechanisms may preserve exclusivity of access to the shared resource, and behavioral atomicity for the relevant code: Avoiding shared state Using synchronization in the signal handler Using synchronization in the regular code Disabling or masking other signals, which provides atomicity (which effectively ensures exclusivity)"
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses a signal handler that introduces a race condition.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses a signal handler that introduces a race condition.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nRace conditions frequently occur in signal handlers, since signal handlers support asynchronous actions. These race conditions have a variety of root causes and symptoms. Attackers may be able to exploit a signal handler race condition to cause the product state to be corrupted, possibly leading to a denial of service or even code execution. These issues occur when non-reentrant functions, or state-sensitive actions occur in the signal handler, where they may be called at any time. These behaviors can violate assumptions being made by the \"regular\" code that is interrupted, or by other signal handlers that may also be invoked. If these functions are called at an inopportune moment - such as while a non-reentrant function is already running - memory corruption could occur that may be exploitable for code execution. Another signal race condition commonly found occurs when free is called within a signal handler, resulting in a double free and therefore a write-what-where condition. Even if a given pointer is set to NULL after it has been freed, a race condition still exists between the time the memory was freed and the pointer was set to NULL. This is especially problematic if the same signal handler has been set for more than one signal -- since it means that the signal handler itself may be reentered. There are several known behaviors related to signal handlers that have received the label of \"signal handler race condition\": Shared state (e.g. global data or static variables) that are accessible to both a signal handler and \"regular\" code Shared state between a signal handler and other signal handlers Use of non-reentrant functionality within a signal handler - which generally implies that shared state is being used. For example, malloc() and free() are non-reentrant because they may use global or static data structures for managing memory, and they are indirectly used by innocent-seeming functions such as syslog(); these functions could be exploited for memory corruption and, possibly, code execution. Association of the same signal handler function with multiple signals - which might imply shared state, since the same code and resources are accessed. For example, this can be a source of double-free and use-after-free weaknesses. Use of setjmp and longjmp, or other mechanisms that prevent a signal handler from returning control back to the original functionality While not technically a race condition, some signal handlers are designed to be called at most once, and being called more than once can introduce security problems, even when there are not any concurrent calls to the signal handler. This can be a source of double-free and use-after-free weaknesses. Signal handler vulnerabilities are often classified based on the absence of a specific protection mechanism, although this style of classification is discouraged in CWE because programmers often have a choice of several different mechanisms for addressing the weakness. Such protection mechanisms may preserve exclusivity of access to the shared resource, and behavioral atomicity for the relevant code: Avoiding shared state Using synchronization in the signal handler Using synchronization in the regular code Disabling or masking other signals, which provides atomicity (which effectively ensures exclusivity)\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Confidentiality, Availability. **Impact**: Modify Application Data, Modify Memory, DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart, Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands.\n  - It may be possible to cause data corruption and possibly execute arbitrary code by modifying global variables or data structures at unexpected times, violating the assumptions of code that uses this global data.\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n  - If a signal handler interrupts code that is executing with privileges, it may be possible that the signal handler will also be executed with elevated privileges, possibly making subsequent exploits more severe.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Requirements; Strategy: Language Selection*. Use a language that does not allow this weakness to occur or provides constructs that make this weakness easier to avoid.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Design signal handlers to only set flags, rather than perform complex functionality. These flags can then be checked and acted upon within the main program loop.\n3. *Phase: Implementation*. Only use reentrant functions within signal handlers. Also, use validation to ensure that state is consistent while performing asynchronous actions that affect the state of execution."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/364.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Signal Handler Race Condition",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-362"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-365",
              "name": "DeprecatedRaceConditionInSwitch",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "This entry has been deprecated."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "It is likely that this entry was initially created based on a misinterpretation of the original source material. The original source intended to explain how switches could be unpredictable when using threads, if the control expressions used data or variables that could change between execution of different threads. That weakness is already covered by CWE-367. Despite the ambiguity in the documentation for some languages and compilers, in practice, they all evaluate the switch control expression only once. If future languages state that the code explicitly evaluates the control expression more than once, then this would not be a weakness, but the language performing as designed."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "This entry has been deprecated. There are no documented cases in which a switch's control expression is evaluated more than once.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis entry has been deprecated. There are no documented cases in which a switch's control expression is evaluated more than once.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIt is likely that this entry was initially created based on a misinterpretation of the original source material. The original source intended to explain how switches could be unpredictable when using threads, if the control expressions used data or variables that could change between execution of different threads. That weakness is already covered by CWE-367. Despite the ambiguity in the documentation for some languages and compilers, in practice, they all evaluate the switch control expression only once. If future languages state that the code explicitly evaluates the control expression more than once, then this would not be a weakness, but the language performing as designed."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/365.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "DEPRECATED: Race Condition in Switch",
                "cwe/status": "Deprecated",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-366",
              "name": "RaceConditionWithinAThread",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "If two threads of execution use a resource simultaneously, there exists the possibility that resources may be used while invalid, in turn making the state of execution undefined."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "If two threads of execution use a resource simultaneously, there exists the possibility that resources may be used while invalid, in turn making the state of execution undefined.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIf two threads of execution use a resource simultaneously, there exists the possibility that resources may be used while invalid, in turn making the state of execution undefined.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Alter Execution Logic, Unexpected State.\n  - The main problem is that -- if a lock is overcome -- data could be altered in a bad state.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Use locking functionality. This is the recommended solution. Implement some form of locking mechanism around code which alters or reads persistent data in a multithreaded environment.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Create resource-locking validation checks. If no inherent locking mechanisms exist, use flags and signals to enforce your own blocking scheme when resources are being used by other threads of execution."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/366.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Race Condition within a Thread",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-362"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-367",
              "name": "TimeOfCheckTimeOfUseToctouRaceCondition",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product checks the state of a resource before using that resource, but the resource's state can change between the check and the use in a way that invalidates the results of the check."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product checks the state of a resource before using that resource, but the resource's state can change between the check and the use in a way that invalidates the results of the check.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product checks the state of a resource before using that resource, but the resource's state can change between the check and the use in a way that invalidates the results of the check.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Alter Execution Logic, Unexpected State.\n  - The attacker can gain access to otherwise unauthorized resources.\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Modify Application Data, Modify Files or Directories, Modify Memory, Other.\n  - Race conditions such as this kind may be employed to gain read or write access to resources which are not normally readable or writable by the user in question.\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Other.\n  - The resource in question, or other resources (through the corrupted one), may be changed in undesirable ways by a malicious user.\n- **Scope**: Non-Repudiation. **Impact**: Hide Activities.\n  - If a file or other resource is written in this method, as opposed to in a valid way, logging of the activity may not occur.\n- **Scope**: Non-Repudiation, Other. **Impact**: Other.\n  - In some cases it may be possible to delete files a malicious user might not otherwise have access to, such as log files.\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Unexpected State.\n  - The product may perform invalid actions when the resource is in an unexpected state.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. The most basic advice for TOCTOU vulnerabilities is to not perform a check before the use. This does not resolve the underlying issue of the execution of a function on a resource whose state and identity cannot be assured, but it does help to limit the false sense of security given by the check.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. When the file being altered is owned by the current user and group, set the effective gid and uid to that of the current user and group when executing this statement.\n3. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Limit the interleaving of operations on files from multiple processes.\n4. *Phase: Implementation, Architecture and Design*. If you cannot perform operations atomically and you must share access to the resource between multiple processes or threads, then try to limit the amount of time (CPU cycles) between the check and use of the resource. This will not fix the problem, but it could make it more difficult for an attack to succeed.\n5. *Phase: Implementation*. Recheck the resource after the use call to verify that the action was taken appropriately.\n6. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Ensure that some environmental locking mechanism can be used to protect resources effectively.\n7. *Phase: Implementation*. Ensure that locking occurs before the check, as opposed to afterwards, such that the resource, as checked, is the same as it is when in use."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/367.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Time-of-check Time-of-use (TOCTOU) Race Condition",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-362"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-368",
              "name": "ContextSwitchingRaceCondition",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A product performs a series of non-atomic actions to switch between contexts that cross privilege or other security boundaries, but a race condition allows an attacker to modify or misrepresent the product's behavior during the switch."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "This is commonly seen in web browser vulnerabilities in which the attacker can perform certain actions while the browser is transitioning from a trusted to an untrusted domain, or vice versa, and the browser performs the actions on one domain using the trust level and resources of the other domain."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "A product performs a series of non-atomic actions to switch between contexts that cross privilege or other security boundaries, but a race condition allows an attacker to modify or misrepresent the product's behavior during the switch.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA product performs a series of non-atomic actions to switch between contexts that cross privilege or other security boundaries, but a race condition allows an attacker to modify or misrepresent the product's behavior during the switch.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThis is commonly seen in web browser vulnerabilities in which the attacker can perform certain actions while the browser is transitioning from a trusted to an untrusted domain, or vice versa, and the browser performs the actions on one domain using the trust level and resources of the other domain.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Confidentiality. **Impact**: Modify Application Data, Read Application Data."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/368.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Context Switching Race Condition",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-362"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-369",
              "name": "DivideByZero",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product divides a value by zero."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "This weakness typically occurs when an unexpected value is provided to the product, or if an error occurs that is not properly detected. It frequently occurs in calculations involving physical dimensions such as size, length, width, and height."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product divides a value by zero.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product divides a value by zero.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThis weakness typically occurs when an unexpected value is provided to the product, or if an error occurs that is not properly detected. It frequently occurs in calculations involving physical dimensions such as size, length, width, and height.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart.\n  - A Divide by Zero results in a crash."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/369.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Divide By Zero",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-682"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-370",
              "name": "MissingCheckForCertificateRevocationAfterInitialCheck",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not check the revocation status of a certificate after its initial revocation check, which can cause the product to perform privileged actions even after the certificate is revoked at a later time."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "If the revocation status of a certificate is not checked before each action that requires privileges, the system may be subject to a race condition. If a certificate is revoked after the initial check, all subsequent actions taken with the owner of the revoked certificate will lose all benefits guaranteed by the certificate. In fact, it is almost certain that the use of a revoked certificate indicates malicious activity."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not check the revocation status of a certificate after its initial revocation check, which can cause the product to perform privileged actions even after the certificate is revoked at a later time.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not check the revocation status of a certificate after its initial revocation check, which can cause the product to perform privileged actions even after the certificate is revoked at a later time.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIf the revocation status of a certificate is not checked before each action that requires privileges, the system may be subject to a race condition. If a certificate is revoked after the initial check, all subsequent actions taken with the owner of the revoked certificate will lose all benefits guaranteed by the certificate. In fact, it is almost certain that the use of a revoked certificate indicates malicious activity.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n  - Trust may be assigned to an entity who is not who it claims to be.\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Modify Application Data.\n  - Data from an untrusted (and possibly malicious) source may be integrated.\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - Data may be disclosed to an entity impersonating a trusted entity, resulting in information disclosure.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Ensure that certificates are checked for revoked status before each use of a protected resource. If the certificate is checked before each access of a protected resource, the delay subject to a possible race condition becomes almost negligible and significantly reduces the risk associated with this issue."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/370.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Missing Check for Certificate Revocation after Initial Check",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-299"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-372",
              "name": "IncompleteInternalStateDistinction",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not properly determine which state it is in, causing it to assume it is in state X when in fact it is in state Y, causing it to perform incorrect operations in a security-relevant manner."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not properly determine which state it is in, causing it to assume it is in state X when in fact it is in state Y, causing it to perform incorrect operations in a security-relevant manner.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not properly determine which state it is in, causing it to assume it is in state X when in fact it is in state Y, causing it to perform incorrect operations in a security-relevant manner.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Varies by Context, Unexpected State."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/372.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Incomplete Internal State Distinction",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-664"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-373",
              "name": "DeprecatedStateSynchronizationError",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "This entry was deprecated because it overlapped the same concepts as race condition (CWE-362) and Improper Synchronization (CWE-662)."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "This entry was deprecated because it overlapped the same concepts as race condition (CWE-362) and Improper Synchronization (CWE-662).",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis entry was deprecated because it overlapped the same concepts as race condition (CWE-362) and Improper Synchronization (CWE-662)."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/373.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "DEPRECATED: State Synchronization Error",
                "cwe/status": "Deprecated",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-374",
              "name": "PassingMutableObjectsToAnUntrustedMethod",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product sends non-cloned mutable data as an argument to a method or function."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The function or method that has been called can alter or delete the mutable data. This could violate assumptions that the calling function has made about its state. In situations where unknown code is called with references to mutable data, this external code could make changes to the data sent. If this data was not previously cloned, the modified data might not be valid in the context of execution."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product sends non-cloned mutable data as an argument to a method or function.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product sends non-cloned mutable data as an argument to a method or function.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThe function or method that has been called can alter or delete the mutable data. This could violate assumptions that the calling function has made about its state. In situations where unknown code is called with references to mutable data, this external code could make changes to the data sent. If this data was not previously cloned, the modified data might not be valid in the context of execution.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Modify Memory.\n  - Potentially data could be tampered with by another function which should not have been tampered with.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Pass in data which should not be altered as constant or immutable.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Clone all mutable data before passing it into an external function . This is the preferred mitigation. This way, regardless of what changes are made to the data, a valid copy is retained for use by the class."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/374.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Passing Mutable Objects to an Untrusted Method",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-668"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-375",
              "name": "ReturningAMutableObjectToAnUntrustedCaller",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Sending non-cloned mutable data as a return value may result in that data being altered or deleted by the calling function."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In situations where functions return references to mutable data, it is possible that the external code which called the function may make changes to the data sent. If this data was not previously cloned, the class will then be using modified data which may violate assumptions about its internal state."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Sending non-cloned mutable data as a return value may result in that data being altered or deleted by the calling function.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSending non-cloned mutable data as a return value may result in that data being altered or deleted by the calling function.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIn situations where functions return references to mutable data, it is possible that the external code which called the function may make changes to the data sent. If this data was not previously cloned, the class will then be using modified data which may violate assumptions about its internal state.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control, Integrity. **Impact**: Modify Memory.\n  - Potentially data could be tampered with by another function which should not have been tampered with.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Declare returned data which should not be altered as constant or immutable.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Clone all mutable data before returning references to it. This is the preferred mitigation. This way, regardless of what changes are made to the data, a valid copy is retained for use by the class."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/375.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Returning a Mutable Object to an Untrusted Caller",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-668"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-377",
              "name": "InsecureTemporaryFile",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Creating and using insecure temporary files can leave application and system data vulnerable to attack."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Creating and using insecure temporary files can leave application and system data vulnerable to attack.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCreating and using insecure temporary files can leave application and system data vulnerable to attack.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity. **Impact**: Read Files or Directories, Modify Files or Directories."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Insecure Temporary File",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-668"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-378",
              "name": "CreationOfTemporaryFileWithInsecurePermissions",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Opening temporary files without appropriate measures or controls can leave the file, its contents and any function that it impacts vulnerable to attack."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Opening temporary files without appropriate measures or controls can leave the file, its contents and any function that it impacts vulnerable to attack.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nOpening temporary files without appropriate measures or controls can leave the file, its contents and any function that it impacts vulnerable to attack.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - If the temporary file can be read by the attacker, sensitive information may be in that file which could be revealed.\n- **Scope**: Authorization, Other. **Impact**: Other.\n  - If that file can be written to by the attacker, the file might be moved into a place to which the attacker does not have access. This will allow the attacker to gain selective resource access-control privileges.\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Other.\n  - Depending on the data stored in the temporary file, there is the potential for an attacker to gain an additional input vector which is trusted as non-malicious. It may be possible to make arbitrary changes to data structures, user information, or even process ownership.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Requirements*. Many contemporary languages have functions which properly handle this condition. Older C temp file functions are especially susceptible.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Ensure that you use proper file permissions. This can be achieved by using a safe temp file function. Temporary files should be writable and readable only by the process that owns the file.\n3. *Phase: Implementation*. Randomize temporary file names. This can also be achieved by using a safe temp-file function. This will ensure that temporary files will not be created in predictable places."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Creation of Temporary File With Insecure Permissions",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-377"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-379",
              "name": "CreationOfTemporaryFileInDirectoryWithInsecurePermissions",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product creates a temporary file in a directory whose permissions allow unintended actors to determine the file's existence or otherwise access that file."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "On some operating systems, the fact that the temporary file exists may be apparent to any user with sufficient privileges to access that directory. Since the file is visible, the application that is using the temporary file could be known. If one has access to list the processes on the system, the attacker has gained information about what the user is doing at that time. By correlating this with the applications the user is running, an attacker could potentially discover what a user's actions are. From this, higher levels of security could be breached."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product creates a temporary file in a directory whose permissions allow unintended actors to determine the file's existence or otherwise access that file.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product creates a temporary file in a directory whose permissions allow unintended actors to determine the file's existence or otherwise access that file.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nOn some operating systems, the fact that the temporary file exists may be apparent to any user with sufficient privileges to access that directory. Since the file is visible, the application that is using the temporary file could be known. If one has access to list the processes on the system, the attacker has gained information about what the user is doing at that time. By correlating this with the applications the user is running, an attacker could potentially discover what a user's actions are. From this, higher levels of security could be breached.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - Since the file is visible and the application which is using the temp file could be known, the attacker has gained information about what the user is doing at that time.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Requirements*. Many contemporary languages have functions which properly handle this condition. Older C temp file functions are especially susceptible.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Try to store sensitive tempfiles in a directory which is not world readable -- i.e., per-user directories.\n3. *Phase: Implementation*. Avoid using vulnerable temp file functions."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Creation of Temporary File in Directory with Insecure Permissions",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-377"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-382",
              "name": "J2eeBadPracticesUseOfSystemExit",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A J2EE application uses System.exit(), which also shuts down its container."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "It is never a good idea for a web application to attempt to shut down the application container. Access to a function that can shut down the application is an avenue for Denial of Service (DoS) attacks."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "A J2EE application uses System.exit(), which also shuts down its container.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA J2EE application uses System.exit(), which also shuts down its container.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIt is never a good idea for a web application to attempt to shut down the application container. Access to a function that can shut down the application is an avenue for Denial of Service (DoS) attacks.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design; Strategy: Separation of Privilege*. The shutdown function should be a privileged function available only to a properly authorized administrative user\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Web applications should not call methods that cause the virtual machine to exit, such as System.exit()\n3. *Phase: Implementation*. Web applications should also not throw any Throwables to the application server as this may adversely affect the container.\n4. *Phase: Implementation*. Non-web applications may have a main() method that contains a System.exit(), but generally should not call System.exit() from other locations in the code"
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/382.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "J2EE Bad Practices: Use of System.exit()",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-705"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-383",
              "name": "J2eeBadPracticesDirectUseOfThreads",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Thread management in a Web application is forbidden in some circumstances and is always highly error prone."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Thread management in a web application is forbidden by the J2EE standard in some circumstances and is always highly error prone. Managing threads is difficult and is likely to interfere in unpredictable ways with the behavior of the application container. Even without interfering with the container, thread management usually leads to bugs that are hard to detect and diagnose like deadlock, race conditions, and other synchronization errors."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Thread management in a Web application is forbidden in some circumstances and is always highly error prone.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThread management in a Web application is forbidden in some circumstances and is always highly error prone.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThread management in a web application is forbidden by the J2EE standard in some circumstances and is always highly error prone. Managing threads is difficult and is likely to interfere in unpredictable ways with the behavior of the application container. Even without interfering with the container, thread management usually leads to bugs that are hard to detect and diagnose like deadlock, race conditions, and other synchronization errors.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. For EJB, use framework approaches for parallel execution, instead of using threads."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/383.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "J2EE Bad Practices: Direct Use of Threads",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-695"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-384",
              "name": "SessionFixation",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Authenticating a user, or otherwise establishing a new user session, without invalidating any existing session identifier gives an attacker the opportunity to steal authenticated sessions."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Such a scenario is commonly observed when: A web application authenticates a user without first invalidating the existing session, thereby continuing to use the session already associated with the user. An attacker is able to force a known session identifier on a user so that, once the user authenticates, the attacker has access to the authenticated session. The application or container uses predictable session identifiers. In the generic exploit of session fixation vulnerabilities, an attacker creates a new session on a web application and records the associated session identifier. The attacker then causes the victim to associate, and possibly authenticate, against the server using that session identifier, giving the attacker access to the user's account through the active session."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Authenticating a user, or otherwise establishing a new user session, without invalidating any existing session identifier gives an attacker the opportunity to steal authenticated sessions.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nAuthenticating a user, or otherwise establishing a new user session, without invalidating any existing session identifier gives an attacker the opportunity to steal authenticated sessions.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nSuch a scenario is commonly observed when: A web application authenticates a user without first invalidating the existing session, thereby continuing to use the session already associated with the user. An attacker is able to force a known session identifier on a user so that, once the user authenticates, the attacker has access to the authenticated session. The application or container uses predictable session identifiers. In the generic exploit of session fixation vulnerabilities, an attacker creates a new session on a web application and records the associated session identifier. The attacker then causes the victim to associate, and possibly authenticate, against the server using that session identifier, giving the attacker access to the user's account through the active session.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Invalidate any existing session identifiers prior to authorizing a new user session.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. For platforms such as ASP that do not generate new values for sessionid cookies, utilize a secondary cookie. In this approach, set a secondary cookie on the user's browser to a random value and set a session variable to the same value. If the session variable and the cookie value ever don't match, invalidate the session, and force the user to log on again.\n3. *Phase: Operation; Strategy: Firewall*. Use an application firewall that can detect attacks against this weakness. It can be beneficial in cases in which the code cannot be fixed (because it is controlled by a third party), as an emergency prevention measure while more comprehensive software assurance measures are applied, or to provide defense in depth [REF-1481]."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/384.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Session Fixation",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Compound",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-610"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-385",
              "name": "CovertTimingChannel",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Covert timing channels convey information by modulating some aspect of system behavior over time, so that the program receiving the information can observe system behavior and infer protected information."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In some instances, knowing when data is transmitted between parties can provide a malicious user with privileged information. Also, externally monitoring the timing of operations can potentially reveal sensitive data. For example, a cryptographic operation can expose its internal state if the time it takes to perform the operation varies, based on the state. Covert channels are frequently classified as either storage or timing channels. Some examples of covert timing channels are the system's paging rate, the time a certain transaction requires to execute, and the time it takes to gain access to a shared bus."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Covert timing channels convey information by modulating some aspect of system behavior over time, so that the program receiving the information can observe system behavior and infer protected information.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCovert timing channels convey information by modulating some aspect of system behavior over time, so that the program receiving the information can observe system behavior and infer protected information.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIn some instances, knowing when data is transmitted between parties can provide a malicious user with privileged information. Also, externally monitoring the timing of operations can potentially reveal sensitive data. For example, a cryptographic operation can expose its internal state if the time it takes to perform the operation varies, based on the state. Covert channels are frequently classified as either storage or timing channels. Some examples of covert timing channels are the system's paging rate, the time a certain transaction requires to execute, and the time it takes to gain access to a shared bus.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Other. **Impact**: Read Application Data, Other.\n  - Information exposure.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Whenever possible, specify implementation strategies that do not introduce time variances in operations.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Often one can artificially manipulate the time which operations take or -- when operations occur -- can remove information from the attacker.\n3. *Phase: Implementation*. It is reasonable to add artificial or random delays so that the amount of CPU time consumed is independent of the action being taken by the application."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/385.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Covert Timing Channel",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-514"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-386",
              "name": "SymbolicNameNotMappingToCorrectObject",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A constant symbolic reference to an object is used, even though the reference can resolve to a different object over time."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "A constant symbolic reference to an object is used, even though the reference can resolve to a different object over time.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA constant symbolic reference to an object is used, even though the reference can resolve to a different object over time.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n  - The attacker can gain access to otherwise unauthorized resources.\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Confidentiality, Other. **Impact**: Modify Application Data, Modify Files or Directories, Read Application Data, Read Files or Directories, Other.\n  - Race conditions such as this kind may be employed to gain read or write access to resources not normally readable or writable by the user in question.\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Modify Application Data, Other.\n  - The resource in question, or other resources (through the corrupted one) may be changed in undesirable ways by a malicious user.\n- **Scope**: Non-Repudiation. **Impact**: Hide Activities.\n  - If a file or other resource is written in this method, as opposed to a valid way, logging of the activity may not occur.\n- **Scope**: Non-Repudiation, Integrity. **Impact**: Modify Files or Directories.\n  - In some cases it may be possible to delete files that a malicious user might not otherwise have access to -- such as log files."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/386.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Symbolic Name not Mapping to Correct Object",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-706"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-390",
              "name": "DetectionOfErrorConditionWithoutAction",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product detects a specific error, but takes no actions to handle the error."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product detects a specific error, but takes no actions to handle the error.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product detects a specific error, but takes no actions to handle the error.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Varies by Context, Unexpected State, Alter Execution Logic.\n  - An attacker could utilize an ignored error condition to place the system in an unexpected state that could lead to the execution of unintended logic and could cause other unintended behavior.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Properly handle each exception. This is the recommended solution. Ensure that all exceptions are handled in such a way that you can be sure of the state of your system at any given moment.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. If a function returns an error, it is important to either fix the problem and try again, alert the user that an error has happened and let the program continue, or alert the user and close and cleanup the program.\n3. *Phase: Testing*. Subject the product to extensive testing to discover some of the possible instances of where/how errors or return values are not handled. Consider testing techniques such as ad hoc, equivalence partitioning, robustness and fault tolerance, mutation, and fuzzing."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/390.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Detection of Error Condition Without Action",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-755"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-391",
              "name": "UncheckedErrorCondition",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "[PLANNED FOR DEPRECATION."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "[PLANNED FOR DEPRECATION. SEE MAINTENANCE NOTES AND CONSIDER CWE-252, CWE-248, OR CWE-1069.] Ignoring exceptions and other error conditions may allow an attacker to induce unexpected behavior unnoticed.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n[PLANNED FOR DEPRECATION. SEE MAINTENANCE NOTES AND CONSIDER CWE-252, CWE-248, OR CWE-1069.] Ignoring exceptions and other error conditions may allow an attacker to induce unexpected behavior unnoticed.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Varies by Context, Unexpected State, Alter Execution Logic.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Requirements*. The choice between a language which has named or unnamed exceptions needs to be done. While unnamed exceptions exacerbate the chance of not properly dealing with an exception, named exceptions suffer from the up call version of the weak base class problem.\n2. *Phase: Requirements*. A language can be used which requires, at compile time, to catch all serious exceptions. However, one must make sure to use the most current version of the API as new exceptions could be added.\n3. *Phase: Implementation*. Catch all relevant exceptions. This is the recommended solution. Ensure that all exceptions are handled in such a way that you can be sure of the state of your system at any given moment."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/391.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Unchecked Error Condition",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-754"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-392",
              "name": "MissingReportOfErrorCondition",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product encounters an error but does not provide a status code or return value to indicate that an error has occurred."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product encounters an error but does not provide a status code or return value to indicate that an error has occurred.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product encounters an error but does not provide a status code or return value to indicate that an error has occurred.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Varies by Context, Unexpected State.\n  - Errors that are not properly reported could place the system in an unexpected state that could lead to unintended behaviors."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/392.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Missing Report of Error Condition",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-755"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-393",
              "name": "ReturnOfWrongStatusCode",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A function or operation returns an incorrect return value or status code that does not indicate the true result of execution, causing the product to modify its behavior based on the incorrect result."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "This can lead to unpredictable behavior. If the function is used to make security-critical decisions or provide security-critical information, then the wrong status code can cause the product to assume that an action is safe or correct, even when it is not."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "A function or operation returns an incorrect return value or status code that does not indicate the true result of execution, causing the product to modify its behavior based on the incorrect result.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA function or operation returns an incorrect return value or status code that does not indicate the true result of execution, causing the product to modify its behavior based on the incorrect result.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThis can lead to unpredictable behavior. If the function is used to make security-critical decisions or provide security-critical information, then the wrong status code can cause the product to assume that an action is safe or correct, even when it is not.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Unexpected State, Alter Execution Logic.\n  - This weakness could place the system in a state that could lead unexpected logic to be executed or other unintended behaviors."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/393.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Return of Wrong Status Code",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-684"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-394",
              "name": "UnexpectedStatusCodeOrReturnValue",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not properly check when a function or operation returns a value that is legitimate for the function, but is not expected by the product."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not properly check when a function or operation returns a value that is legitimate for the function, but is not expected by the product.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not properly check when a function or operation returns a value that is legitimate for the function, but is not expected by the product.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Unexpected State, Alter Execution Logic."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/394.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Unexpected Status Code or Return Value",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-754"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-395",
              "name": "UseOfNullpointerexceptionCatchToDetectNullPointerDereference",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Catching NullPointerException should not be used as an alternative to programmatic checks to prevent dereferencing a null pointer."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Programmers typically catch NullPointerException under three circumstances: The program contains a null pointer dereference. Catching the resulting exception was easier than fixing the underlying problem. The program explicitly throws a NullPointerException to signal an error condition. The code is part of a test harness that supplies unexpected input to the classes under test. Of these three circumstances, only the last is acceptable."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Catching NullPointerException should not be used as an alternative to programmatic checks to prevent dereferencing a null pointer.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCatching NullPointerException should not be used as an alternative to programmatic checks to prevent dereferencing a null pointer.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nProgrammers typically catch NullPointerException under three circumstances: The program contains a null pointer dereference. Catching the resulting exception was easier than fixing the underlying problem. The program explicitly throws a NullPointerException to signal an error condition. The code is part of a test harness that supplies unexpected input to the classes under test. Of these three circumstances, only the last is acceptable.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Resource Consumption (CPU).\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Implementation*. Do not extensively rely on catching exceptions (especially for validating user input) to handle errors. Handling exceptions can decrease the performance of an application."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/395.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Use of NullPointerException Catch to Detect NULL Pointer Dereference",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-705"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-396",
              "name": "DeclarationOfCatchForGenericException",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Catching overly broad exceptions promotes complex error handling code that is more likely to contain security vulnerabilities."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Multiple catch blocks can get ugly and repetitive, but \"condensing\" catch blocks by catching a high-level class like Exception can obscure exceptions that deserve special treatment or that should not be caught at this point in the program. Catching an overly broad exception essentially defeats the purpose of a language's typed exceptions, and can become particularly dangerous if the program grows and begins to throw new types of exceptions. The new exception types will not receive any attention."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Catching overly broad exceptions promotes complex error handling code that is more likely to contain security vulnerabilities.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCatching overly broad exceptions promotes complex error handling code that is more likely to contain security vulnerabilities.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nMultiple catch blocks can get ugly and repetitive, but \"condensing\" catch blocks by catching a high-level class like Exception can obscure exceptions that deserve special treatment or that should not be caught at this point in the program. Catching an overly broad exception essentially defeats the purpose of a language's typed exceptions, and can become particularly dangerous if the program grows and begins to throw new types of exceptions. The new exception types will not receive any attention.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Non-Repudiation, Other. **Impact**: Hide Activities.\n  - A generic exception can hide details about unexpected adversary activities by making it difficult to properly troubleshoot error conditions during execution."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/396.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Declaration of Catch for Generic Exception",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-705"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-397",
              "name": "DeclarationOfThrowsForGenericException",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product throws or raises an overly broad exceptions that can hide important details and produce inappropriate responses to certain conditions."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Declaring a method to throw Exception or Throwable promotes generic error handling procedures that make it difficult for callers to perform proper error handling and error recovery. For example, Java's exception mechanism makes it easy for callers to anticipate what can go wrong and write code to handle each specific exceptional circumstance. Declaring that a method throws a generic form of exception defeats this system."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product throws or raises an overly broad exceptions that can hide important details and produce inappropriate responses to certain conditions.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product throws or raises an overly broad exceptions that can hide important details and produce inappropriate responses to certain conditions.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nDeclaring a method to throw Exception or Throwable promotes generic error handling procedures that make it difficult for callers to perform proper error handling and error recovery. For example, Java's exception mechanism makes it easy for callers to anticipate what can go wrong and write code to handle each specific exceptional circumstance. Declaring that a method throws a generic form of exception defeats this system.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Non-Repudiation, Other. **Impact**: Hide Activities, Alter Execution Logic.\n  - Throwing a generic exception can hide details about unexpected adversary activities by making it difficult to properly troubleshoot error conditions during execution."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/397.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Declaration of Throws for Generic Exception",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-705"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-400",
              "name": "UncontrolledResourceConsumption",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not properly control the allocation and maintenance of a limited resource."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not properly control the allocation and maintenance of a limited resource.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not properly control the allocation and maintenance of a limited resource.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart, DoS: Resource Consumption (CPU), DoS: Resource Consumption (Memory), DoS: Resource Consumption (Other).\n  - If an attacker can trigger the allocation of the limited resources, but the number or size of the resources is not controlled, then the most common result is denial of service. This would prevent valid users from accessing the product, and it could potentially have an impact on the surrounding environment, i.e., the product may slow down, crash due to unhandled errors, or lock out legitimate users. For example, a memory exhaustion attack against an application could slow down the application as well as its host operating system.\n- **Scope**: Access Control, Other. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism, Other.\n  - In some cases it may be possible to force the product to \"fail open\" in the event of resource exhaustion. The state of the product -- and possibly the security functionality - may then be compromised.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Design throttling mechanisms into the system architecture. The best protection is to limit the amount of resources that an unauthorized user can cause to be expended. A strong authentication and access control model will help prevent such attacks from occurring in the first place. The login application should be protected against DoS attacks as much as possible. Limiting the database access, perhaps by caching result sets, can help minimize the resources expended. To further limit the potential for a DoS attack, consider tracking the rate of requests received from users and blocking requests that exceed a defined rate threshold.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Mitigation of resource exhaustion attacks requires that the target system either: recognizes the attack and denies that user further access for a given amount of time, or uniformly throttles all requests in order to make it more difficult to consume resources more quickly than they can again be freed. The first of these solutions is an issue in itself though, since it may allow attackers to prevent the use of the system by a particular valid user. If the attacker impersonates the valid user, they may be able to prevent the user from accessing the server in question. The second solution is simply difficult to effectively institute -- and even when properly done, it does not provide a full solution. It simply makes the attack require more resources on the part of the attacker.\n3. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Ensure that protocols have specific limits of scale placed on them.\n4. *Phase: Implementation*. Ensure that all failures in resource allocation place the system into a safe posture."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Uncontrolled Resource Consumption",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-664"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-401",
              "name": "MissingReleaseOfMemoryAfterEffectiveLifetime",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not sufficiently track and release allocated memory after it has been used, making the memory unavailable for reallocation and reuse."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not sufficiently track and release allocated memory after it has been used, making the memory unavailable for reallocation and reuse.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not sufficiently track and release allocated memory after it has been used, making the memory unavailable for reallocation and reuse.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart, DoS: Instability, DoS: Resource Consumption (CPU), DoS: Resource Consumption (Memory).\n  - Most memory leaks result in general product reliability problems, but if an attacker can intentionally trigger a memory leak, the attacker might be able to launch a denial of service attack (by crashing or hanging the program) or take advantage of other unexpected program behavior resulting from a low memory condition.\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Reduce Performance.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation; Strategy: Libraries or Frameworks*. Choose a language or tool that provides automatic memory management, or makes manual memory management less error-prone. For example, glibc in Linux provides protection against free of invalid pointers. When using Xcode to target OS X or iOS, enable automatic reference counting (ARC) [REF-391]. To help correctly and consistently manage memory when programming in C++, consider using a smart pointer class such as std::auto_ptr (defined by ISO/IEC ISO/IEC 14882:2003), std::shared_ptr and std::unique_ptr (specified by an upcoming revision of the C++ standard, informally referred to as C++ 1x), or equivalent solutions such as Boost.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Use an abstraction library to abstract away risky APIs. Not a complete solution.\n3. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Build and Compilation*. Consider using the Boehm-Demers-Weiser garbage collector (bdwgc), which can help avoid leaks."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/401.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Missing Release of Memory after Effective Lifetime",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-772"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-402",
              "name": "ResourceLeak",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product makes resources available to untrusted parties when those resources are only intended to be accessed by the product."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product makes resources available to untrusted parties when those resources are only intended to be accessed by the product.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product makes resources available to untrusted parties when those resources are only intended to be accessed by the product.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/402.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Transmission of Private Resources into a New Sphere ('Resource Leak')",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-668"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-403",
              "name": "FileDescriptorLeak",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A process does not close sensitive file descriptors before invoking a child process, which allows the child to perform unauthorized I/O operations using those descriptors."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "When a new process is forked or executed, the child process inherits any open file descriptors. When the child process has fewer privileges than the parent process, this might introduce a vulnerability if the child process can access the file descriptor but does not have the privileges to access the associated file."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "A process does not close sensitive file descriptors before invoking a child process, which allows the child to perform unauthorized I/O operations using those descriptors.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA process does not close sensitive file descriptors before invoking a child process, which allows the child to perform unauthorized I/O operations using those descriptors.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nWhen a new process is forked or executed, the child process inherits any open file descriptors. When the child process has fewer privileges than the parent process, this might introduce a vulnerability if the child process can access the file descriptor but does not have the privileges to access the associated file.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity. **Impact**: Read Application Data, Modify Application Data."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/403.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Exposure of File Descriptor to Unintended Control Sphere ('File Descriptor Leak')",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-402"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-404",
              "name": "ImproperResourceShutdownOrRelease",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not release or incorrectly releases a resource before it is made available for re-use."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "When a resource is created or allocated, the developer is responsible for properly releasing the resource as well as accounting for all potential paths of expiration or invalidation, such as a set period of time or revocation."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not release or incorrectly releases a resource before it is made available for re-use.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not release or incorrectly releases a resource before it is made available for re-use.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nWhen a resource is created or allocated, the developer is responsible for properly releasing the resource as well as accounting for all potential paths of expiration or invalidation, such as a set period of time or revocation.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Availability, Other. **Impact**: DoS: Resource Consumption (Other), Varies by Context.\n  - Most unreleased resource issues result in general software reliability problems, but if an attacker can intentionally trigger a resource leak, the attacker might be able to launch a denial of service attack by depleting the resource pool.\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - When a resource containing sensitive information is not correctly shutdown, it may expose the sensitive data in a subsequent allocation.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Requirements; Strategy: Language Selection*. Use a language that does not allow this weakness to occur or provides constructs that make this weakness easier to avoid. For example, languages such as Java, Ruby, and Lisp perform automatic garbage collection that releases memory for objects that have been deallocated.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. It is good practice to be responsible for freeing all resources you allocate and to be consistent with how and where you free memory in a function. If you allocate memory that you intend to free upon completion of the function, you must be sure to free the memory at all exit points for that function including error conditions.\n3. *Phase: Implementation*. Memory should be allocated/freed using matching functions such as malloc/free, new/delete, and new[]/delete[].\n4. *Phase: Implementation*. When releasing a complex object or structure, ensure that you properly dispose of all of its member components, not just the object itself."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/404.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Improper Resource Shutdown or Release",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-664"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-405",
              "name": "AsymmetricResourceConsumptionAmplification",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not properly control situations in which an adversary can cause the product to consume or produce excessive resources without requiring the adversary to invest equivalent work or otherwise prove authorization, i.e., the adversary's influence is \"asymmetric.\""
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "This can lead to poor performance due to \"amplification\" of resource consumption, typically in a non-linear fashion. This situation is worsened if the product allows malicious users or attackers to consume more resources than their access level permits."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not properly control situations in which an adversary can cause the product to consume or produce excessive resources without requiring the adversary to invest equivalent work or otherwise prove authorization, i.e., the adversary's influence is \"asymmetric.\"",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not properly control situations in which an adversary can cause the product to consume or produce excessive resources without requiring the adversary to invest equivalent work or otherwise prove authorization, i.e., the adversary's influence is \"asymmetric.\"\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThis can lead to poor performance due to \"amplification\" of resource consumption, typically in a non-linear fashion. This situation is worsened if the product allows malicious users or attackers to consume more resources than their access level permits.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Amplification, DoS: Resource Consumption (CPU), DoS: Resource Consumption (Memory), DoS: Resource Consumption (Other).\n  - Sometimes this is a factor in \"flood\" attacks, but other types of amplification exist.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. An application must make resources available to a client commensurate with the client's access level.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. An application must, at all times, keep track of allocated resources and meter their usage appropriately.\n3. *Phase: System Configuration*. Consider disabling resource-intensive algorithms on the server side, such as Diffie-Hellman key exchange."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/405.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Asymmetric Resource Consumption (Amplification)",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-400"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-406",
              "name": "InsufficientControlOfNetworkMessageVolumeNetworkAmplification",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not sufficiently monitor or control transmitted network traffic volume, so that an actor can cause the product to transmit more traffic than should be allowed for that actor."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In the absence of a policy to restrict asymmetric resource consumption, the application or system cannot distinguish between legitimate transmissions and traffic intended to serve as an amplifying attack on target systems. Systems can often be configured to restrict the amount of traffic sent out on behalf of a client, based on the client's origin or access level. This is usually defined in a resource allocation policy. In the absence of a mechanism to keep track of transmissions, the system or application can be easily abused to transmit asymmetrically greater traffic than the request or client should be permitted to."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not sufficiently monitor or control transmitted network traffic volume, so that an actor can cause the product to transmit more traffic than should be allowed for that actor.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not sufficiently monitor or control transmitted network traffic volume, so that an actor can cause the product to transmit more traffic than should be allowed for that actor.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIn the absence of a policy to restrict asymmetric resource consumption, the application or system cannot distinguish between legitimate transmissions and traffic intended to serve as an amplifying attack on target systems. Systems can often be configured to restrict the amount of traffic sent out on behalf of a client, based on the client's origin or access level. This is usually defined in a resource allocation policy. In the absence of a mechanism to keep track of transmissions, the system or application can be easily abused to transmit asymmetrically greater traffic than the request or client should be permitted to.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Amplification, DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart, DoS: Resource Consumption (CPU), DoS: Resource Consumption (Memory), DoS: Resource Consumption (Other).\n  - System resources can be quickly consumed leading to poor application performance or system crash. This may affect network performance and could be used to attack other systems and applications relying on network performance.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design; Strategy: Separation of Privilege*. An application must make network resources available to a client commensurate with the client's access level.\n2. *Phase: Policy*. Define a clear policy for network resource allocation and consumption.\n3. *Phase: Implementation*. An application must, at all times, keep track of network resources and meter their usage appropriately."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/406.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Insufficient Control of Network Message Volume (Network Amplification)",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-405"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-407",
              "name": "InefficientAlgorithmicComplexity",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "An algorithm in a product has an inefficient worst-case computational complexity that may be detrimental to system performance and can be triggered by an attacker, typically using crafted manipulations that ensure that the worst case is being reached."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "An algorithm in a product has an inefficient worst-case computational complexity that may be detrimental to system performance and can be triggered by an attacker, typically using crafted manipulations that ensure that the worst case is being reached.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nAn algorithm in a product has an inefficient worst-case computational complexity that may be detrimental to system performance and can be triggered by an attacker, typically using crafted manipulations that ensure that the worst case is being reached.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Resource Consumption (CPU), DoS: Resource Consumption (Memory), DoS: Resource Consumption (Other).\n  - The typical consequence is CPU consumption, but memory consumption and consumption of other resources can also occur."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/407.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Inefficient Algorithmic Complexity",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-405"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-408",
              "name": "IncorrectBehaviorOrderEarlyAmplification",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product allows an entity to perform a legitimate but expensive operation before authentication or authorization has taken place."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product allows an entity to perform a legitimate but expensive operation before authentication or authorization has taken place.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product allows an entity to perform a legitimate but expensive operation before authentication or authorization has taken place.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Amplification, DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart, DoS: Resource Consumption (CPU), DoS: Resource Consumption (Memory).\n  - System resources, CPU and memory, can be quickly consumed. This can lead to poor system performance or system crash."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/408.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Incorrect Behavior Order: Early Amplification",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-696"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-409",
              "name": "ImproperHandlingOfHighlyCompressedDataDataAmplification",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not handle or incorrectly handles a compressed input with a very high compression ratio that produces a large output."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "An example of data amplification is a \"decompression bomb,\" a small ZIP file that can produce a large amount of data when it is decompressed."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not handle or incorrectly handles a compressed input with a very high compression ratio that produces a large output.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not handle or incorrectly handles a compressed input with a very high compression ratio that produces a large output.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nAn example of data amplification is a \"decompression bomb,\" a small ZIP file that can produce a large amount of data when it is decompressed.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Amplification, DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart, DoS: Resource Consumption (CPU), DoS: Resource Consumption (Memory).\n  - System resources, CPU and memory, can be quickly consumed. This can lead to poor system performance or system crash."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/409.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Improper Handling of Highly Compressed Data (Data Amplification)",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-405"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-410",
              "name": "InsufficientResourcePool",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product's resource pool is not large enough to handle peak demand, which allows an attacker to prevent others from accessing the resource by using a (relatively) large number of requests for resources."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Frequently the consequence is a \"flood\" of connection or sessions."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product's resource pool is not large enough to handle peak demand, which allows an attacker to prevent others from accessing the resource by using a (relatively) large number of requests for resources.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product's resource pool is not large enough to handle peak demand, which allows an attacker to prevent others from accessing the resource by using a (relatively) large number of requests for resources.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nFrequently the consequence is a \"flood\" of connection or sessions.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Availability, Integrity, Other. **Impact**: DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart, Other.\n  - Floods often cause a crash or other problem besides denial of the resource itself; these are likely examples of *other* vulnerabilities, not an insufficient resource pool.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Do not perform resource-intensive transactions for unauthenticated users and/or invalid requests.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Consider implementing a velocity check mechanism which would detect abusive behavior.\n3. *Phase: Operation*. Consider load balancing as an option to handle heavy loads.\n4. *Phase: Implementation*. Make sure that resource handles are properly closed when no longer needed.\n5. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Identify the system's resource intensive operations and consider protecting them from abuse (e.g. malicious automated script which runs the resources out)."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/410.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Insufficient Resource Pool",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-664"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-412",
              "name": "UnrestrictedExternallyAccessibleLock",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product properly checks for the existence of a lock, but the lock can be externally controlled or influenced by an actor that is outside of the intended sphere of control."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "This prevents the product from acting on associated resources or performing other behaviors that are controlled by the presence of the lock. Relevant locks might include an exclusive lock or mutex, or modifying a shared resource that is treated as a lock. If the lock can be held for an indefinite period of time, then the denial of service could be permanent."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product properly checks for the existence of a lock, but the lock can be externally controlled or influenced by an actor that is outside of the intended sphere of control.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product properly checks for the existence of a lock, but the lock can be externally controlled or influenced by an actor that is outside of the intended sphere of control.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThis prevents the product from acting on associated resources or performing other behaviors that are controlled by the presence of the lock. Relevant locks might include an exclusive lock or mutex, or modifying a shared resource that is treated as a lock. If the lock can be held for an indefinite period of time, then the denial of service could be permanent.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Resource Consumption (Other).\n  - When an attacker can control a lock, the program may wait indefinitely until the attacker releases the lock, causing a denial of service to other users of the program. This is especially problematic if there is a blocking operation on the lock.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Implementation*. Use any access control that is offered by the functionality that is offering the lock.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Implementation*. Use unpredictable names or identifiers for the locks. This might not always be possible or feasible.\n3. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Consider modifying your code to use non-blocking synchronization methods."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/412.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Unrestricted Externally Accessible Lock",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-667"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-413",
              "name": "ImproperResourceLocking",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not lock or does not correctly lock a resource when the product must have exclusive access to the resource."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "When a resource is not properly locked, an attacker could modify the resource while it is being operated on by the product. This might violate the product's assumption that the resource will not change, potentially leading to unexpected behaviors."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not lock or does not correctly lock a resource when the product must have exclusive access to the resource.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not lock or does not correctly lock a resource when the product must have exclusive access to the resource.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nWhen a resource is not properly locked, an attacker could modify the resource while it is being operated on by the product. This might violate the product's assumption that the resource will not change, potentially leading to unexpected behaviors.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Availability. **Impact**: Modify Application Data, DoS: Instability, DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Use a non-conflicting privilege scheme.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Implementation*. Use synchronization when locking a resource."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/413.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Improper Resource Locking",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-667"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-414",
              "name": "MissingLockCheck",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A product does not check to see if a lock is present before performing sensitive operations on a resource."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "A product does not check to see if a lock is present before performing sensitive operations on a resource.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA product does not check to see if a lock is present before performing sensitive operations on a resource.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Availability. **Impact**: Modify Application Data, DoS: Instability, DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Implementation*. Implement a reliable lock mechanism."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/414.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Missing Lock Check",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-667"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-415",
              "name": "DoubleFree",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product calls free() twice on the same memory address."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product calls free() twice on the same memory address.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product calls free() twice on the same memory address.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Confidentiality, Availability. **Impact**: Modify Memory, Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands.\n  - When a program calls free() twice with the same argument, the program's memory management data structures may become corrupted, potentially leading to the reading or modification of unexpected memory addresses. This corruption can cause the program to crash or, in some circumstances, cause two later calls to malloc() to return the same pointer. If malloc() returns the same value twice and the program later gives the attacker control over the data that is written into this doubly-allocated memory, the program becomes vulnerable to a buffer overflow attack. Doubly freeing memory may result in a write-what-where condition, allowing an attacker to execute arbitrary code.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Choose a language that provides automatic memory management.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Ensure that each allocation is freed only once. After freeing a chunk, set the pointer to NULL to ensure the pointer cannot be freed again. In complicated error conditions, be sure that clean-up routines respect the state of allocation properly. If the language is object oriented, ensure that object destructors delete each chunk of memory only once.\n3. *Phase: Implementation*. Use a static analysis tool to find double free instances."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/415.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Double Free",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-825"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-416",
              "name": "UseAfterFree",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product reuses or references memory after it has been freed."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product reuses or references memory after it has been freed. At some point afterward, the memory may be allocated again and saved in another pointer, while the original pointer references a location somewhere within the new allocation. Any operations using the original pointer are no longer valid because the memory \"belongs\" to the code that operates on the new pointer.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product reuses or references memory after it has been freed. At some point afterward, the memory may be allocated again and saved in another pointer, while the original pointer references a location somewhere within the new allocation. Any operations using the original pointer are no longer valid because the memory \"belongs\" to the code that operates on the new pointer.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Modify Memory.\n  - The use of previously freed memory may corrupt valid data, if the memory area in question has been allocated and used properly elsewhere.\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart.\n  - If chunk consolidation occurs after the use of previously freed data, the process may crash when invalid data is used as chunk information.\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Memory.\n  - Read operations on freed memory can sometimes leak sensitive information instead of causing a crash\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Confidentiality, Availability. **Impact**: Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands.\n  - If malicious data is entered before chunk consolidation can take place, it may be possible to take advantage of a write-what-where primitive to execute arbitrary code. If the newly allocated data happens to hold a class, in C++ for example, various function pointers may be scattered within the heap data. If one of these function pointers is overwritten with an address to valid shellcode, execution of arbitrary code can be achieved.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design; Strategy: Language Selection*. Choose a language that provides automatic memory management.\n2. *Phase: Implementation; Strategy: Attack Surface Reduction*. When freeing pointers, be sure to set them to NULL once they are freed. However, the utilization of multiple or complex data structures may lower the usefulness of this strategy."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/416.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Use After Free",
                "cwe/status": "Stable",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-825"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-419",
              "name": "UnprotectedPrimaryChannel",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses a primary channel for administration or restricted functionality, but it does not properly protect the channel."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses a primary channel for administration or restricted functionality, but it does not properly protect the channel.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses a primary channel for administration or restricted functionality, but it does not properly protect the channel.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity, Bypass Protection Mechanism.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Do not expose administrative functionnality on the user UI.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Protect the administrative/restricted functionality with a strong authentication mechanism."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/419.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Unprotected Primary Channel",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-923"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-420",
              "name": "UnprotectedAlternateChannel",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product protects a primary channel, but it does not use the same level of protection for an alternate channel."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product protects a primary channel, but it does not use the same level of protection for an alternate channel.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product protects a primary channel, but it does not use the same level of protection for an alternate channel.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity, Bypass Protection Mechanism.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Identify all alternate channels and use the same protection mechanisms that are used for the primary channels."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/420.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Unprotected Alternate Channel",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-923"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-421",
              "name": "RaceConditionDuringAccessToAlternateChannel",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product opens an alternate channel to communicate with an authorized user, but the channel is accessible to other actors."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "This creates a race condition that allows an attacker to access the channel before the authorized user does."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product opens an alternate channel to communicate with an authorized user, but the channel is accessible to other actors.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product opens an alternate channel to communicate with an authorized user, but the channel is accessible to other actors.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThis creates a race condition that allows an attacker to access the channel before the authorized user does.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity, Bypass Protection Mechanism."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/421.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Race Condition During Access to Alternate Channel",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-420"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-422",
              "name": "Shatter",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not properly verify the source of a message in the Windows Messaging System while running at elevated privileges, creating an alternate channel through which an attacker can directly send a message to the product."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not properly verify the source of a message in the Windows Messaging System while running at elevated privileges, creating an alternate channel through which an attacker can directly send a message to the product.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not properly verify the source of a message in the Windows Messaging System while running at elevated privileges, creating an alternate channel through which an attacker can directly send a message to the product.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity, Bypass Protection Mechanism.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Always verify and authenticate the source of the message."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/422.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Unprotected Windows Messaging Channel ('Shatter')",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-420"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-423",
              "name": "DeprecatedProxiedTrustedChannel",
