            {
              "id": "CWE-424",
              "name": "ImproperProtectionOfAlternatePath",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not sufficiently protect all possible paths that a user can take to access restricted functionality or resources."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not sufficiently protect all possible paths that a user can take to access restricted functionality or resources.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not sufficiently protect all possible paths that a user can take to access restricted functionality or resources.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism, Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Deploy different layers of protection to implement security in depth."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/424.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Improper Protection of Alternate Path",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-638"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-425",
              "name": "ForcedBrowsing",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The web application does not adequately enforce appropriate authorization on all restricted URLs, scripts, or files."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The web application does not adequately enforce appropriate authorization on all restricted URLs, scripts, or files.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe web application does not adequately enforce appropriate authorization on all restricted URLs, scripts, or files.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability, Access Control. **Impact**: Read Application Data, Modify Application Data, Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands, Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Operation*. Apply appropriate access control authorizations for each access to all restricted URLs, scripts or files.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Consider using MVC based frameworks such as Struts."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/425.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Direct Request ('Forced Browsing')",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-862"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-426",
              "name": "UntrustedSearchPath",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product searches for critical resources using an externally-supplied search path that can point to resources that are not under the product's direct control."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "This might allow attackers to execute their own programs, access unauthorized data files, or modify configuration in unexpected ways. If the product uses a search path to locate critical resources such as programs, then an attacker could modify that search path to point to a malicious program, which the targeted product would then execute. The problem extends to any type of critical resource that the product trusts. Some of the most common variants of untrusted search path are: In various UNIX and Linux-based systems, the PATH environment variable may be consulted to locate executable programs, and LD_PRELOAD may be used to locate a separate library. In various Microsoft-based systems, the PATH environment variable is consulted to locate a DLL, if the DLL is not found in other paths that appear earlier in the search order."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product searches for critical resources using an externally-supplied search path that can point to resources that are not under the product's direct control.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product searches for critical resources using an externally-supplied search path that can point to resources that are not under the product's direct control.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThis might allow attackers to execute their own programs, access unauthorized data files, or modify configuration in unexpected ways. If the product uses a search path to locate critical resources such as programs, then an attacker could modify that search path to point to a malicious program, which the targeted product would then execute. The problem extends to any type of critical resource that the product trusts. Some of the most common variants of untrusted search path are: In various UNIX and Linux-based systems, the PATH environment variable may be consulted to locate executable programs, and LD_PRELOAD may be used to locate a separate library. In various Microsoft-based systems, the PATH environment variable is consulted to locate a DLL, if the DLL is not found in other paths that appear earlier in the search order.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Confidentiality, Availability, Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity, Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands.\n  - There is the potential for arbitrary code execution with privileges of the vulnerable program.\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart.\n  - The program could be redirected to the wrong files, potentially triggering a crash or hang when the targeted file is too large or does not have the expected format.\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Files or Directories.\n  - The program could send the output of unauthorized files to the attacker.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Implementation; Strategy: Attack Surface Reduction*. Hard-code the search path to a set of known-safe values (such as system directories), or only allow them to be specified by the administrator in a configuration file. Do not allow these settings to be modified by an external party. Be careful to avoid related weaknesses such as CWE-426 and CWE-428.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. When invoking other programs, specify those programs using fully-qualified pathnames. While this is an effective approach, code that uses fully-qualified pathnames might not be portable to other systems that do not use the same pathnames. The portability can be improved by locating the full-qualified paths in a centralized, easily-modifiable location within the source code, and having the code refer to these paths.\n3. *Phase: Implementation*. Remove or restrict all environment settings before invoking other programs. This includes the PATH environment variable, LD_LIBRARY_PATH, and other settings that identify the location of code libraries, and any application-specific search paths.\n4. *Phase: Implementation*. Check your search path before use and remove any elements that are likely to be unsafe, such as the current working directory or a temporary files directory.\n5. *Phase: Implementation*. Use other functions that require explicit paths. Making use of any of the other readily available functions that require explicit paths is a safe way to avoid this problem. For example, system() in C does not require a full path since the shell can take care of it, while execl() and execv() require a full path."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/426.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Untrusted Search Path",
                "cwe/status": "Stable",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-642"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-427",
              "name": "UncontrolledSearchPathElement",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses a fixed or controlled search path to find resources, but one or more locations in that path can be under the control of unintended actors."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Although this weakness can occur with any type of resource, it is frequently introduced when a product uses a directory search path to find executables or code libraries, but the path contains a directory that can be modified by an attacker, such as \"/tmp\" or the current working directory. In Windows-based systems, when the LoadLibrary or LoadLibraryEx function is called with a DLL name that does not contain a fully qualified path, the function follows a search order that includes two path elements that might be uncontrolled: the directory from which the program has been loaded the current working directory In some cases, the attack can be conducted remotely, such as when SMB or WebDAV network shares are used. One or more locations in that path could include the Windows drive root or its subdirectories. This often exists in Linux-based code assuming the controlled nature of the root directory (/) or its subdirectories (/etc, etc), or a code that recursively accesses the parent directory. In Windows, the drive root and some of its subdirectories have weak permissions by default, which makes them uncontrolled. In some Unix-based systems, a PATH might be created that contains an empty element, e.g. by splicing an empty variable into the PATH. This empty element can be interpreted as equivalent to the current working directory, which might be an untrusted search element. In software package management frameworks (e.g., npm, RubyGems, or PyPi), the framework may identify dependencies on third-party libraries or other packages, then consult a repository that contains the desired package. The framework may search a public repository before a private repository. This could be exploited by attackers by placing a malicious package in the public repository that has the same name as a package from the private repository. The search path might not be directly under control of the developer relying on the framework, but this search order effectively contains an untrusted element."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses a fixed or controlled search path to find resources, but one or more locations in that path can be under the control of unintended actors.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses a fixed or controlled search path to find resources, but one or more locations in that path can be under the control of unintended actors.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nAlthough this weakness can occur with any type of resource, it is frequently introduced when a product uses a directory search path to find executables or code libraries, but the path contains a directory that can be modified by an attacker, such as \"/tmp\" or the current working directory. In Windows-based systems, when the LoadLibrary or LoadLibraryEx function is called with a DLL name that does not contain a fully qualified path, the function follows a search order that includes two path elements that might be uncontrolled: the directory from which the program has been loaded the current working directory In some cases, the attack can be conducted remotely, such as when SMB or WebDAV network shares are used. One or more locations in that path could include the Windows drive root or its subdirectories. This often exists in Linux-based code assuming the controlled nature of the root directory (/) or its subdirectories (/etc, etc), or a code that recursively accesses the parent directory. In Windows, the drive root and some of its subdirectories have weak permissions by default, which makes them uncontrolled. In some Unix-based systems, a PATH might be created that contains an empty element, e.g. by splicing an empty variable into the PATH. This empty element can be interpreted as equivalent to the current working directory, which might be an untrusted search element. In software package management frameworks (e.g., npm, RubyGems, or PyPi), the framework may identify dependencies on third-party libraries or other packages, then consult a repository that contains the desired package. The framework may search a public repository before a private repository. This could be exploited by attackers by placing a malicious package in the public repository that has the same name as a package from the private repository. The search path might not be directly under control of the developer relying on the framework, but this search order effectively contains an untrusted element.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability. **Impact**: Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Implementation; Strategy: Attack Surface Reduction*. Hard-code the search path to a set of known-safe values (such as system directories), or only allow them to be specified by the administrator in a configuration file. Do not allow these settings to be modified by an external party. Be careful to avoid related weaknesses such as CWE-426 and CWE-428.\n2. *Phase: Implementation; Strategy: Attack Surface Reduction*. When invoking other programs, specify those programs using fully-qualified pathnames. While this is an effective approach, code that uses fully-qualified pathnames might not be portable to other systems that do not use the same pathnames. The portability can be improved by locating the full-qualified paths in a centralized, easily-modifiable location within the source code, and having the code refer to these paths.\n3. *Phase: Implementation; Strategy: Attack Surface Reduction*. Remove or restrict all environment settings before invoking other programs. This includes the PATH environment variable, LD_LIBRARY_PATH, and other settings that identify the location of code libraries, and any application-specific search paths.\n4. *Phase: Implementation*. Check your search path before use and remove any elements that are likely to be unsafe, such as the current working directory or a temporary files directory. Since this is a denylist approach, it might not be a complete solution.\n5. *Phase: Implementation*. Use other functions that require explicit paths. Making use of any of the other readily available functions that require explicit paths is a safe way to avoid this problem. For example, system() in C does not require a full path since the shell can take care of finding the program using the PATH environment variable, while execl() and execv() require a full path."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/427.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Uncontrolled Search Path Element",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-668"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-428",
              "name": "UnquotedSearchPathOrElement",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses a search path that contains an unquoted element, in which the element contains whitespace or other separators."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "If a malicious individual has access to the file system, it is possible to elevate privileges by inserting such a file as \"C:\\Program.exe\" to be run by a privileged program making use of WinExec."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses a search path that contains an unquoted element, in which the element contains whitespace or other separators. This can cause the product to access resources in a parent path.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses a search path that contains an unquoted element, in which the element contains whitespace or other separators. This can cause the product to access resources in a parent path.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIf a malicious individual has access to the file system, it is possible to elevate privileges by inserting such a file as \"C:\\Program.exe\" to be run by a privileged program making use of WinExec.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability. **Impact**: Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Properly quote the full search path before executing a program on the system.\n2. *Phase: Implementation; Strategy: Input Validation*. Assume all input is malicious. Use an \"accept known good\" input validation strategy, i.e., use a list of acceptable inputs that strictly conform to specifications. Reject any input that does not strictly conform to specifications, or transform it into something that does. When performing input validation, consider all potentially relevant properties, including length, type of input, the full range of acceptable values, missing or extra inputs, syntax, consistency across related fields, and conformance to business rules. As an example of business rule logic, \"boat\" may be syntactically valid because it only contains alphanumeric characters, but it is not valid if the input is only expected to contain colors such as \"red\" or \"blue.\" Do not rely exclusively on looking for malicious or malformed inputs. This is likely to miss at least one undesirable input, especially if the code's environment changes. This can give attackers enough room to bypass the intended validation. However, denylists can be useful for detecting potential attacks or determining which inputs are so malformed that they should be rejected outright.\n3. *Phase: Implementation; Strategy: Input Validation*. Inputs should be decoded and canonicalized to the application's current internal representation before being validated (CWE-180). Make sure that the application does not decode the same input twice (CWE-174). Such errors could be used to bypass allowlist validation schemes by introducing dangerous inputs after they have been checked."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/428.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Unquoted Search Path or Element",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-668"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-430",
              "name": "DeploymentOfWrongHandler",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The wrong \"handler\" is assigned to process an object."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "An example of deploying the wrong handler would be calling a servlet to reveal source code of a .JSP file, or automatically \"determining\" type of the object even if it is contradictory to an explicitly specified type."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The wrong \"handler\" is assigned to process an object.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe wrong \"handler\" is assigned to process an object.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nAn example of deploying the wrong handler would be calling a servlet to reveal source code of a .JSP file, or automatically \"determining\" type of the object even if it is contradictory to an explicitly specified type.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Varies by Context, Unexpected State.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Perform a type check before interpreting an object.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Reject any inconsistent types, such as a file with a .GIF extension that appears to consist of PHP code."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/430.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Deployment of Wrong Handler",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-691"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-431",
              "name": "MissingHandler",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A handler is not available or implemented."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "When an exception is thrown and not caught, the process has given up an opportunity to decide if a given failure or event is worth a change in execution."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "A handler is not available or implemented.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA handler is not available or implemented.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nWhen an exception is thrown and not caught, the process has given up an opportunity to decide if a given failure or event is worth a change in execution.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Varies by Context.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Handle all possible situations (e.g. error condition).\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. If an operation can throw an Exception, implement a handler for that specific exception."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/431.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Missing Handler",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-691"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-432",
              "name": "DangerousSignalHandlerNotDisabledDuringSensitiveOperations",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses a signal handler that shares state with other signal handlers, but it does not properly mask or prevent those signal handlers from being invoked while the original signal handler is still running."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "During the execution of a signal handler, it can be interrupted by another handler when a different signal is sent. If the two handlers share state - such as global variables - then an attacker can corrupt the state by sending another signal before the first handler has completed execution."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses a signal handler that shares state with other signal handlers, but it does not properly mask or prevent those signal handlers from being invoked while the original signal handler is still running.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses a signal handler that shares state with other signal handlers, but it does not properly mask or prevent those signal handlers from being invoked while the original signal handler is still running.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nDuring the execution of a signal handler, it can be interrupted by another handler when a different signal is sent. If the two handlers share state - such as global variables - then an attacker can corrupt the state by sending another signal before the first handler has completed execution.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Modify Application Data.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Turn off dangerous handlers when performing sensitive operations."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/432.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Dangerous Signal Handler not Disabled During Sensitive Operations",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-364"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-433",
              "name": "UnparsedRawWebContentDelivery",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product stores raw content or supporting code under the web document root with an extension that is not specifically handled by the server."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "If code is stored in a file with an extension such as \".inc\" or \".pl\", and the web server does not have a handler for that extension, then the server will likely send the contents of the file directly to the requester without the pre-processing that was expected. When that file contains sensitive information such as database credentials, this may allow the attacker to compromise the application or associated components."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product stores raw content or supporting code under the web document root with an extension that is not specifically handled by the server.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product stores raw content or supporting code under the web document root with an extension that is not specifically handled by the server.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIf code is stored in a file with an extension such as \".inc\" or \".pl\", and the web server does not have a handler for that extension, then the server will likely send the contents of the file directly to the requester without the pre-processing that was expected. When that file contains sensitive information such as database credentials, this may allow the attacker to compromise the application or associated components.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Perform a type check before interpreting files.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Do not store sensitive information in files which may be misinterpreted."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/433.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Unparsed Raw Web Content Delivery",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-219"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-434",
              "name": "UnrestrictedUploadOfFileWithDangerousType",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product allows the upload or transfer of dangerous file types that are automatically processed within its environment."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product allows the upload or transfer of dangerous file types that are automatically processed within its environment.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product allows the upload or transfer of dangerous file types that are automatically processed within its environment.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Confidentiality, Availability. **Impact**: Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands.\n  - Arbitrary code execution is possible if an uploaded file is interpreted and executed as code by the recipient. This is especially true for web-server extensions such as .asp and .php because these file types are often treated as automatically executable, even when file system permissions do not specify execution. For example, in Unix environments, programs typically cannot run unless the execute bit is set, but PHP programs may be executed by the web server without directly invoking them on the operating system.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Generate a new, unique filename for an uploaded file instead of using the user-supplied filename, so that no external input is used at all.[REF-422] [REF-423]\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design; Strategy: Enforcement by Conversion*. When the set of acceptable objects, such as filenames or URLs, is limited or known, create a mapping from a set of fixed input values (such as numeric IDs) to the actual filenames or URLs, and reject all other inputs.\n3. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Consider storing the uploaded files outside of the web document root entirely. Then, use other mechanisms to deliver the files dynamically. [REF-423]\n4. *Phase: Implementation; Strategy: Input Validation*. Assume all input is malicious. Use an \"accept known good\" input validation strategy, i.e., use a list of acceptable inputs that strictly conform to specifications. Reject any input that does not strictly conform to specifications, or transform it into something that does. When performing input validation, consider all potentially relevant properties, including length, type of input, the full range of acceptable values, missing or extra inputs, syntax, consistency across related fields, and conformance to business rules. As an example of business rule logic, \"boat\" may be syntactically valid because it only contains alphanumeric characters, but it is not valid if the input is only expected to contain colors such as \"red\" or \"blue.\" Do not rely exclusively on looking for malicious or malformed inputs. This is likely to miss at least one undesirable input, especially if the code's environment changes. This can give attackers enough room to bypass the intended validation. However, denylists can be useful for detecting potential attacks or determining which inputs are so malformed that they should be rejected outright. For example, limiting filenames to alphanumeric characters can help to restrict the introduction of unintended file extensions.\n5. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Define a very limited set of allowable extensions and only generate filenames that end in these extensions. Consider the possibility of XSS (CWE-79) before allowing .html or .htm file types.\n6. *Phase: Implementation; Strategy: Input Validation*. Ensure that only one extension is used in the filename. Some web servers, including some versions of Apache, may process files based on inner extensions so that \"filename.php.gif\" is fed to the PHP interpreter.[REF-422] [REF-423]\n7. *Phase: Implementation*. When running on a web server that supports case-insensitive filenames, perform case-insensitive evaluations of the extensions that are provided.\n8. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. For any security checks that are performed on the client side, ensure that these checks are duplicated on the server side, in order to avoid CWE-602. Attackers can bypass the client-side checks by modifying values after the checks have been performed, or by changing the client to remove the client-side checks entirely. Then, these modified values would be submitted to the server.\n9. *Phase: Implementation*. Do not rely exclusively on sanity checks of file contents to ensure that the file is of the expected type and size. It may be possible for an attacker to hide code in some file segments that will still be executed by the server. For example, GIF images may contain a free-form comments field.\n10. *Phase: Implementation*. Do not rely exclusively on the MIME content type or filename attribute when determining how to render a file. Validating the MIME content type and ensuring that it matches the extension is only a partial solution.\n11. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Operation; Strategy: Environment Hardening*. Run your code using the lowest privileges that are required to accomplish the necessary tasks [REF-76]. If possible, create isolated accounts with limited privileges that are only used for a single task. That way, a successful attack will not immediately give the attacker access to the rest of the software or its environment. For example, database applications rarely need to run as the database administrator, especially in day-to-day operations.\n12. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Operation; Strategy: Sandbox or Jail*. Run the code in a \"jail\" or similar sandbox environment that enforces strict boundaries between the process and the operating system. This may effectively restrict which files can be accessed in a particular directory or which commands can be executed by the software. OS-level examples include the Unix chroot jail, AppArmor, and SELinux. In general, managed code may provide some protection. For example, java.io.FilePermission in the Java SecurityManager allows the software to specify restrictions on file operations. This may not be a feasible solution, and it only limits the impact to the operating system; the rest of the application may still be subject to compromise. Be careful to avoid CWE-243 and other weaknesses related to jails."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/434.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Unrestricted Upload of File with Dangerous Type",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-669"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-435",
              "name": "ImproperInteractionBetweenMultipleCorrectlyBehavingEntities",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "An interaction error occurs when two entities have correct behavior when running independently of each other, but when they are integrated as components in a larger system or process, they introduce incorrect behaviors that may cause resultant weaknesses."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "When a system or process combines multiple independent components, this often produces new, emergent behaviors at the system level. However, if the interactions between these components are not fully accounted for, some of the emergent behaviors can be incorrect or even insecure."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "An interaction error occurs when two entities have correct behavior when running independently of each other, but when they are integrated as components in a larger system or process, they introduce incorrect behaviors that may cause resultant weaknesses.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nAn interaction error occurs when two entities have correct behavior when running independently of each other, but when they are integrated as components in a larger system or process, they introduce incorrect behaviors that may cause resultant weaknesses.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nWhen a system or process combines multiple independent components, this often produces new, emergent behaviors at the system level. However, if the interactions between these components are not fully accounted for, some of the emergent behaviors can be incorrect or even insecure.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Unexpected State, Varies by Context."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/435.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Improper Interaction Between Multiple Correctly-Behaving Entities",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Pillar"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-436",
              "name": "InterpretationConflict",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Product A handles inputs or steps differently than Product B, which causes A to perform incorrect actions based on its perception of B's state."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "This is generally found in proxies, firewalls, anti-virus software, and other intermediary devices that monitor, allow, deny, or modify traffic based on how the client or server is expected to behave."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Product A handles inputs or steps differently than Product B, which causes A to perform incorrect actions based on its perception of B's state.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nProduct A handles inputs or steps differently than Product B, which causes A to perform incorrect actions based on its perception of B's state.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThis is generally found in proxies, firewalls, anti-virus software, and other intermediary devices that monitor, allow, deny, or modify traffic based on how the client or server is expected to behave.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Unexpected State, Varies by Context."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/436.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Interpretation Conflict",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-435"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-437",
              "name": "IncompleteModelOfEndpointFeatures",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A product acts as an intermediary or monitor between two or more endpoints, but it does not have a complete model of an endpoint's features, behaviors, or state, potentially causing the product to perform incorrect actions based on this incomplete model."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "A product acts as an intermediary or monitor between two or more endpoints, but it does not have a complete model of an endpoint's features, behaviors, or state, potentially causing the product to perform incorrect actions based on this incomplete model.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA product acts as an intermediary or monitor between two or more endpoints, but it does not have a complete model of an endpoint's features, behaviors, or state, potentially causing the product to perform incorrect actions based on this incomplete model.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Unexpected State, Varies by Context."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/437.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Incomplete Model of Endpoint Features",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-436"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-439",
              "name": "BehavioralChangeInNewVersionOrEnvironment",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A's behavior or functionality changes with a new version of A, or a new environment, which is not known (or manageable) by B."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "A's behavior or functionality changes with a new version of A, or a new environment, which is not known (or manageable) by B.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA's behavior or functionality changes with a new version of A, or a new environment, which is not known (or manageable) by B.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation, Varies by Context."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/439.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Behavioral Change in New Version or Environment",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-435"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-440",
              "name": "ExpectedBehaviorViolation",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A feature, API, or function does not perform according to its specification."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "A feature, API, or function does not perform according to its specification.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA feature, API, or function does not perform according to its specification.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation, Varies by Context."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/440.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Expected Behavior Violation",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-684"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-441",
              "name": "ConfusedDeputy",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product receives a request, message, or directive from an upstream component, but the product does not sufficiently preserve the original source of the request before forwarding the request to an external actor that is outside of the product's control sphere."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "If an attacker cannot directly contact a target, but the product has access to the target, then the attacker can send a request to the product and have it be forwarded to the target. The request would appear to be coming from the product's system, not the attacker's system. As a result, the attacker can bypass access controls (such as firewalls) or hide the source of malicious requests, since the requests would not be coming directly from the attacker. Since proxy functionality and message-forwarding often serve a legitimate purpose, this issue only becomes a vulnerability when: The product runs with different privileges or on a different system, or otherwise has different levels of access than the upstream component; The attacker is prevented from making the request directly to the target; and The attacker can create a request that the proxy does not explicitly intend to be forwarded on the behalf of the requester. Such a request might point to an unexpected hostname, port number, hardware IP, or service. Or, the request might be sent to an allowed service, but the request could contain disallowed directives, commands, or resources."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product receives a request, message, or directive from an upstream component, but the product does not sufficiently preserve the original source of the request before forwarding the request to an external actor that is outside of the product's control sphere. This causes the product to appear to be the source of the request, leading it to act as a proxy or other intermediary between the upstream component and the external actor.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product receives a request, message, or directive from an upstream component, but the product does not sufficiently preserve the original source of the request before forwarding the request to an external actor that is outside of the product's control sphere. This causes the product to appear to be the source of the request, leading it to act as a proxy or other intermediary between the upstream component and the external actor.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIf an attacker cannot directly contact a target, but the product has access to the target, then the attacker can send a request to the product and have it be forwarded to the target. The request would appear to be coming from the product's system, not the attacker's system. As a result, the attacker can bypass access controls (such as firewalls) or hide the source of malicious requests, since the requests would not be coming directly from the attacker. Since proxy functionality and message-forwarding often serve a legitimate purpose, this issue only becomes a vulnerability when: The product runs with different privileges or on a different system, or otherwise has different levels of access than the upstream component; The attacker is prevented from making the request directly to the target; and The attacker can create a request that the proxy does not explicitly intend to be forwarded on the behalf of the requester. Such a request might point to an unexpected hostname, port number, hardware IP, or service. Or, the request might be sent to an allowed service, but the request could contain disallowed directives, commands, or resources.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Non-Repudiation, Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity, Hide Activities, Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Enforce the use of strong mutual authentication mechanism between the two parties.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Whenever a product is an intermediary or proxy for transactions between two other components, the proxy core should not drop the identity of the initiator of the transaction. The immutability of the identity of the initiator must be maintained and should be forwarded all the way to the target."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/441.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Unintended Proxy or Intermediary ('Confused Deputy')",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-610"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-443",
              "name": "DeprecatedHttpResponseSplitting",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "This weakness can be found at CWE-113."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "This weakness can be found at CWE-113.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis weakness can be found at CWE-113."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/443.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "DEPRECATED: HTTP response splitting",
                "cwe/status": "Deprecated",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-444",
              "name": "HttpRequestResponseSmuggling",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product acts as an intermediary HTTP agent (such as a proxy or firewall) in the data flow between two entities such as a client and server, but it does not interpret malformed HTTP requests or responses in ways that are consistent with how the messages will be processed by those entities that are at the ultimate destination."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "HTTP requests or responses (\"messages\") can be malformed or unexpected in ways that cause web servers or clients to interpret the messages in different ways than intermediary HTTP agents such as load balancers, reverse proxies, web caching proxies, application firewalls, etc. For example, an adversary may be able to add duplicate or different header fields that a client or server might interpret as one set of messages, whereas the intermediary might interpret the same sequence of bytes as a different set of messages. For example, discrepancies can arise in how to handle duplicate headers like two Transfer-encoding (TE) or two Content-length (CL), or the malicious HTTP message will have different headers for TE and CL. The inconsistent parsing and interpretation of messages can allow the adversary to \"smuggle\" a message to the client/server without the intermediary being aware of it. This weakness is usually the result of the usage of outdated or incompatible HTTP protocol versions in the HTTP agents."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product acts as an intermediary HTTP agent (such as a proxy or firewall) in the data flow between two entities such as a client and server, but it does not interpret malformed HTTP requests or responses in ways that are consistent with how the messages will be processed by those entities that are at the ultimate destination.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product acts as an intermediary HTTP agent (such as a proxy or firewall) in the data flow between two entities such as a client and server, but it does not interpret malformed HTTP requests or responses in ways that are consistent with how the messages will be processed by those entities that are at the ultimate destination.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nHTTP requests or responses (\"messages\") can be malformed or unexpected in ways that cause web servers or clients to interpret the messages in different ways than intermediary HTTP agents such as load balancers, reverse proxies, web caching proxies, application firewalls, etc. For example, an adversary may be able to add duplicate or different header fields that a client or server might interpret as one set of messages, whereas the intermediary might interpret the same sequence of bytes as a different set of messages. For example, discrepancies can arise in how to handle duplicate headers like two Transfer-encoding (TE) or two Content-length (CL), or the malicious HTTP message will have different headers for TE and CL. The inconsistent parsing and interpretation of messages can allow the adversary to \"smuggle\" a message to the client/server without the intermediary being aware of it. This weakness is usually the result of the usage of outdated or incompatible HTTP protocol versions in the HTTP agents.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Non-Repudiation, Access Control. **Impact**: Unexpected State, Hide Activities, Bypass Protection Mechanism.\n  - An attacker could create HTTP messages to exploit a number of weaknesses including 1) the message can trick the web server to associate a URL with another URL's webpage and caching the contents of the webpage (web cache poisoning attack), 2) the message can be structured to bypass the firewall protection mechanisms and gain unauthorized access to a web application, and 3) the message can invoke a script or a page that returns client credentials (similar to a Cross Site Scripting attack).\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Use a web server that employs a strict HTTP parsing procedure, such as Apache [REF-433].\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Use only SSL communication.\n3. *Phase: Implementation*. Terminate the client session after each request.\n4. *Phase: System Configuration*. Turn all pages to non-cacheable."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/444.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Inconsistent Interpretation of HTTP Requests ('HTTP Request/Response Smuggling')",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-436"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-446",
              "name": "UiDiscrepancyForSecurityFeature",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The user interface does not correctly enable or configure a security feature, but the interface provides feedback that causes the user to believe that the feature is in a secure state."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "When the user interface does not properly reflect what the user asks of it, then it can lead the user into a false sense of security. For example, the user might check a box to enable a security option to enable encrypted communications, but the product does not actually enable the encryption. Alternately, the user might provide a \"restrict ALL\" access control rule, but the product only implements \"restrict SOME\"."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The user interface does not correctly enable or configure a security feature, but the interface provides feedback that causes the user to believe that the feature is in a secure state.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe user interface does not correctly enable or configure a security feature, but the interface provides feedback that causes the user to believe that the feature is in a secure state.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nWhen the user interface does not properly reflect what the user asks of it, then it can lead the user into a false sense of security. For example, the user might check a box to enable a security option to enable encrypted communications, but the product does not actually enable the encryption. Alternately, the user might provide a \"restrict ALL\" access control rule, but the product only implements \"restrict SOME\".\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Varies by Context."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/446.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "UI Discrepancy for Security Feature",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-684"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-447",
              "name": "UnimplementedOrUnsupportedFeatureInUi",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A UI function for a security feature appears to be supported and gives feedback to the user that suggests that it is supported, but the underlying functionality is not implemented."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "A UI function for a security feature appears to be supported and gives feedback to the user that suggests that it is supported, but the underlying functionality is not implemented.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA UI function for a security feature appears to be supported and gives feedback to the user that suggests that it is supported, but the underlying functionality is not implemented.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Varies by Context, Unexpected State.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Testing*. Perform functionality testing before deploying the application."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/447.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Unimplemented or Unsupported Feature in UI",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-671"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-448",
              "name": "ObsoleteFeatureInUi",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A UI function is obsolete and the product does not warn the user."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "A UI function is obsolete and the product does not warn the user.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA UI function is obsolete and the product does not warn the user.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation, Varies by Context.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Remove the obsolete feature from the UI. Warn the user that the feature is no longer supported."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/448.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Obsolete Feature in UI",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-446"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-449",
              "name": "TheUiPerformsTheWrongAction",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The UI performs the wrong action with respect to the user's request."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The UI performs the wrong action with respect to the user's request.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe UI performs the wrong action with respect to the user's request.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation, Varies by Context."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/449.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "The UI Performs the Wrong Action",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-446"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-450",
              "name": "MultipleInterpretationsOfUiInput",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The UI has multiple interpretations of user input but does not prompt the user when it selects the less secure interpretation."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The UI has multiple interpretations of user input but does not prompt the user when it selects the less secure interpretation.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe UI has multiple interpretations of user input but does not prompt the user when it selects the less secure interpretation.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Varies by Context.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation; Strategy: Input Validation*. Assume all input is malicious. Use an \"accept known good\" input validation strategy, i.e., use a list of acceptable inputs that strictly conform to specifications. Reject any input that does not strictly conform to specifications, or transform it into something that does. When performing input validation, consider all potentially relevant properties, including length, type of input, the full range of acceptable values, missing or extra inputs, syntax, consistency across related fields, and conformance to business rules. As an example of business rule logic, \"boat\" may be syntactically valid because it only contains alphanumeric characters, but it is not valid if the input is only expected to contain colors such as \"red\" or \"blue.\" Do not rely exclusively on looking for malicious or malformed inputs. This is likely to miss at least one undesirable input, especially if the code's environment changes. This can give attackers enough room to bypass the intended validation. However, denylists can be useful for detecting potential attacks or determining which inputs are so malformed that they should be rejected outright.\n2. *Phase: Implementation; Strategy: Input Validation*. Inputs should be decoded and canonicalized to the application's current internal representation before being validated (CWE-180). Make sure that the application does not decode the same input twice (CWE-174). Such errors could be used to bypass allowlist validation schemes by introducing dangerous inputs after they have been checked."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/450.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Multiple Interpretations of UI Input",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-357"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-451",
              "name": "UserInterfaceUiMisrepresentationOfCriticalInformation",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The user interface (UI) does not properly represent critical information to the user, allowing the information - or its source - to be obscured or spoofed."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "If an attacker can cause the UI to display erroneous data, or to otherwise convince the user to display information that appears to come from a trusted source, then the attacker could trick the user into performing the wrong action. This is often a component in phishing attacks, but other kinds of problems exist. For example, if the UI is used to monitor the security state of a system or network, then omitting or obscuring an important indicator could prevent the user from detecting and reacting to a security-critical event. UI misrepresentation can take many forms: Incorrect indicator: incorrect information is displayed, which prevents the user from understanding the true state of the product or the environment the product is monitoring, especially of potentially-dangerous conditions or operations. This can be broken down into several different subtypes. Overlay: an area of the display is intended to give critical information, but another process can modify the display by overlaying another element on top of it. The user is not interacting with the expected portion of the user interface. This is the problem that enables clickjacking attacks, although many other types of attacks exist that involve overlay. Icon manipulation: the wrong icon, or the wrong color indicator, can be influenced (such as making a dangerous .EXE executable look like a harmless .GIF) Timing: the product is performing a state transition or context switch that is presented to the user with an indicator, but a race condition can cause the wrong indicator to be used before the product has fully switched context. The race window could be extended indefinitely if the attacker can trigger an error. Visual truncation: important information could be truncated from the display, such as a long filename with a dangerous extension that is not displayed in the GUI because the malicious portion is truncated. The use of excessive whitespace can also cause truncation, or place the potentially-dangerous indicator outside of the user's field of view (e.g. \"filename.txt .exe\"). A different type of truncation can occur when a portion of the information is removed due to reasons other than length, such as the accidental insertion of an end-of-input marker in the middle of an input, such as a NUL byte in a C-style string. Visual distinction: visual information might be presented in a way that makes it difficult for the user to quickly and correctly distinguish between critical and unimportant segments of the display. Homographs: letters from different character sets, fonts, or languages can appear very similar (i.e. may be visually equivalent) in a way that causes the human user to misread the text (for example, to conduct phishing attacks to trick a user into visiting a malicious web site with a visually-similar name as a trusted site). This can be regarded as a type of visual distinction issue."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The user interface (UI) does not properly represent critical information to the user, allowing the information - or its source - to be obscured or spoofed. This is often a component in phishing attacks.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe user interface (UI) does not properly represent critical information to the user, allowing the information - or its source - to be obscured or spoofed. This is often a component in phishing attacks.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIf an attacker can cause the UI to display erroneous data, or to otherwise convince the user to display information that appears to come from a trusted source, then the attacker could trick the user into performing the wrong action. This is often a component in phishing attacks, but other kinds of problems exist. For example, if the UI is used to monitor the security state of a system or network, then omitting or obscuring an important indicator could prevent the user from detecting and reacting to a security-critical event. UI misrepresentation can take many forms: Incorrect indicator: incorrect information is displayed, which prevents the user from understanding the true state of the product or the environment the product is monitoring, especially of potentially-dangerous conditions or operations. This can be broken down into several different subtypes. Overlay: an area of the display is intended to give critical information, but another process can modify the display by overlaying another element on top of it. The user is not interacting with the expected portion of the user interface. This is the problem that enables clickjacking attacks, although many other types of attacks exist that involve overlay. Icon manipulation: the wrong icon, or the wrong color indicator, can be influenced (such as making a dangerous .EXE executable look like a harmless .GIF) Timing: the product is performing a state transition or context switch that is presented to the user with an indicator, but a race condition can cause the wrong indicator to be used before the product has fully switched context. The race window could be extended indefinitely if the attacker can trigger an error. Visual truncation: important information could be truncated from the display, such as a long filename with a dangerous extension that is not displayed in the GUI because the malicious portion is truncated. The use of excessive whitespace can also cause truncation, or place the potentially-dangerous indicator outside of the user's field of view (e.g. \"filename.txt .exe\"). A different type of truncation can occur when a portion of the information is removed due to reasons other than length, such as the accidental insertion of an end-of-input marker in the middle of an input, such as a NUL byte in a C-style string. Visual distinction: visual information might be presented in a way that makes it difficult for the user to quickly and correctly distinguish between critical and unimportant segments of the display. Homographs: letters from different character sets, fonts, or languages can appear very similar (i.e. may be visually equivalent) in a way that causes the human user to misread the text (for example, to conduct phishing attacks to trick a user into visiting a malicious web site with a visually-similar name as a trusted site). This can be regarded as a type of visual distinction issue.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Non-Repudiation, Access Control. **Impact**: Hide Activities, Bypass Protection Mechanism.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation; Strategy: Input Validation*. Perform data validation (e.g. syntax, length, etc.) before interpreting the data.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design; Strategy: Output Encoding*. Create a strategy for presenting information, and plan for how to display unusual characters."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/451.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "User Interface (UI) Misrepresentation of Critical Information",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-684"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-453",
              "name": "InsecureDefaultVariableInitialization",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product, by default, initializes an internal variable with an insecure or less secure value than is possible."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product, by default, initializes an internal variable with an insecure or less secure value than is possible.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product, by default, initializes an internal variable with an insecure or less secure value than is possible.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Modify Application Data.\n  - An attacker could gain access to and modify sensitive data or system information.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: System Configuration*. Disable or change default settings when they can be used to abuse the system. Since those default settings are shipped with the product they are likely to be known by a potential attacker who is familiar with the product. For instance, default credentials should be changed or the associated accounts should be disabled."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/453.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Insecure Default Variable Initialization",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-1188"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-454",
              "name": "ExternalInitializationOfTrustedVariablesOrDataStores",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product initializes critical internal variables or data stores using inputs that can be modified by untrusted actors."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "A product system should be reluctant to trust variables that have been initialized outside of its trust boundary, especially if they are initialized by users. The variables may have been initialized incorrectly. If an attacker can initialize the variable, then they can influence what the vulnerable system will do."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product initializes critical internal variables or data stores using inputs that can be modified by untrusted actors.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product initializes critical internal variables or data stores using inputs that can be modified by untrusted actors.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nA product system should be reluctant to trust variables that have been initialized outside of its trust boundary, especially if they are initialized by users. The variables may have been initialized incorrectly. If an attacker can initialize the variable, then they can influence what the vulnerable system will do.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Modify Application Data.\n  - An attacker could gain access to and modify sensitive data or system information.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation; Strategy: Input Validation*. A product system should be reluctant to trust variables that have been initialized outside of its trust boundary. Ensure adequate checking (e.g. input validation) is performed when relying on input from outside a trust boundary.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Avoid any external control of variables. If necessary, restrict the variables that can be modified using an allowlist, and use a different namespace or naming convention if possible."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/454.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "External Initialization of Trusted Variables or Data Stores",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-1419"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-455",
              "name": "NonExitOnFailedInitialization",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not exit or otherwise modify its operation when security-relevant errors occur during initialization, such as when a configuration file has a format error or a hardware security module (HSM) cannot be activated, which can cause the product to execute in a less secure fashion than intended by the administrator."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not exit or otherwise modify its operation when security-relevant errors occur during initialization, such as when a configuration file has a format error or a hardware security module (HSM) cannot be activated, which can cause the product to execute in a less secure fashion than intended by the administrator.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not exit or otherwise modify its operation when security-relevant errors occur during initialization, such as when a configuration file has a format error or a hardware security module (HSM) cannot be activated, which can cause the product to execute in a less secure fashion than intended by the administrator.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Modify Application Data, Alter Execution Logic.\n  - The application could be placed in an insecure state that may allow an attacker to modify sensitive data or allow unintended logic to be executed.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Follow the principle of failing securely when an error occurs. The system should enter a state where it is not vulnerable and will not display sensitive error messages to a potential attacker."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/455.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Non-exit on Failed Initialization",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-705"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-456",
              "name": "MissingInitializationOfAVariable",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not initialize critical variables, which causes the execution environment to use unexpected values."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not initialize critical variables, which causes the execution environment to use unexpected values.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not initialize critical variables, which causes the execution environment to use unexpected values.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Unexpected State, Quality Degradation, Varies by Context.\n  - The uninitialized data may be invalid, causing logic errors within the program. In some cases, this could result in a security problem.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation; Strategy: Attack Surface Reduction*. Ensure that critical variables are initialized before first use [REF-1485].\n2. *Phase: Requirements; Strategy: Language Selection*. Choose a language that is not susceptible to these issues."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/456.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Missing Initialization of a Variable",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-909"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-457",
              "name": "UseOfUninitializedVariable",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The code uses a variable that has not been initialized, leading to unpredictable or unintended results."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In some languages such as C and C++, stack variables are not initialized by default. They generally contain junk data with the contents of stack memory before the function was invoked. An attacker can sometimes control or read these contents. In other languages or conditions, a variable that is not explicitly initialized can be given a default value that has security implications, depending on the logic of the program. The presence of an uninitialized variable can sometimes indicate a typographic error in the code."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The code uses a variable that has not been initialized, leading to unpredictable or unintended results.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code uses a variable that has not been initialized, leading to unpredictable or unintended results.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIn some languages such as C and C++, stack variables are not initialized by default. They generally contain junk data with the contents of stack memory before the function was invoked. An attacker can sometimes control or read these contents. In other languages or conditions, a variable that is not explicitly initialized can be given a default value that has security implications, depending on the logic of the program. The presence of an uninitialized variable can sometimes indicate a typographic error in the code.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Availability, Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Other.\n  - Initial variables usually contain junk, which can not be trusted for consistency. This can lead to denial of service conditions, or modify control flow in unexpected ways. In some cases, an attacker can \"pre-initialize\" the variable using previous actions, which might enable code execution. This can cause a race condition if a lock variable check passes when it should not.\n- **Scope**: Authorization, Other. **Impact**: Other.\n  - Strings that are not initialized are especially dangerous, since many functions expect a null at the end -- and only at the end -- of a string.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation; Strategy: Attack Surface Reduction*. Ensure that critical variables are initialized before first use [REF-1485].\n2. *Phase: Build and Compilation; Strategy: Compilation or Build Hardening*. Most compilers will complain about the use of uninitialized variables if warnings are turned on.\n3. *Phase: Implementation, Operation*. When using a language that does not require explicit declaration of variables, run or compile the software in a mode that reports undeclared or unknown variables. This may indicate the presence of a typographic error in the variable's name.\n4. *Phase: Requirements; Strategy: Language Selection*. Choose a language that is not susceptible to these issues.\n5. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Mitigating technologies such as safe string libraries and container abstractions could be introduced."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/457.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Use of Uninitialized Variable",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-908"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-458",
              "name": "DeprecatedIncorrectInitialization",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "This weakness has been deprecated because its name and description did not match."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "This weakness has been deprecated because its name and description did not match. The description duplicated CWE-454, while the name suggested a more abstract initialization problem. Please refer to CWE-665 for the more abstract problem.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis weakness has been deprecated because its name and description did not match. The description duplicated CWE-454, while the name suggested a more abstract initialization problem. Please refer to CWE-665 for the more abstract problem."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/458.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "DEPRECATED: Incorrect Initialization",
                "cwe/status": "Deprecated",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-459",
              "name": "IncompleteCleanup",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not properly \"clean up\" and remove temporary or supporting resources after they have been used."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not properly \"clean up\" and remove temporary or supporting resources after they have been used.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not properly \"clean up\" and remove temporary or supporting resources after they have been used.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other, Confidentiality, Integrity. **Impact**: Other, Read Application Data, Modify Application Data, DoS: Resource Consumption (Other).\n  - It is possible to overflow the number of temporary files because directories typically have limits on the number of files allowed. This could create a denial of service problem.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Implementation*. Temporary files and other supporting resources should be deleted/released immediately after they are no longer needed."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/459.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Incomplete Cleanup",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-404"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-460",
              "name": "ImproperCleanupOnThrownException",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not clean up its state or incorrectly cleans up its state when an exception is thrown, leading to unexpected state or control flow."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Often, when functions or loops become complicated, some level of resource cleanup is needed throughout execution. Exceptions can disturb the flow of the code and prevent the necessary cleanup from happening."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not clean up its state or incorrectly cleans up its state when an exception is thrown, leading to unexpected state or control flow.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not clean up its state or incorrectly cleans up its state when an exception is thrown, leading to unexpected state or control flow.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nOften, when functions or loops become complicated, some level of resource cleanup is needed throughout execution. Exceptions can disturb the flow of the code and prevent the necessary cleanup from happening.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Varies by Context.\n  - The code could be left in a bad state.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. If one breaks from a loop or function by throwing an exception, make sure that cleanup happens or that you should exit the program. Use throwing exceptions sparsely."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/460.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Improper Cleanup on Thrown Exception",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-459"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-462",
              "name": "DuplicateKeyInAssociativeListAlist",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Duplicate keys in associative lists can lead to non-unique keys being mistaken for an error."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "A duplicate key entry -- if the alist is designed properly -- could be used as a constant time replace function. However, duplicate key entries could be inserted by mistake. Because of this ambiguity, duplicate key entries in an association list are not recommended and should not be allowed."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Duplicate keys in associative lists can lead to non-unique keys being mistaken for an error.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nDuplicate keys in associative lists can lead to non-unique keys being mistaken for an error.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nA duplicate key entry -- if the alist is designed properly -- could be used as a constant time replace function. However, duplicate key entries could be inserted by mistake. Because of this ambiguity, duplicate key entries in an association list are not recommended and should not be allowed.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation, Varies by Context.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Use a hash table instead of an alist.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Use an alist which checks the uniqueness of hash keys with each entry before inserting the entry."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/462.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Duplicate Key in Associative List (Alist)",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-694"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-463",
              "name": "DeletionOfDataStructureSentinel",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The accidental deletion of a data-structure sentinel can cause serious programming logic problems."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Often times data-structure sentinels are used to mark structure of the data structure. A common example of this is the null character at the end of strings. Another common example is linked lists which may contain a sentinel to mark the end of the list. It is dangerous to allow this type of control data to be easily accessible. Therefore, it is important to protect from the deletion or modification outside of some wrapper interface which provides safety."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The accidental deletion of a data-structure sentinel can cause serious programming logic problems.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe accidental deletion of a data-structure sentinel can cause serious programming logic problems.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nOften times data-structure sentinels are used to mark structure of the data structure. A common example of this is the null character at the end of strings. Another common example is linked lists which may contain a sentinel to mark the end of the list. It is dangerous to allow this type of control data to be easily accessible. Therefore, it is important to protect from the deletion or modification outside of some wrapper interface which provides safety.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Availability, Other. **Impact**: Other.\n  - Generally this error will cause the data structure to not work properly.\n- **Scope**: Authorization, Other. **Impact**: Other.\n  - If a control character, such as NULL is removed, one may cause resource access control problems.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Use an abstraction library to abstract away risky APIs. Not a complete solution.\n2. *Phase: Build and Compilation; Strategy: Compilation or Build Hardening*. Run or compile the software using features or extensions that automatically provide a protection mechanism that mitigates or eliminates buffer overflows. For example, certain compilers and extensions provide automatic buffer overflow detection mechanisms that are built into the compiled code. Examples include the Microsoft Visual Studio /GS flag, Fedora/Red Hat FORTIFY_SOURCE GCC flag, StackGuard, and ProPolice.\n3. *Phase: Operation*. Use OS-level preventative functionality. Not a complete solution."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/463.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Deletion of Data Structure Sentinel",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-707"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-464",
              "name": "AdditionOfDataStructureSentinel",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The accidental addition of a data-structure sentinel can cause serious programming logic problems."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Data-structure sentinels are often used to mark the structure of data. A common example of this is the null character at the end of strings or a special sentinel to mark the end of a linked list. It is dangerous to allow this type of control data to be easily accessible. Therefore, it is important to protect from the addition or modification of sentinels."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The accidental addition of a data-structure sentinel can cause serious programming logic problems.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe accidental addition of a data-structure sentinel can cause serious programming logic problems.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nData-structure sentinels are often used to mark the structure of data. A common example of this is the null character at the end of strings or a special sentinel to mark the end of a linked list. It is dangerous to allow this type of control data to be easily accessible. Therefore, it is important to protect from the addition or modification of sentinels.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Modify Application Data.\n  - Generally this error will cause the data structure to not work properly by truncating the data.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation, Architecture and Design*. Encapsulate the user from interacting with data sentinels. Validate user input to verify that sentinels are not present.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Proper error checking can reduce the risk of inadvertently introducing sentinel values into data. For example, if a parsing function fails or encounters an error, it might return a value that is the same as the sentinel.\n3. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Use an abstraction library to abstract away risky APIs. This is not a complete solution.\n4. *Phase: Operation*. Use OS-level preventative functionality. This is not a complete solution."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/464.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Addition of Data Structure Sentinel",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-138"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-466",
              "name": "ReturnOfPointerValueOutsideOfExpectedRange",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A function can return a pointer to memory that is outside of the buffer that the pointer is expected to reference."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "A function can return a pointer to memory that is outside of the buffer that the pointer is expected to reference.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA function can return a pointer to memory that is outside of the buffer that the pointer is expected to reference.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity. **Impact**: Read Memory, Modify Memory."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/466.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Return of Pointer Value Outside of Expected Range",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-119"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-467",
              "name": "UseOfSizeofOnAPointerType",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The code calls sizeof() on a pointer type, which can be an incorrect calculation if the programmer intended to determine the size of the data that is being pointed to."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The use of sizeof() on a pointer can sometimes generate useful information. An obvious case is to find out the wordsize on a platform. More often than not, the appearance of sizeof(pointer) indicates a bug."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The code calls sizeof() on a pointer type, which can be an incorrect calculation if the programmer intended to determine the size of the data that is being pointed to.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code calls sizeof() on a pointer type, which can be an incorrect calculation if the programmer intended to determine the size of the data that is being pointed to.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThe use of sizeof() on a pointer can sometimes generate useful information. An obvious case is to find out the wordsize on a platform. More often than not, the appearance of sizeof(pointer) indicates a bug.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Confidentiality. **Impact**: Modify Memory, Read Memory.\n  - This error can often cause one to allocate a buffer that is much smaller than what is needed, leading to resultant weaknesses such as buffer overflows.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Use expressions such as \"sizeof(*pointer)\" instead of \"sizeof(pointer)\", unless you intend to run sizeof() on a pointer type to gain some platform independence or if you are allocating a variable on the stack."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/467.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Use of sizeof() on a Pointer Type",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-131"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-468",
              "name": "IncorrectPointerScaling",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "In C and C++, one may often accidentally refer to the wrong memory due to the semantics of when math operations are implicitly scaled."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "In C and C++, one may often accidentally refer to the wrong memory due to the semantics of when math operations are implicitly scaled.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn C and C++, one may often accidentally refer to the wrong memory due to the semantics of when math operations are implicitly scaled.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity. **Impact**: Read Memory, Modify Memory.\n  - Incorrect pointer scaling will often result in buffer overflow conditions. Confidentiality can be compromised if the weakness is in the context of a buffer over-read or under-read.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Use a platform with high-level memory abstractions.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Always use array indexing instead of direct pointer manipulation.\n3. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Use technologies for preventing buffer overflows."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/468.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Incorrect Pointer Scaling",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-682"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-469",
              "name": "UseOfPointerSubtractionToDetermineSize",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product subtracts one pointer from another in order to determine size, but this calculation can be incorrect if the pointers do not exist in the same memory chunk."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product subtracts one pointer from another in order to determine size, but this calculation can be incorrect if the pointers do not exist in the same memory chunk.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product subtracts one pointer from another in order to determine size, but this calculation can be incorrect if the pointers do not exist in the same memory chunk.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control, Integrity, Confidentiality, Availability. **Impact**: Modify Memory, Read Memory, Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands, Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n  - There is the potential for arbitrary code execution with privileges of the vulnerable program.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Save an index variable. This is the recommended solution. Rather than subtract pointers from one another, use an index variable of the same size as the pointers in question. Use this variable to \"walk\" from one pointer to the other and calculate the difference. Always validate this number."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/469.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Use of Pointer Subtraction to Determine Size",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-682"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-470",
              "name": "UnsafeReflection",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses external input with reflection to select which classes or code to use, but it does not sufficiently prevent the input from selecting improper classes or code."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "If the product uses external inputs to determine which class to instantiate or which method to invoke, then an attacker could supply values to select unexpected classes or methods. If this occurs, then the attacker could create control flow paths that were not intended by the developer. These paths could bypass authentication or access control checks, or otherwise cause the product to behave in an unexpected manner. This situation becomes a doomsday scenario if the attacker can upload files into a location that appears on the product's classpath (CWE-427) or add new entries to the product's classpath (CWE-426). Under either of these conditions, the attacker can use reflection to introduce new, malicious behavior into the product."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses external input with reflection to select which classes or code to use, but it does not sufficiently prevent the input from selecting improper classes or code.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses external input with reflection to select which classes or code to use, but it does not sufficiently prevent the input from selecting improper classes or code.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIf the product uses external inputs to determine which class to instantiate or which method to invoke, then an attacker could supply values to select unexpected classes or methods. If this occurs, then the attacker could create control flow paths that were not intended by the developer. These paths could bypass authentication or access control checks, or otherwise cause the product to behave in an unexpected manner. This situation becomes a doomsday scenario if the attacker can upload files into a location that appears on the product's classpath (CWE-427) or add new entries to the product's classpath (CWE-426). Under either of these conditions, the attacker can use reflection to introduce new, malicious behavior into the product.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Confidentiality, Availability, Other. **Impact**: Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands, Alter Execution Logic.\n  - The attacker might be able to execute code that is not directly accessible to the attacker. Alternately, the attacker could call unexpected code in the wrong place or the wrong time, possibly modifying critical system state.\n- **Scope**: Availability, Other. **Impact**: DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart, Other.\n  - The attacker might be able to use reflection to call the wrong code, possibly with unexpected arguments that violate the API (CWE-227). This could cause the product to exit or hang.\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - By causing the wrong code to be invoked, the attacker might be able to trigger a runtime error that leaks sensitive information in the error message, such as CWE-536.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Refactor your code to avoid using reflection.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Do not use user-controlled inputs to select and load classes or code.\n3. *Phase: Implementation*. Apply strict input validation by using allowlists or indirect selection to ensure that the user is only selecting allowable classes or code."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/470.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Use of Externally-Controlled Input to Select Classes or Code ('Unsafe Reflection')",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-913"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-471",
              "name": "ModificationOfAssumedImmutableDataMaid",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not properly protect an assumed-immutable element from being modified by an attacker."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "This occurs when a particular input is critical enough to the functioning of the application that it should not be modifiable at all, but it is. Certain resources are often assumed to be immutable when they are not, such as hidden form fields in web applications, cookies, and reverse DNS lookups."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not properly protect an assumed-immutable element from being modified by an attacker.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not properly protect an assumed-immutable element from being modified by an attacker.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThis occurs when a particular input is critical enough to the functioning of the application that it should not be modifiable at all, but it is. Certain resources are often assumed to be immutable when they are not, such as hidden form fields in web applications, cookies, and reverse DNS lookups.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Modify Application Data.\n  - Common data types that are attacked are environment variables, web application parameters, and HTTP headers.\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Unexpected State.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Operation, Implementation*. When the data is stored or transmitted through untrusted sources that could modify the data, implement integrity checks to detect unauthorized modification, or store/transmit the data in a trusted location that is free from external influence."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/471.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Modification of Assumed-Immutable Data (MAID)",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-664"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-472",
              "name": "ExternalControlOfAssumedImmutableWebParameter",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The web application does not sufficiently verify inputs that are assumed to be immutable but are actually externally controllable, such as hidden form fields."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "If a web product does not properly protect assumed-immutable values from modification in hidden form fields, parameters, cookies, or URLs, this can lead to modification of critical data. Web applications often mistakenly make the assumption that data passed to the client in hidden fields or cookies is not susceptible to tampering. Improper validation of data that are user-controllable can lead to the application processing incorrect, and often malicious, input. For example, custom cookies commonly store session data or persistent data across sessions. This kind of session data is normally involved in security related decisions on the server side, such as user authentication and access control. Thus, the cookies might contain sensitive data such as user credentials and privileges. This is a dangerous practice, as it can often lead to improper reliance on the value of the client-provided cookie by the server side application."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The web application does not sufficiently verify inputs that are assumed to be immutable but are actually externally controllable, such as hidden form fields.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe web application does not sufficiently verify inputs that are assumed to be immutable but are actually externally controllable, such as hidden form fields.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIf a web product does not properly protect assumed-immutable values from modification in hidden form fields, parameters, cookies, or URLs, this can lead to modification of critical data. Web applications often mistakenly make the assumption that data passed to the client in hidden fields or cookies is not susceptible to tampering. Improper validation of data that are user-controllable can lead to the application processing incorrect, and often malicious, input. For example, custom cookies commonly store session data or persistent data across sessions. This kind of session data is normally involved in security related decisions on the server side, such as user authentication and access control. Thus, the cookies might contain sensitive data such as user credentials and privileges. This is a dangerous practice, as it can often lead to improper reliance on the value of the client-provided cookie by the server side application.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Modify Application Data.\n  - Without appropriate protection mechanisms, the client can easily tamper with cookies and similar web data. Reliance on the cookies without detailed validation can lead to problems such as SQL injection. If you use cookie values for security related decisions on the server side, manipulating the cookies might lead to violations of security policies such as authentication bypassing, user impersonation and privilege escalation. In addition, storing sensitive data in the cookie without appropriate protection can also lead to disclosure of sensitive user data, especially data stored in persistent cookies.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation; Strategy: Input Validation*. Assume all input is malicious. Use an \"accept known good\" input validation strategy, i.e., use a list of acceptable inputs that strictly conform to specifications. Reject any input that does not strictly conform to specifications, or transform it into something that does. When performing input validation, consider all potentially relevant properties, including length, type of input, the full range of acceptable values, missing or extra inputs, syntax, consistency across related fields, and conformance to business rules. As an example of business rule logic, \"boat\" may be syntactically valid because it only contains alphanumeric characters, but it is not valid if the input is only expected to contain colors such as \"red\" or \"blue.\" Do not rely exclusively on looking for malicious or malformed inputs. This is likely to miss at least one undesirable input, especially if the code's environment changes. This can give attackers enough room to bypass the intended validation. However, denylists can be useful for detecting potential attacks or determining which inputs are so malformed that they should be rejected outright.\n2. *Phase: Implementation; Strategy: Input Validation*. Inputs should be decoded and canonicalized to the application's current internal representation before being validated (CWE-180). Make sure that the application does not decode the same input twice (CWE-174). Such errors could be used to bypass allowlist validation schemes by introducing dangerous inputs after they have been checked."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/472.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "External Control of Assumed-Immutable Web Parameter",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-642"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-473",
              "name": "PhpExternalVariableModification",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A PHP application does not properly protect against the modification of variables from external sources, such as query parameters or cookies."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "A PHP application does not properly protect against the modification of variables from external sources, such as query parameters or cookies. This can expose the application to numerous weaknesses that would not exist otherwise.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA PHP application does not properly protect against the modification of variables from external sources, such as query parameters or cookies. This can expose the application to numerous weaknesses that would not exist otherwise.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Modify Application Data.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Requirements, Implementation*. Carefully identify which variables can be controlled or influenced by an external user, and consider adopting a naming convention to emphasize when externally modifiable variables are being used. An application should be reluctant to trust variables that have been initialized outside of its trust boundary. Ensure adequate checking is performed when relying on input from outside a trust boundary. Do not allow your application to run with register_globals enabled. If you implement a register_globals emulator, be extremely careful of variable extraction, dynamic evaluation, and similar issues, since weaknesses in your emulation could allow external variable modification to take place even without register_globals."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/473.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "PHP External Variable Modification",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-471"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-474",
              "name": "UseOfFunctionWithInconsistentImplementations",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The code uses a function that has inconsistent implementations across operating systems and versions."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The use of inconsistent implementations can cause changes in behavior when the code is ported or built under a different environment than the programmer expects, which can lead to security problems in some cases. The implementation of many functions varies by platform, and at times, even by different versions of the same platform. Implementation differences can include: Slight differences in the way parameters are interpreted leading to inconsistent results. Some implementations of the function carry significant security risks. The function might not be defined on all platforms. The function might change which return codes it can provide, or change the meaning of its return codes."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The code uses a function that has inconsistent implementations across operating systems and versions.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code uses a function that has inconsistent implementations across operating systems and versions.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThe use of inconsistent implementations can cause changes in behavior when the code is ported or built under a different environment than the programmer expects, which can lead to security problems in some cases. The implementation of many functions varies by platform, and at times, even by different versions of the same platform. Implementation differences can include: Slight differences in the way parameters are interpreted leading to inconsistent results. Some implementations of the function carry significant security risks. The function might not be defined on all platforms. The function might change which return codes it can provide, or change the meaning of its return codes.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation, Varies by Context.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Requirements*. Do not accept inconsistent behavior from the API specifications when the deviant behavior increase the risk level."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/474.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Use of Function with Inconsistent Implementations",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-758"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-475",
              "name": "UndefinedBehaviorForInputToApi",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The behavior of this function is undefined unless its control parameter is set to a specific value."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The behavior of this function is undefined unless its control parameter is set to a specific value.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe behavior of this function is undefined unless its control parameter is set to a specific value.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation, Varies by Context."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/475.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Undefined Behavior for Input to API",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-573"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-476",
              "name": "NullPointerDereference",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product dereferences a pointer that it expects to be valid but is NULL."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product dereferences a pointer that it expects to be valid but is NULL.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product dereferences a pointer that it expects to be valid but is NULL.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart.\n  - NULL pointer dereferences usually result in the failure of the process unless exception handling (on some platforms) is available and implemented. Even when exception handling is being used, it can still be very difficult to return the software to a safe state of operation.\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Confidentiality. **Impact**: Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands, Read Memory, Modify Memory.\n  - In rare circumstances, when NULL is equivalent to the 0x0 memory address and privileged code can access it, then writing or reading memory is possible, which may lead to code execution.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. For any pointers that could have been modified or provided from a function that can return NULL, check the pointer for NULL before use. When working with a multithreaded or otherwise asynchronous environment, ensure that proper locking APIs are used to lock before the check, and unlock when it has finished [REF-1484].\n2. *Phase: Requirements*. Select a programming language that is not susceptible to these issues.\n3. *Phase: Implementation*. Check the results of all functions that return a value and verify that the value is non-null before acting upon it.\n4. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Identify all variables and data stores that receive information from external sources, and apply input validation to make sure that they are only initialized to expected values.\n5. *Phase: Implementation*. Explicitly initialize all variables and other data stores, either during declaration or just before the first usage."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "NULL Pointer Dereference",
                "cwe/status": "Stable",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-710"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-477",
              "name": "UseOfObsoleteFunction",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The code uses deprecated or obsolete functions, which suggests that the code has not been actively reviewed or maintained."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "As programming languages evolve, functions occasionally become obsolete due to: Advances in the language Improved understanding of how operations should be performed effectively and securely Changes in the conventions that govern certain operations Functions that are removed are usually replaced by newer counterparts that perform the same task in some different and hopefully improved way."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The code uses deprecated or obsolete functions, which suggests that the code has not been actively reviewed or maintained.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code uses deprecated or obsolete functions, which suggests that the code has not been actively reviewed or maintained.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nAs programming languages evolve, functions occasionally become obsolete due to: Advances in the language Improved understanding of how operations should be performed effectively and securely Changes in the conventions that govern certain operations Functions that are removed are usually replaced by newer counterparts that perform the same task in some different and hopefully improved way.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Refer to the documentation for the obsolete function in order to determine why it is deprecated or obsolete and to learn about alternative ways to achieve the same functionality.\n2. *Phase: Requirements*. Consider seriously the security implications of using an obsolete function. Consider using alternate functions."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/477.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Use of Obsolete Function",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-710"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-478",
              "name": "MissingDefaultCaseInMultipleConditionExpression",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The code does not have a default case in an expression with multiple conditions, such as a switch statement."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "If a multiple-condition expression (such as a switch in C) omits the default case but does not consider or handle all possible values that could occur, then this might lead to complex logical errors and resultant weaknesses. Because of this, further decisions are made based on poor information, and cascading failure results. This cascading failure may result in any number of security issues, and constitutes a significant failure in the system."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The code does not have a default case in an expression with multiple conditions, such as a switch statement.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code does not have a default case in an expression with multiple conditions, such as a switch statement.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIf a multiple-condition expression (such as a switch in C) omits the default case but does not consider or handle all possible values that could occur, then this might lead to complex logical errors and resultant weaknesses. Because of this, further decisions are made based on poor information, and cascading failure results. This cascading failure may result in any number of security issues, and constitutes a significant failure in the system.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Varies by Context, Alter Execution Logic.\n  - Depending on the logical circumstances involved, any consequences may result: e.g., issues of confidentiality, authentication, authorization, availability, integrity, accountability, or non-repudiation.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Ensure that there are no cases unaccounted for when adjusting program flow or values based on the value of a given variable. In the case of switch style statements, the very simple act of creating a default case can, if done correctly, mitigate this situation. Often however, the default case is used simply to represent an assumed option, as opposed to working as a check for invalid input. This is poor practice and in some cases is as bad as omitting a default case entirely."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/478.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Missing Default Case in Multiple Condition Expression",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-1023"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-479",
              "name": "SignalHandlerUseOfANonReentrantFunction",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product defines a signal handler that calls a non-reentrant function."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Non-reentrant functions are functions that cannot safely be called, interrupted, and then recalled before the first call has finished without resulting in memory corruption. This can lead to an unexpected system state and unpredictable results with a variety of potential consequences depending on context, including denial of service and code execution. Many functions are not reentrant, but some of them can result in the corruption of memory if they are used in a signal handler. The function call syslog() is an example of this. In order to perform its functionality, it allocates a small amount of memory as \"scratch space.\" If syslog() is suspended by a signal call and the signal handler calls syslog(), the memory used by both of these functions enters an undefined, and possibly, exploitable state. Implementations of malloc() and free() manage metadata in global structures in order to track which memory is allocated versus which memory is available, but they are non-reentrant. Simultaneous calls to these functions can cause corruption of the metadata."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product defines a signal handler that calls a non-reentrant function.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product defines a signal handler that calls a non-reentrant function.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nNon-reentrant functions are functions that cannot safely be called, interrupted, and then recalled before the first call has finished without resulting in memory corruption. This can lead to an unexpected system state and unpredictable results with a variety of potential consequences depending on context, including denial of service and code execution. Many functions are not reentrant, but some of them can result in the corruption of memory if they are used in a signal handler. The function call syslog() is an example of this. In order to perform its functionality, it allocates a small amount of memory as \"scratch space.\" If syslog() is suspended by a signal call and the signal handler calls syslog(), the memory used by both of these functions enters an undefined, and possibly, exploitable state. Implementations of malloc() and free() manage metadata in global structures in order to track which memory is allocated versus which memory is available, but they are non-reentrant. Simultaneous calls to these functions can cause corruption of the metadata.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Confidentiality, Availability. **Impact**: Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands.\n  - It may be possible to execute arbitrary code through the use of a write-what-where condition.\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Modify Memory, Modify Application Data.\n  - Signal race conditions often result in data corruption.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Requirements*. Require languages or libraries that provide reentrant functionality, or otherwise make it easier to avoid this weakness.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Design signal handlers to only set flags rather than perform complex functionality.\n3. *Phase: Implementation*. Ensure that non-reentrant functions are not found in signal handlers.\n4. *Phase: Implementation*. Use sanity checks to reduce the timing window for exploitation of race conditions. This is only a partial solution, since many attacks might fail, but other attacks still might work within the narrower window, even accidentally."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/479.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Signal Handler Use of a Non-reentrant Function",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-828"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-480",
              "name": "UseOfIncorrectOperator",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product accidentally uses the wrong operator, which changes the logic in security-relevant ways."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "These types of errors are generally the result of a typo by the programmer."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product accidentally uses the wrong operator, which changes the logic in security-relevant ways.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product accidentally uses the wrong operator, which changes the logic in security-relevant ways.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThese types of errors are generally the result of a typo by the programmer.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Alter Execution Logic.\n  - This weakness can cause unintended logic to be executed and other unexpected application behavior."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/480.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Use of Incorrect Operator",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-670"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-481",
              "name": "AssigningInsteadOfComparing",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The code uses an operator for assignment when the intention was to perform a comparison."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In many languages the compare statement is very close in appearance to the assignment statement and are often confused. This bug is generally the result of a typo and usually causes obvious problems with program execution. If the comparison is in an if statement, the if statement will usually evaluate the value of the right-hand side of the predicate."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The code uses an operator for assignment when the intention was to perform a comparison.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code uses an operator for assignment when the intention was to perform a comparison.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIn many languages the compare statement is very close in appearance to the assignment statement and are often confused. This bug is generally the result of a typo and usually causes obvious problems with program execution. If the comparison is in an if statement, the if statement will usually evaluate the value of the right-hand side of the predicate.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Alter Execution Logic.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Place constants on the left. If one attempts to assign a constant with a variable, the compiler will produce an error."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/481.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Assigning instead of Comparing",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-480"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-482",
              "name": "ComparingInsteadOfAssigning",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The code uses an operator for comparison when the intention was to perform an assignment."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In many languages, the compare statement is very close in appearance to the assignment statement; they are often confused."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The code uses an operator for comparison when the intention was to perform an assignment.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code uses an operator for comparison when the intention was to perform an assignment.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIn many languages, the compare statement is very close in appearance to the assignment statement; they are often confused.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Availability, Integrity. **Impact**: Unexpected State.\n  - The assignment will not take place, which should cause obvious program execution problems.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Testing*. Many IDEs and static analysis products will detect this problem."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/482.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Comparing instead of Assigning",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-480"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-483",
              "name": "IncorrectBlockDelimitation",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The code does not explicitly delimit a block that is intended to contain 2 or more statements, creating a logic error."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In some languages, braces (or other delimiters) are optional for blocks. When the delimiter is omitted, it is possible to insert a logic error in which a statement is thought to be in a block but is not. In some cases, the logic error can have security implications."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The code does not explicitly delimit a block that is intended to contain 2 or more statements, creating a logic error.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code does not explicitly delimit a block that is intended to contain 2 or more statements, creating a logic error.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIn some languages, braces (or other delimiters) are optional for blocks. When the delimiter is omitted, it is possible to insert a logic error in which a statement is thought to be in a block but is not. In some cases, the logic error can have security implications.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability. **Impact**: Alter Execution Logic.\n  - This is a general logic error which will often lead to obviously-incorrect behaviors that are quickly noticed and fixed. In lightly tested or untested code, this error may be introduced it into a production environment and provide additional attack vectors by creating a control flow path leading to an unexpected state in the application. The consequences will depend on the types of behaviors that are being incorrectly executed.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Always use explicit block delimitation and use static-analysis technologies to enforce this practice."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/483.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Incorrect Block Delimitation",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-670"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-484",
              "name": "OmittedBreakStatementInSwitch",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product omits a break statement within a switch or similar construct, causing code associated with multiple conditions to execute."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "This can lead to critical code executing in situations where it should not."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product omits a break statement within a switch or similar construct, causing code associated with multiple conditions to execute. This can cause problems when the programmer only intended to execute code associated with one condition.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product omits a break statement within a switch or similar construct, causing code associated with multiple conditions to execute. This can cause problems when the programmer only intended to execute code associated with one condition.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThis can lead to critical code executing in situations where it should not.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Alter Execution Logic.\n  - This weakness can cause unintended logic to be executed and other unexpected application behavior.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Omitting a break statement so that one may fall through is often indistinguishable from an error, and therefore should be avoided. If you need to use fall-through capabilities, make sure that you have clearly documented this within the switch statement, and ensure that you have examined all the logical possibilities.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. The functionality of omitting a break statement could be clarified with an if statement. This method is much safer."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/484.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Omitted Break Statement in Switch",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-710"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-486",
              "name": "ComparisonOfClassesByName",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product compares classes by name, which can cause it to use the wrong class when multiple classes can have the same name."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "If the decision to trust the methods and data of an object is based on the name of a class, it is possible for malicious users to send objects of the same name as trusted classes and thereby gain the trust afforded to known classes and types."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product compares classes by name, which can cause it to use the wrong class when multiple classes can have the same name.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product compares classes by name, which can cause it to use the wrong class when multiple classes can have the same name.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIf the decision to trust the methods and data of an object is based on the name of a class, it is possible for malicious users to send objects of the same name as trusted classes and thereby gain the trust afforded to known classes and types.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Confidentiality, Availability. **Impact**: Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands.\n  - If a product relies solely on the name of an object to determine identity, it may execute the incorrect or unintended code.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Use class equivalency to determine type. Rather than use the class name to determine if an object is of a given type, use the getClass() method, and == operator."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/486.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Comparison of Classes by Name",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-1025"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-487",
              "name": "RelianceOnPackageLevelScope",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Java packages are not inherently closed; therefore, relying on them for code security is not a good practice."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The purpose of package scope is to prevent accidental access by other parts of a program. This is an ease-of-software-development feature but not a security feature."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Java packages are not inherently closed; therefore, relying on them for code security is not a good practice.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nJava packages are not inherently closed; therefore, relying on them for code security is not a good practice.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThe purpose of package scope is to prevent accidental access by other parts of a program. This is an ease-of-software-development feature but not a security feature.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - Any data in a Java package can be accessed outside of the Java framework if the package is distributed.\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Modify Application Data.\n  - The data in a Java class can be modified by anyone outside of the Java framework if the package is distributed.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Implementation*. Data should be private static and final whenever possible. This will assure that your code is protected by instantiating early, preventing access and tampering."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/487.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Reliance on Package-level Scope",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-664"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-488",
              "name": "ExposureOfDataElementToWrongSession",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not sufficiently enforce boundaries between the states of different sessions, causing data to be provided to, or used by, the wrong session."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Data can \"bleed\" from one session to another through member variables of singleton objects, such as Servlets, and objects from a shared pool. In the case of Servlets, developers sometimes do not understand that, unless a Servlet implements the SingleThreadModel interface, the Servlet is a singleton; there is only one instance of the Servlet, and that single instance is used and re-used to handle multiple requests that are processed simultaneously by different threads. A common result is that developers use Servlet member fields in such a way that one user may inadvertently see another user's data. In other words, storing user data in Servlet member fields introduces a data access race condition."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not sufficiently enforce boundaries between the states of different sessions, causing data to be provided to, or used by, the wrong session.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not sufficiently enforce boundaries between the states of different sessions, causing data to be provided to, or used by, the wrong session.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nData can \"bleed\" from one session to another through member variables of singleton objects, such as Servlets, and objects from a shared pool. In the case of Servlets, developers sometimes do not understand that, unless a Servlet implements the SingleThreadModel interface, the Servlet is a singleton; there is only one instance of the Servlet, and that single instance is used and re-used to handle multiple requests that are processed simultaneously by different threads. A common result is that developers use Servlet member fields in such a way that one user may inadvertently see another user's data. In other words, storing user data in Servlet member fields introduces a data access race condition.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Protect the application's sessions from information leakage. Make sure that a session's data is not used or visible by other sessions.\n2. *Phase: Testing*. Use a static analysis tool to scan the code for information leakage vulnerabilities (e.g. Singleton Member Field).\n3. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. In a multithreading environment, storing user data in Servlet member fields introduces a data access race condition. Do not use member fields to store information in the Servlet."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/488.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Exposure of Data Element to Wrong Session",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-668"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-489",
              "name": "ActiveDebugCode",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product is released with debugging code still enabled or active."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product is released with debugging code still enabled or active.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product is released with debugging code still enabled or active.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability, Access Control, Other. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism, Read Application Data, Gain Privileges or Assume Identity, Varies by Context.\n  - Active debug code can create unintended entry points or expose sensitive information. The severity of the exposed debug code will depend on the particular instance. At the least, it will give an attacker sensitive information about the settings and mechanics of web applications on the server. At worst, as is often the case, the debug code will allow an attacker complete control over the web application and server, as well as confidential information that either of these access.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Build and Compilation, Distribution*. Remove debug code before deploying the application."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Active Debug Code",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-710"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-491",
              "name": "ObjectHijack",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A class has a cloneable() method that is not declared final, which allows an object to be created without calling the constructor."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "A class has a cloneable() method that is not declared final, which allows an object to be created without calling the constructor. This can cause the object to be in an unexpected state.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA class has a cloneable() method that is not declared final, which allows an object to be created without calling the constructor. This can cause the object to be in an unexpected state.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Unexpected State, Varies by Context.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Make the cloneable() method final."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/491.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Public cloneable() Method Without Final ('Object Hijack')",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-668"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-492",
              "name": "UseOfInnerClassContainingSensitiveData",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Inner classes are translated into classes that are accessible at package scope and may expose code that the programmer intended to keep private to attackers."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Inner classes quietly introduce several security concerns because of the way they are translated into Java bytecode. In Java source code, it appears that an inner class can be declared to be accessible only by the enclosing class, but Java bytecode has no concept of an inner class, so the compiler must transform an inner class declaration into a peer class with package level access to the original outer class. More insidiously, since an inner class can access private fields in its enclosing class, once an inner class becomes a peer class in bytecode, the compiler converts private fields accessed by the inner class into protected fields."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Inner classes are translated into classes that are accessible at package scope and may expose code that the programmer intended to keep private to attackers.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInner classes are translated into classes that are accessible at package scope and may expose code that the programmer intended to keep private to attackers.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nInner classes quietly introduce several security concerns because of the way they are translated into Java bytecode. In Java source code, it appears that an inner class can be declared to be accessible only by the enclosing class, but Java bytecode has no concept of an inner class, so the compiler must transform an inner class declaration into a peer class with package level access to the original outer class. More insidiously, since an inner class can access private fields in its enclosing class, once an inner class becomes a peer class in bytecode, the compiler converts private fields accessed by the inner class into protected fields.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - \"Inner Classes\" data confidentiality aspects can often be overcome.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Using sealed classes protects object-oriented encapsulation paradigms and therefore protects code from being extended in unforeseen ways.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Inner Classes do not provide security. Warning: Never reduce the security of the object from an outer class, going to an inner class. If an outer class is final or private, ensure that its inner class is private as well."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/492.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Use of Inner Class Containing Sensitive Data",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-668"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-493",
              "name": "CriticalPublicVariableWithoutFinalModifier",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product has a critical public variable that is not final, which allows the variable to be modified to contain unexpected values."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "If a field is non-final and public, it can be changed once the value is set by any function that has access to the class which contains the field. This could lead to a vulnerability if other parts of the program make assumptions about the contents of that field."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product has a critical public variable that is not final, which allows the variable to be modified to contain unexpected values.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product has a critical public variable that is not final, which allows the variable to be modified to contain unexpected values.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIf a field is non-final and public, it can be changed once the value is set by any function that has access to the class which contains the field. This could lead to a vulnerability if other parts of the program make assumptions about the contents of that field.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Modify Application Data.\n  - The object could potentially be tampered with.\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - The object could potentially allow the object to be read.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Declare all public fields as final when possible, especially if it is used to maintain internal state of an Applet or of classes used by an Applet. If a field must be public, then perform all appropriate sanity checks before accessing the field from your code."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/493.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Critical Public Variable Without Final Modifier",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-668"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-494",
              "name": "DownloadOfCodeWithoutIntegrityCheck",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product downloads source code or an executable from a remote location and executes the code without sufficiently verifying the origin and integrity of the code."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "An attacker can execute malicious code by compromising the host server, performing DNS spoofing, or modifying the code in transit."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product downloads source code or an executable from a remote location and executes the code without sufficiently verifying the origin and integrity of the code.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product downloads source code or an executable from a remote location and executes the code without sufficiently verifying the origin and integrity of the code.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nAn attacker can execute malicious code by compromising the host server, performing DNS spoofing, or modifying the code in transit.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Availability, Confidentiality, Other. **Impact**: Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands, Alter Execution Logic, Other.\n  - Executing untrusted code could compromise the control flow of the program. The untrusted code could execute attacker-controlled commands, read or modify sensitive resources, or prevent the software from functioning correctly for legitimate users.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Perform proper forward and reverse DNS lookups to detect DNS spoofing.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Operation*. Encrypt the code with a reliable encryption scheme before transmitting. This will only be a partial solution, since it will not detect DNS spoofing and it will not prevent your code from being modified on the hosting site.\n3. *Phase: Architecture and Design; Strategy: Libraries or Frameworks*. Use a vetted library or framework that does not allow this weakness to occur or provides constructs that make this weakness easier to avoid [REF-1482]. Speficially, it may be helpful to use tools or frameworks to perform integrity checking on the transmitted code. When providing the code that is to be downloaded, such as for automatic updates of the software, then use cryptographic signatures for the code and modify the download clients to verify the signatures. Ensure that the implementation does not contain CWE-295, CWE-320, CWE-347, and related weaknesses. Use code signing technologies such as Authenticode. See references [REF-454] [REF-455] [REF-456].\n4. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Operation; Strategy: Environment Hardening*. Run your code using the lowest privileges that are required to accomplish the necessary tasks [REF-76]. If possible, create isolated accounts with limited privileges that are only used for a single task. That way, a successful attack will not immediately give the attacker access to the rest of the software or its environment. For example, database applications rarely need to run as the database administrator, especially in day-to-day operations.\n5. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Operation; Strategy: Sandbox or Jail*. Run the code in a \"jail\" or similar sandbox environment that enforces strict boundaries between the process and the operating system. This may effectively restrict which files can be accessed in a particular directory or which commands can be executed by the software. OS-level examples include the Unix chroot jail, AppArmor, and SELinux. In general, managed code may provide some protection. For example, java.io.FilePermission in the Java SecurityManager allows the software to specify restrictions on file operations. This may not be a feasible solution, and it only limits the impact to the operating system; the rest of the application may still be subject to compromise. Be careful to avoid CWE-243 and other weaknesses related to jails."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/494.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Download of Code Without Integrity Check",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-345"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-495",
              "name": "PrivateDataStructureReturnedFromAPublicMethod",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product has a method that is declared public, but returns a reference to a private data structure, which could then be modified in unexpected ways."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product has a method that is declared public, but returns a reference to a private data structure, which could then be modified in unexpected ways.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product has a method that is declared public, but returns a reference to a private data structure, which could then be modified in unexpected ways.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Modify Application Data.\n  - The contents of the data structure can be modified from outside the intended scope.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Declare the method private.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Clone the member data and keep an unmodified version of the data private to the object.\n3. *Phase: Implementation*. Use public setter methods that govern how a private member can be modified."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/495.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Private Data Structure Returned From A Public Method",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-664"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-496",
              "name": "PublicDataAssignedToPrivateArrayTypedField",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Assigning public data to a private array is equivalent to giving public access to the array."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Assigning public data to a private array is equivalent to giving public access to the array.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nAssigning public data to a private array is equivalent to giving public access to the array.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Modify Application Data.\n  - The contents of the array can be modified from outside the intended scope.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Do not allow objects to modify private members of a class."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/496.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Public Data Assigned to Private Array-Typed Field",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-664"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-497",
              "name": "ExposureOfSensitiveSystemInformationToAnUnauthorizedControlSphere",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not properly prevent sensitive system-level information from being accessed by unauthorized actors who do not have the same level of access to the underlying system as the product does."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Network-based products, such as web applications, often run on top of an operating system or similar environment. When the product communicates with outside parties, details about the underlying system are expected to remain hidden, such as path names for data files, other OS users, installed packages, the application environment, etc. This system information may be provided by the product itself, or buried within diagnostic or debugging messages. Debugging information helps an adversary learn about the system and form an attack plan. An information exposure occurs when system data or debugging information leaves the program through an output stream or logging function that makes it accessible to unauthorized parties. Using other weaknesses, an attacker could cause errors to occur; the response to these errors can reveal detailed system information, along with other impacts. An attacker can use messages that reveal technologies, operating systems, and product versions to tune the attack against known vulnerabilities in these technologies. A product may use diagnostic methods that provide significant implementation details such as stack traces as part of its error handling mechanism."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not properly prevent sensitive system-level information from being accessed by unauthorized actors who do not have the same level of access to the underlying system as the product does.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not properly prevent sensitive system-level information from being accessed by unauthorized actors who do not have the same level of access to the underlying system as the product does.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nNetwork-based products, such as web applications, often run on top of an operating system or similar environment. When the product communicates with outside parties, details about the underlying system are expected to remain hidden, such as path names for data files, other OS users, installed packages, the application environment, etc. This system information may be provided by the product itself, or buried within diagnostic or debugging messages. Debugging information helps an adversary learn about the system and form an attack plan. An information exposure occurs when system data or debugging information leaves the program through an output stream or logging function that makes it accessible to unauthorized parties. Using other weaknesses, an attacker could cause errors to occur; the response to these errors can reveal detailed system information, along with other impacts. An attacker can use messages that reveal technologies, operating systems, and product versions to tune the attack against known vulnerabilities in these technologies. A product may use diagnostic methods that provide significant implementation details such as stack traces as part of its error handling mechanism.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Implementation*. Production applications should never use methods that generate internal details such as stack traces and error messages unless that information is directly committed to a log that is not viewable by the end user. All error message text should be HTML entity encoded before being written to the log file to protect against potential cross-site scripting attacks against the viewer of the logs"
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/497.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Exposure of Sensitive System Information to an Unauthorized Control Sphere",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-200"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-498",
              "name": "CloneableClassContainingSensitiveInformation",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The code contains a class with sensitive data, but the class is cloneable."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Cloneable classes are effectively open classes, since data cannot be hidden in them. Classes that do not explicitly deny cloning can be cloned by any other class without running the constructor."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The code contains a class with sensitive data, but the class is cloneable. The data can then be accessed by cloning the class.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code contains a class with sensitive data, but the class is cloneable. The data can then be accessed by cloning the class.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nCloneable classes are effectively open classes, since data cannot be hidden in them. Classes that do not explicitly deny cloning can be cloned by any other class without running the constructor.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism.\n  - A class that can be cloned can be produced without executing the constructor. This is dangerous since the constructor may perform security-related checks. By allowing the object to be cloned, those checks may be bypassed.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. If you do make your classes clonable, ensure that your clone method is final and throw super.clone()."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/498.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Cloneable Class Containing Sensitive Information",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-668"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-499",
              "name": "SerializableClassContainingSensitiveData",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The code contains a class with sensitive data, but the class does not explicitly deny serialization."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Serializable classes are effectively open classes since data cannot be hidden in them. Classes that do not explicitly deny serialization can be serialized by any other class, which can then in turn use the data stored inside it."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The code contains a class with sensitive data, but the class does not explicitly deny serialization. The data can be accessed by serializing the class through another class.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code contains a class with sensitive data, but the class does not explicitly deny serialization. The data can be accessed by serializing the class through another class.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nSerializable classes are effectively open classes since data cannot be hidden in them. Classes that do not explicitly deny serialization can be serialized by any other class, which can then in turn use the data stored inside it.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - an attacker can write out the class to a byte stream, then extract the important data from it.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. In Java, explicitly define final writeObject() to prevent serialization. This is the recommended solution. Define the writeObject() function to throw an exception explicitly denying serialization.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Make sure to prevent serialization of your objects."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/499.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Serializable Class Containing Sensitive Data",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-668"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-500",
              "name": "PublicStaticFieldNotMarkedFinal",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "An object contains a public static field that is not marked final, which might allow it to be modified in unexpected ways."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Public static variables can be read without an accessor and changed without a mutator by any classes in the application."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "An object contains a public static field that is not marked final, which might allow it to be modified in unexpected ways.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nAn object contains a public static field that is not marked final, which might allow it to be modified in unexpected ways.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nPublic static variables can be read without an accessor and changed without a mutator by any classes in the application.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Modify Application Data.\n  - The object could potentially be tampered with.\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - The object could potentially allow the object to be read.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Clearly identify the scope for all critical data elements, including whether they should be regarded as static.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Make any static fields private and constant. A constant field is denoted by the keyword 'const' in C/C++ and ' final' in Java"
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/500.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Public Static Field Not Marked Final",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-493"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-501",
              "name": "TrustBoundaryViolation",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product mixes trusted and untrusted data in the same data structure or structured message."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "A trust boundary can be thought of as line drawn through a program. On one side of the line, data is untrusted. On the other side of the line, data is assumed to be trustworthy. The purpose of validation logic is to allow data to safely cross the trust boundary - to move from untrusted to trusted. A trust boundary violation occurs when a program blurs the line between what is trusted and what is untrusted. By combining trusted and untrusted data in the same data structure, it becomes easier for programmers to mistakenly trust unvalidated data."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product mixes trusted and untrusted data in the same data structure or structured message.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product mixes trusted and untrusted data in the same data structure or structured message.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nA trust boundary can be thought of as line drawn through a program. On one side of the line, data is untrusted. On the other side of the line, data is assumed to be trustworthy. The purpose of validation logic is to allow data to safely cross the trust boundary - to move from untrusted to trusted. A trust boundary violation occurs when a program blurs the line between what is trusted and what is untrusted. By combining trusted and untrusted data in the same data structure, it becomes easier for programmers to mistakenly trust unvalidated data.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/501.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Trust Boundary Violation",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-664"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-502",
              "name": "DeserializationOfUntrustedData",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product deserializes untrusted data without sufficiently ensuring that the resulting data will be valid."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product deserializes untrusted data without sufficiently ensuring that the resulting data will be valid.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product deserializes untrusted data without sufficiently ensuring that the resulting data will be valid.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Modify Application Data, Unexpected State.\n  - Attackers can modify unexpected objects or data that was assumed to be safe from modification. Deserialized data or code could be modified without using the provided accessor functions, or unexpected functions could be invoked.\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Resource Consumption (CPU).\n  - If a function is making an assumption on when to terminate, based on a sentry in a string, it could easily never terminate.\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Varies by Context.\n  - The consequences can vary widely, because it depends on which objects or methods are being deserialized, and how they are used. Making an assumption that the code in the deserialized object is valid is dangerous and can enable exploitation. One example is attackers using gadget chains to perform unauthorized actions, such as generating a shell.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Implementation*. If available, use the signing/sealing features of the programming language to assure that deserialized data has not been tainted. For example, a hash-based message authentication code (HMAC) could be used to ensure that data has not been modified.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. When deserializing data, populate a new object rather than just deserializing. The result is that the data flows through safe input validation and that the functions are safe.\n3. *Phase: Implementation*. Explicitly define a final object() to prevent deserialization.\n4. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Implementation*. Make fields transient to protect them from deserialization. An attempt to serialize and then deserialize a class containing transient fields will result in NULLs where the transient data should be. This is an excellent way to prevent time, environment-based, or sensitive variables from being carried over and used improperly.\n5. *Phase: Implementation*. Avoid having unnecessary types or gadgets (a sequence of instances and method invocations that can self-execute during the deserialization process, often found in libraries) available that can be leveraged for malicious ends. This limits the potential for unintended or unauthorized types and gadgets to be leveraged by the attacker. Add only acceptable classes to an allowlist. Note: new gadgets are constantly being discovered, so this alone is not a sufficient mitigation.\n6. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Implementation*. Employ cryptography of the data or code for protection. However, it's important to note that it would still be client-side security. This is risky because if the client is compromised then the security implemented on the client (the cryptography) can be bypassed.\n7. *Phase: Operation; Strategy: Firewall*. Use an application firewall that can detect attacks against this weakness. It can be beneficial in cases in which the code cannot be fixed (because it is controlled by a third party), as an emergency prevention measure while more comprehensive software assurance measures are applied, or to provide defense in depth [REF-1481]."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/502.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Deserialization of Untrusted Data",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-913"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-506",
              "name": "EmbeddedMaliciousCode",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product contains code that appears to be malicious in nature."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Malicious flaws have acquired colorful names, including Trojan horse, trapdoor, timebomb, and logic-bomb. A developer might insert malicious code with the intent to subvert the security of a product or its host system at some time in the future. It generally refers to a program that performs a useful service but exploits rights of the program's user in a way the user does not intend."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product contains code that appears to be malicious in nature.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product contains code that appears to be malicious in nature.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nMalicious flaws have acquired colorful names, including Trojan horse, trapdoor, timebomb, and logic-bomb. A developer might insert malicious code with the intent to subvert the security of a product or its host system at some time in the future. It generally refers to a program that performs a useful service but exploits rights of the program's user in a way the user does not intend.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability. **Impact**: Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation, Operation*. Remove the malicious code and start an effort to ensure that no more malicious code exists. This may require a detailed review of all code, as it is possible to hide a serious attack in only one or two lines of code. These lines may be located almost anywhere in an application and may have been intentionally obfuscated by the attacker."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/506.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Embedded Malicious Code",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-912"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-507",
              "name": "TrojanHorse",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product appears to contain benign or useful functionality, but it also contains code that is hidden from normal operation that violates the intended security policy of the user or the system administrator."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product appears to contain benign or useful functionality, but it also contains code that is hidden from normal operation that violates the intended security policy of the user or the system administrator.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product appears to contain benign or useful functionality, but it also contains code that is hidden from normal operation that violates the intended security policy of the user or the system administrator.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability. **Impact**: Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Operation*. Most antivirus software scans for Trojan Horses.\n2. *Phase: Installation*. Verify the integrity of the product that is being installed."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/507.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Trojan Horse",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-506"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-508",
              "name": "NonReplicatingMaliciousCode",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Non-replicating malicious code only resides on the target system or product that is attacked; it does not attempt to spread to other systems."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Non-replicating malicious code only resides on the target system or product that is attacked; it does not attempt to spread to other systems.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nNon-replicating malicious code only resides on the target system or product that is attacked; it does not attempt to spread to other systems.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability. **Impact**: Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Operation*. Antivirus software can help mitigate known malicious code.\n2. *Phase: Installation*. Verify the integrity of the software that is being installed."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/508.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Non-Replicating Malicious Code",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-507"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-509",
              "name": "ReplicatingMaliciousCodeVirusOrWorm",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Replicating malicious code, including viruses and worms, will attempt to attack other systems once it has successfully compromised the target system or the product."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Replicating malicious code, including viruses and worms, will attempt to attack other systems once it has successfully compromised the target system or the product.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nReplicating malicious code, including viruses and worms, will attempt to attack other systems once it has successfully compromised the target system or the product.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability. **Impact**: Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Operation*. Antivirus software scans for viruses or worms.\n2. *Phase: Installation*. Always verify the integrity of the software that is being installed."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/509.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Replicating Malicious Code (Virus or Worm)",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-507"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-510",
              "name": "Trapdoor",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A trapdoor is a hidden piece of code that responds to a special input, allowing its user access to resources without passing through the normal security enforcement mechanism."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "A trapdoor is a hidden piece of code that responds to a special input, allowing its user access to resources without passing through the normal security enforcement mechanism.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA trapdoor is a hidden piece of code that responds to a special input, allowing its user access to resources without passing through the normal security enforcement mechanism.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability, Access Control. **Impact**: Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands, Bypass Protection Mechanism.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Installation*. Always verify the integrity of the software that is being installed.\n2. *Phase: Testing*. Identify and closely inspect the conditions for entering privileged areas of the code, especially those related to authentication, process invocation, and network communications."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/510.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Trapdoor",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-506"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-511",
              "name": "LogicTimeBomb",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product contains code that is designed to disrupt the legitimate operation of the product (or its environment) when a certain time passes, or when a certain logical condition is met."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "When the time bomb or logic bomb is detonated, it may perform a denial of service such as crashing the system, deleting critical data, or degrading system response time. This bomb might be placed within either a replicating or non-replicating Trojan horse."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product contains code that is designed to disrupt the legitimate operation of the product (or its environment) when a certain time passes, or when a certain logical condition is met.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product contains code that is designed to disrupt the legitimate operation of the product (or its environment) when a certain time passes, or when a certain logical condition is met.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nWhen the time bomb or logic bomb is detonated, it may perform a denial of service such as crashing the system, deleting critical data, or degrading system response time. This bomb might be placed within either a replicating or non-replicating Trojan horse.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other, Integrity. **Impact**: Varies by Context, Alter Execution Logic.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Installation*. Always verify the integrity of the product that is being installed."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/511.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Logic/Time Bomb",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-506"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-512",
              "name": "Spyware",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product collects personally identifiable information about a human user or the user's activities, but the product accesses this information using other resources besides itself, and it does not require that user's explicit approval or direct input into the product."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\"Spyware\" is a commonly used term with many definitions and interpretations. In general, it is meant to refer to products that collect information or install functionality that human users might not allow if they were fully aware of the actions being taken by the software. For example, a user might expect that tax software would collect a social security number and include it when filing a tax return, but that same user would not expect gaming software to obtain the social security number from that tax software's data."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product collects personally identifiable information about a human user or the user's activities, but the product accesses this information using other resources besides itself, and it does not require that user's explicit approval or direct input into the product.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product collects personally identifiable information about a human user or the user's activities, but the product accesses this information using other resources besides itself, and it does not require that user's explicit approval or direct input into the product.\n\n## Extended Description\n\n\"Spyware\" is a commonly used term with many definitions and interpretations. In general, it is meant to refer to products that collect information or install functionality that human users might not allow if they were fully aware of the actions being taken by the software. For example, a user might expect that tax software would collect a social security number and include it when filing a tax return, but that same user would not expect gaming software to obtain the social security number from that tax software's data.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Operation*. Use spyware detection and removal software.\n2. *Phase: Installation*. Always verify the integrity of the product that is being installed."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/512.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Spyware",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-506"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-514",
              "name": "CovertChannel",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A covert channel is a path that can be used to transfer information in a way not intended by the system's designers."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Typically the system has not given authorization for the transmission and has no knowledge of its occurrence."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "A covert channel is a path that can be used to transfer information in a way not intended by the system's designers.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA covert channel is a path that can be used to transfer information in a way not intended by the system's designers.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nTypically the system has not given authorization for the transmission and has no knowledge of its occurrence.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Access Control. **Impact**: Read Application Data, Bypass Protection Mechanism."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/514.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Covert Channel",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-1229"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-515",
              "name": "CovertStorageChannel",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A covert storage channel transfers information through the setting of bits by one program and the reading of those bits by another."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Covert storage channels occur when out-of-band data is stored in messages for the purpose of memory reuse. Covert channels are frequently classified as either storage or timing channels. Examples would include using a file intended to hold only audit information to convey user passwords--using the name of a file or perhaps status bits associated with it that can be read by all users to signal the contents of the file. Steganography, concealing information in such a manner that no one but the intended recipient knows of the existence of the message, is a good example of a covert storage channel."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "A covert storage channel transfers information through the setting of bits by one program and the reading of those bits by another. What distinguishes this case from that of ordinary operation is that the bits are used to convey encoded information.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA covert storage channel transfers information through the setting of bits by one program and the reading of those bits by another. What distinguishes this case from that of ordinary operation is that the bits are used to convey encoded information.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nCovert storage channels occur when out-of-band data is stored in messages for the purpose of memory reuse. Covert channels are frequently classified as either storage or timing channels. Examples would include using a file intended to hold only audit information to convey user passwords--using the name of a file or perhaps status bits associated with it that can be read by all users to signal the contents of the file. Steganography, concealing information in such a manner that no one but the intended recipient knows of the existence of the message, is a good example of a covert storage channel.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - Covert storage channels may provide attackers with important information about the system in question.\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - If these messages or packets are sent with unnecessary data contained within, it may tip off malicious listeners as to the process that created the message. With this information, attackers may learn any number of things, including the hardware platform, operating system, or algorithms used by the sender. This information can be of significant value to the user in launching further attacks.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Ensure that all reserved fields are set to zero before messages are sent and that no unnecessary information is included."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/515.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Covert Storage Channel",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-514"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-516",
              "name": "DeprecatedCovertTimingChannel",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "This weakness can be found at CWE-385."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "This weakness can be found at CWE-385.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis weakness can be found at CWE-385."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/516.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "DEPRECATED: Covert Timing Channel",
                "cwe/status": "Deprecated",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-520",
              "name": "NetMisconfigurationUseOfImpersonation",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Allowing a .NET application to run at potentially escalated levels of access to the underlying operating and file systems can be dangerous and result in various forms of attacks."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": ".NET server applications can optionally execute using the identity of the user authenticated to the client. The intention of this functionality is to bypass authentication and access control checks within the .NET application code. Authentication is done by the underlying web server (Microsoft Internet Information Service IIS), which passes the authenticated token, or unauthenticated anonymous token, to the .NET application. Using the token to impersonate the client, the application then relies on the settings within the NTFS directories and files to control access. Impersonation enables the application, on the server running the .NET application, to both execute code and access resources in the context of the authenticated and authorized user."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Allowing a .NET application to run at potentially escalated levels of access to the underlying operating and file systems can be dangerous and result in various forms of attacks.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nAllowing a .NET application to run at potentially escalated levels of access to the underlying operating and file systems can be dangerous and result in various forms of attacks.\n\n## Extended Description\n\n.NET server applications can optionally execute using the identity of the user authenticated to the client. The intention of this functionality is to bypass authentication and access control checks within the .NET application code. Authentication is done by the underlying web server (Microsoft Internet Information Service IIS), which passes the authenticated token, or unauthenticated anonymous token, to the .NET application. Using the token to impersonate the client, the application then relies on the settings within the NTFS directories and files to control access. Impersonation enables the application, on the server running the .NET application, to both execute code and access resources in the context of the authenticated and authorized user.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Operation*. Run the application with limited privilege to the underlying operating and file system."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/520.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": ".NET Misconfiguration: Use of Impersonation",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-266"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-521",
              "name": "WeakPasswordRequirements",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not require that users should have strong passwords."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not require that users should have strong passwords.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not require that users should have strong passwords.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n  - An attacker could easily guess user passwords and gain access user accounts.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. A product's design should require adherance to an appropriate password policy. Specific password requirements depend strongly on contextual factors, but it is recommended to contain the following attributes: Enforcement of a minimum and maximum length Restrictions against password reuse Restrictions against using common passwords Restrictions against using contextual string in the password (e.g., user id, app name) Depending on the threat model, the password policy may include several additional attributes. Complex passwords requiring mixed character sets (alpha, numeric, special, mixed case) Increasing the range of characters makes the password harder to crack and may be appropriate for systems relying on single factor authentication. Unfortunately, a complex password may be difficult to memorize, encouraging a user to select a short password or to incorrectly manage the password (write it down). Another disadvantage of this approach is that it often does not result in a significant increases in overal password complexity due to people's predictable usage of various symbols. Large Minimum Length (encouraging passphrases instead of passwords) Increasing the number of characters makes the password harder to crack and may be appropriate for systems relying on single factor authentication. A disadvantage of this approach is that selecting a good passphrase is not easy and poor passwords can still be generated. Some prompting may be needed to encourage long un-predictable passwords. Randomly Chosen Secrets Generating a password for the user can help make sure that length and complexity requirements are met, and can result in secure passwords being used. A disadvantage of this approach is that the resulting password or passpharse may be too difficult to memorize, encouraging them to be written down. See NIST 800-63B [REF-1053] for further information on password requirements.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Consider a second authentication factor beyond the password, which prevents the password from being a single point of failure. See CWE-308 for further information.\n3. *Phase: Implementation*. Consider implementing a password complexity meter to inform users when a chosen password meets the required attributes.\n4. *Phase: Implementation*. Previously, \"password expiration\" was widely advocated as a defense-in-depth approach to minimize the risk of weak passwords, and it has become a common practice. Password expiration requires a password to be changed within a fixed time window (such as every 90 days). However, this approach has significant limitations in the current threat landscape, and its utility has been reduced in light of the adoption of related protection mechanisms (such as password complexity and computational effort), along with the recognition that regular password changes often caused users to generate more predictable passwords. As a result, this is now a Discouraged Common Practice [REF-1488] [REF-1489], especially as the sole factor in protecting passwords. It is still strongly encouraged to force password changes in case of evidence of compromise, but this is not the same as a forced \"expiration\" on an arbitrary time frame."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/521.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Weak Password Requirements",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-1391"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-522",
              "name": "InsufficientlyProtectedCredentials",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product transmits or stores authentication credentials, but it uses an insecure method that is susceptible to unauthorized interception and/or retrieval."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product transmits or stores authentication credentials, but it uses an insecure method that is susceptible to unauthorized interception and/or retrieval.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product transmits or stores authentication credentials, but it uses an insecure method that is susceptible to unauthorized interception and/or retrieval.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n  - An attacker could gain access to user accounts and access sensitive data used by the user accounts.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Use an appropriate security mechanism to protect the credentials.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Make appropriate use of cryptography to protect the credentials.\n3. *Phase: Implementation*. Use industry standards to protect the credentials (e.g. LDAP, keystore, etc.)."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/522.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Insufficiently Protected Credentials",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-1390"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-523",
              "name": "UnprotectedTransportOfCredentials",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Login pages do not use adequate measures to protect the user name and password while they are in transit from the client to the server."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Login pages do not use adequate measures to protect the user name and password while they are in transit from the client to the server.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nLogin pages do not use adequate measures to protect the user name and password while they are in transit from the client to the server.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Operation, System Configuration*. Enforce SSL use for the login page or any page used to transmit user credentials or other sensitive information. Even if the entire site does not use SSL, it MUST use SSL for login. Additionally, to help prevent phishing attacks, make sure that SSL serves the login page. SSL allows the user to verify the identity of the server to which they are connecting. If the SSL serves login page, the user can be certain they are talking to the proper end system. A phishing attack would typically redirect a user to a site that does not have a valid trusted server certificate issued from an authorized supplier."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/523.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Unprotected Transport of Credentials",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-522"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-524",
              "name": "UseOfCacheContainingSensitiveInformation",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The code uses a cache that contains sensitive information, but the cache can be read by an actor outside of the intended control sphere."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Applications may use caches to improve efficiency when communicating with remote entities or performing intensive calculations. A cache maintains a pool of objects, threads, connections, pages, financial data, passwords, or other resources to minimize the time it takes to initialize and access these resources. If the cache is accessible to unauthorized actors, attackers can read the cache and obtain this sensitive information."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The code uses a cache that contains sensitive information, but the cache can be read by an actor outside of the intended control sphere.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code uses a cache that contains sensitive information, but the cache can be read by an actor outside of the intended control sphere.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nApplications may use caches to improve efficiency when communicating with remote entities or performing intensive calculations. A cache maintains a pool of objects, threads, connections, pages, financial data, passwords, or other resources to minimize the time it takes to initialize and access these resources. If the cache is accessible to unauthorized actors, attackers can read the cache and obtain this sensitive information.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Protect information stored in cache.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Do not store unnecessarily sensitive information in the cache.\n3. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Consider using encryption in the cache."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/524.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Use of Cache Containing Sensitive Information",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-668"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-525",
              "name": "UseOfWebBrowserCacheContainingSensitiveInformation",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The web application does not use an appropriate caching policy that specifies the extent to which each web page and associated form fields should be cached."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The web application does not use an appropriate caching policy that specifies the extent to which each web page and associated form fields should be cached.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe web application does not use an appropriate caching policy that specifies the extent to which each web page and associated form fields should be cached.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - Browsers often store information in a client-side cache, which can leave behind sensitive information for other users to find and exploit, such as passwords or credit card numbers. The locations at most risk include public terminals, such as those in libraries and Internet cafes.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Protect information stored in cache.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Use a restrictive caching policy for forms and web pages that potentially contain sensitive information, such as \"no-cache\" in the Cache-Control header.\n3. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Do not store unnecessarily sensitive information in the cache.\n4. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Consider using encryption in the cache."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/525.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Use of Web Browser Cache Containing Sensitive Information",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-524"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-526",
              "name": "CleartextStorageOfSensitiveInformationInAnEnvironmentVariable",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses an environment variable to store unencrypted sensitive information."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Information stored in an environment variable can be accessible by other processes with the execution context, including child processes that dependencies are executed in, or serverless functions in cloud environments. An environment variable's contents can also be inserted into messages, headers, log files, or other outputs. Often these other dependencies have no need to use the environment variable in question. A weakness that discloses environment variables could expose this information."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses an environment variable to store unencrypted sensitive information.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses an environment variable to store unencrypted sensitive information.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nInformation stored in an environment variable can be accessible by other processes with the execution context, including child processes that dependencies are executed in, or serverless functions in cloud environments. An environment variable's contents can also be inserted into messages, headers, log files, or other outputs. Often these other dependencies have no need to use the environment variable in question. A weakness that discloses environment variables could expose this information.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Encrypt information stored in the environment variable to protect it from being exposed to an unauthorized user. If encryption is not feasible or is considered too expensive for the business use of the application, then consider using a properly protected configuration file instead of an environment variable. It should be understood that unencrypted information in a config file is also not guaranteed to be protected, but it is still a better choice, because it reduces attack surface related to weaknesses such as CWE-214. In some settings, vaults might be a feasible option for safer data transfer. Users should be notified of the business choice made to not protect the sensitive information through encryption.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. If the environment variable is not necessary for the desired behavior, then remove it entirely, or clear it to an empty value."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/526.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Cleartext Storage of Sensitive Information in an Environment Variable",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-312"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-527",
              "name": "ExposureOfVersionControlRepositoryToAnUnauthorizedControlSphere",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product stores a CVS, git, or other repository in a directory, archive, or other resource that is stored, transferred, or otherwise made accessible to unauthorized actors."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Version control repositories such as CVS or git store version-specific metadata and other details within subdirectories. If these subdirectories are stored on a web server or added to an archive, then these could be used by an attacker. This information may include usernames, filenames, path root, IP addresses, and detailed \"diff\" data about how files have been changed - which could reveal source code snippets that were never intended to be made public."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product stores a CVS, git, or other repository in a directory, archive, or other resource that is stored, transferred, or otherwise made accessible to unauthorized actors.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product stores a CVS, git, or other repository in a directory, archive, or other resource that is stored, transferred, or otherwise made accessible to unauthorized actors.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nVersion control repositories such as CVS or git store version-specific metadata and other details within subdirectories. If these subdirectories are stored on a web server or added to an archive, then these could be used by an attacker. This information may include usernames, filenames, path root, IP addresses, and detailed \"diff\" data about how files have been changed - which could reveal source code snippets that were never intended to be made public.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data, Read Files or Directories.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Operation, Distribution, System Configuration*. Recommendations include removing any CVS directories and repositories from the production server, disabling the use of remote CVS repositories, and ensuring that the latest CVS patches and version updates have been performed."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/527.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Exposure of Version-Control Repository to an Unauthorized Control Sphere",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-552"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-528",
              "name": "ExposureOfCoreDumpFileToAnUnauthorizedControlSphere",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product generates a core dump file in a directory, archive, or other resource that is stored, transferred, or otherwise made accessible to unauthorized actors."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product generates a core dump file in a directory, archive, or other resource that is stored, transferred, or otherwise made accessible to unauthorized actors.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product generates a core dump file in a directory, archive, or other resource that is stored, transferred, or otherwise made accessible to unauthorized actors.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data, Read Files or Directories.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: System Configuration*. Protect the core dump files from unauthorized access."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/528.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Exposure of Core Dump File to an Unauthorized Control Sphere",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-552"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-529",
              "name": "ExposureOfAccessControlListFilesToAnUnauthorizedControlSphere",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product stores access control list files in a directory or other container that is accessible to actors outside of the intended control sphere."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Exposure of these access control list files may give the attacker information about the configuration of the site or system. This information may then be used to bypass the intended security policy or identify trusted systems from which an attack can be launched."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product stores access control list files in a directory or other container that is accessible to actors outside of the intended control sphere.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product stores access control list files in a directory or other container that is accessible to actors outside of the intended control sphere.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nExposure of these access control list files may give the attacker information about the configuration of the site or system. This information may then be used to bypass the intended security policy or identify trusted systems from which an attack can be launched.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Access Control. **Impact**: Read Application Data, Bypass Protection Mechanism.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: System Configuration*. Protect access control list files."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/529.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Exposure of Access Control List Files to an Unauthorized Control Sphere",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-552"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-530",
              "name": "ExposureOfBackupFileToAnUnauthorizedControlSphere",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A backup file is stored in a directory or archive that is made accessible to unauthorized actors."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Often, older backup files are renamed with an extension such as .~bk to distinguish them from production files. The source code for old files that have been renamed in this manner and left in the webroot can often be retrieved. This renaming may have been performed automatically by the web server, or manually by the administrator."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "A backup file is stored in a directory or archive that is made accessible to unauthorized actors.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA backup file is stored in a directory or archive that is made accessible to unauthorized actors.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nOften, older backup files are renamed with an extension such as .~bk to distinguish them from production files. The source code for old files that have been renamed in this manner and left in the webroot can often be retrieved. This renaming may have been performed automatically by the web server, or manually by the administrator.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - At a minimum, an attacker who retrieves this file would have all the information contained in it, whether that be database calls, the format of parameters accepted by the application, or simply information regarding the architectural structure of your site.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Policy*. Recommendations include implementing a security policy within your organization that prohibits backing up web application source code in the webroot."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/530.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Exposure of Backup File to an Unauthorized Control Sphere",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-552"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-531",
              "name": "InclusionOfSensitiveInformationInTestCode",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Accessible test applications can pose a variety of security risks."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Accessible test applications can pose a variety of security risks. Since developers or administrators rarely consider that someone besides themselves would even know about the existence of these applications, it is common for them to contain sensitive information or functions.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nAccessible test applications can pose a variety of security risks. Since developers or administrators rarely consider that someone besides themselves would even know about the existence of these applications, it is common for them to contain sensitive information or functions.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Distribution, Installation*. Remove test code before deploying the application into production."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/531.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Inclusion of Sensitive Information in Test Code",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-540"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-532",
              "name": "InsertionOfSensitiveInformationIntoLogFile",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product writes sensitive information to a log file."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product writes sensitive information to a log file.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product writes sensitive information to a log file.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - Logging sensitive user data, full path names, or system information often provides attackers with an additional, less-protected path to acquiring the information.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Implementation*. Consider seriously the sensitivity of the information written into log files. Do not write secrets into the log files.\n2. *Phase: Distribution*. Remove debug log files before deploying the application into production.\n3. *Phase: Operation*. Protect log files against unauthorized read/write.\n4. *Phase: Implementation*. Adjust configurations appropriately when software is transitioned from a debug state to production."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/532.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Insertion of Sensitive Information into Log File",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-538"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-533",
              "name": "DeprecatedInformationExposureThroughServerLogFiles",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "This entry has been deprecated because its abstraction was too low-level."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "This entry has been deprecated because its abstraction was too low-level. See CWE-532.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis entry has been deprecated because its abstraction was too low-level. See CWE-532."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/533.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "DEPRECATED: Information Exposure Through Server Log Files",
                "cwe/status": "Deprecated",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-534",
              "name": "DeprecatedInformationExposureThroughDebugLogFiles",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "This entry has been deprecated because its abstraction was too low-level."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "This entry has been deprecated because its abstraction was too low-level. See CWE-532.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis entry has been deprecated because its abstraction was too low-level. See CWE-532."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/534.html",
