            {
              "id": "CWE-535",
              "name": "ExposureOfInformationThroughShellErrorMessage",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A command shell error message indicates that there exists an unhandled exception in the web application code."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "A command shell error message indicates that there exists an unhandled exception in the web application code. In many cases, an attacker can leverage the conditions that cause these errors in order to gain unauthorized access to the system.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA command shell error message indicates that there exists an unhandled exception in the web application code. In many cases, an attacker can leverage the conditions that cause these errors in order to gain unauthorized access to the system.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/535.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Exposure of Information Through Shell Error Message",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-211"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-536",
              "name": "ServletRuntimeErrorMessageContainingSensitiveInformation",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A servlet error message indicates that there exists an unhandled exception in the web application code and may provide useful information to an attacker."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "A servlet error message indicates that there exists an unhandled exception in the web application code and may provide useful information to an attacker.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA servlet error message indicates that there exists an unhandled exception in the web application code and may provide useful information to an attacker.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - The error message may contain the location of the file in which the offending function is located. This may disclose the web root's absolute path as well as give the attacker the location of application files or configuration information. It may even disclose the portion of code that failed. In many cases, an attacker can use the data to launch further attacks against the system."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/536.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Servlet Runtime Error Message Containing Sensitive Information",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-211"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-537",
              "name": "JavaRuntimeErrorMessageContainingSensitiveInformation",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "In many cases, an attacker can leverage the conditions that cause unhandled exception errors in order to gain unauthorized access to the system."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "In many cases, an attacker can leverage the conditions that cause unhandled exception errors in order to gain unauthorized access to the system.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn many cases, an attacker can leverage the conditions that cause unhandled exception errors in order to gain unauthorized access to the system.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Do not expose sensitive error information to the user."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/537.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Java Runtime Error Message Containing Sensitive Information",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-211"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-538",
              "name": "InsertionOfSensitiveInformationIntoExternallyAccessibleFileOrDirectory",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product places sensitive information into files or directories that are accessible to actors who are allowed to have access to the files, but not to the sensitive information."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product places sensitive information into files or directories that are accessible to actors who are allowed to have access to the files, but not to the sensitive information.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product places sensitive information into files or directories that are accessible to actors who are allowed to have access to the files, but not to the sensitive information.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Files or Directories.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Operation, System Configuration*. Do not expose file and directory information to the user."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/538.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Insertion of Sensitive Information into Externally-Accessible File or Directory",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-200"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-539",
              "name": "UseOfPersistentCookiesContainingSensitiveInformation",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The web application uses persistent cookies, but the cookies contain sensitive information."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Cookies are small bits of data that are sent by the web application but stored locally in the browser. This lets the application use the cookie to pass information between pages and store variable information. The web application controls what information is stored in a cookie and how it is used. Typical types of information stored in cookies are session identifiers, personalization and customization information, and in rare cases even usernames to enable automated logins. There are two different types of cookies: session cookies and persistent cookies. Session cookies just live in the browser's memory and are not stored anywhere, but persistent cookies are stored on the browser's hard drive. This can cause security and privacy issues depending on the information stored in the cookie and how it is accessed."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The web application uses persistent cookies, but the cookies contain sensitive information.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe web application uses persistent cookies, but the cookies contain sensitive information.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nCookies are small bits of data that are sent by the web application but stored locally in the browser. This lets the application use the cookie to pass information between pages and store variable information. The web application controls what information is stored in a cookie and how it is used. Typical types of information stored in cookies are session identifiers, personalization and customization information, and in rare cases even usernames to enable automated logins. There are two different types of cookies: session cookies and persistent cookies. Session cookies just live in the browser's memory and are not stored anywhere, but persistent cookies are stored on the browser's hard drive. This can cause security and privacy issues depending on the information stored in the cookie and how it is accessed.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Do not store sensitive information in persistent cookies."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/539.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Use of Persistent Cookies Containing Sensitive Information",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-552"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-540",
              "name": "InclusionOfSensitiveInformationInSourceCode",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Source code on a web server or repository often contains sensitive information and should generally not be accessible to users."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "There are situations where it is critical to remove source code from an area or server. For example, obtaining Perl source code on a system allows an attacker to understand the logic of the script and extract extremely useful information such as code bugs or logins and passwords."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Source code on a web server or repository often contains sensitive information and should generally not be accessible to users.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSource code on a web server or repository often contains sensitive information and should generally not be accessible to users.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThere are situations where it is critical to remove source code from an area or server. For example, obtaining Perl source code on a system allows an attacker to understand the logic of the script and extract extremely useful information such as code bugs or logins and passwords.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design, System Configuration*. Recommendations include removing this script from the web server and moving it to a location not accessible from the Internet."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/540.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Inclusion of Sensitive Information in Source Code",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-538"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-541",
              "name": "InclusionOfSensitiveInformationInAnIncludeFile",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "If an include file source is accessible, the file can contain usernames and passwords, as well as sensitive information pertaining to the application and system."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "If an include file source is accessible, the file can contain usernames and passwords, as well as sensitive information pertaining to the application and system.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIf an include file source is accessible, the file can contain usernames and passwords, as well as sensitive information pertaining to the application and system.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Do not store sensitive information in include files.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design, System Configuration*. Protect include files from being exposed."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/541.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Inclusion of Sensitive Information in an Include File",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-540"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-542",
              "name": "DeprecatedInformationExposureThroughCleanupLogFiles",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "This entry has been deprecated because its abstraction was too low-level."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "This entry has been deprecated because its abstraction was too low-level. See CWE-532.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis entry has been deprecated because its abstraction was too low-level. See CWE-532."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/542.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "DEPRECATED: Information Exposure Through Cleanup Log Files",
                "cwe/status": "Deprecated",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-543",
              "name": "UseOfSingletonPatternWithoutSynchronizationInAMultithreadedContext",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses the singleton pattern when creating a resource within a multithreaded environment."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The use of a singleton pattern may not be thread-safe."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses the singleton pattern when creating a resource within a multithreaded environment.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses the singleton pattern when creating a resource within a multithreaded environment.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThe use of a singleton pattern may not be thread-safe.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other, Integrity. **Impact**: Other, Modify Application Data.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Use the Thread-Specific Storage Pattern. See References.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Do not use member fields to store information in the Servlet. In multithreading environments, storing user data in Servlet member fields introduces a data access race condition.\n3. *Phase: Implementation*. Avoid using the double-checked locking pattern in language versions that cannot guarantee thread safety. This pattern may be used to avoid the overhead of a synchronized call, but in certain versions of Java (for example), this has been shown to be unsafe because it still introduces a race condition (CWE-209)."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/543.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Use of Singleton Pattern Without Synchronization in a Multithreaded Context",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-820"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-544",
              "name": "MissingStandardizedErrorHandlingMechanism",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not use a standardized method for handling errors throughout the code, which might introduce inconsistent error handling and resultant weaknesses."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "If the product handles error messages individually, on a one-by-one basis, this is likely to result in inconsistent error handling. The causes of errors may be lost. Also, detailed information about the causes of an error may be unintentionally returned to the user."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not use a standardized method for handling errors throughout the code, which might introduce inconsistent error handling and resultant weaknesses.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not use a standardized method for handling errors throughout the code, which might introduce inconsistent error handling and resultant weaknesses.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIf the product handles error messages individually, on a one-by-one basis, this is likely to result in inconsistent error handling. The causes of errors may be lost. Also, detailed information about the causes of an error may be unintentionally returned to the user.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation, Unexpected State, Varies by Context.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. define a strategy for handling errors of different severities, such as fatal errors versus basic log events. Use or create built-in language features, or an external package, that provides an easy-to-use API and define coding standards for the detection and handling of errors."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/544.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Missing Standardized Error Handling Mechanism",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-755"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-545",
              "name": "DeprecatedUseOfDynamicClassLoading",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "This weakness has been deprecated because it partially overlaps CWE-470, it describes legitimate programmer behavior, and other portions will need to be integrated into other entries."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "This weakness has been deprecated because it partially overlaps CWE-470, it describes legitimate programmer behavior, and other portions will need to be integrated into other entries.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis weakness has been deprecated because it partially overlaps CWE-470, it describes legitimate programmer behavior, and other portions will need to be integrated into other entries."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/545.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "DEPRECATED: Use of Dynamic Class Loading",
                "cwe/status": "Deprecated",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-546",
              "name": "SuspiciousComment",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The code contains comments that suggest the presence of bugs, incomplete functionality, or weaknesses."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Many suspicious comments, such as BUG, HACK, FIXME, LATER, LATER2, TODO, in the code indicate missing security functionality and checking. Others indicate code problems that programmers should fix, such as hard-coded variables, error handling, not using stored procedures, and performance issues."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The code contains comments that suggest the presence of bugs, incomplete functionality, or weaknesses.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code contains comments that suggest the presence of bugs, incomplete functionality, or weaknesses.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nMany suspicious comments, such as BUG, HACK, FIXME, LATER, LATER2, TODO, in the code indicate missing security functionality and checking. Others indicate code problems that programmers should fix, such as hard-coded variables, error handling, not using stored procedures, and performance issues.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation.\n  - Suspicious comments could be an indication that there are problems in the source code that may need to be fixed and is an indication of poor quality. This could lead to further bugs and the introduction of weaknesses.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Documentation*. Remove comments that suggest the presence of bugs, incomplete functionality, or weaknesses, before deploying the application."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/546.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Suspicious Comment",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-1078"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-547",
              "name": "UseOfHardCodedSecurityRelevantConstants",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses hard-coded constants instead of symbolic names for security-critical values, which increases the likelihood of mistakes during code maintenance or security policy change."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "If the developer does not find all occurrences of the hard-coded constants, an incorrect policy decision may be made if one of the constants is not changed. Making changes to these values will require code changes that may be difficult or impossible once the system is released to the field. In addition, these hard-coded values may become available to attackers if the code is ever disclosed."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses hard-coded constants instead of symbolic names for security-critical values, which increases the likelihood of mistakes during code maintenance or security policy change.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses hard-coded constants instead of symbolic names for security-critical values, which increases the likelihood of mistakes during code maintenance or security policy change.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIf the developer does not find all occurrences of the hard-coded constants, an incorrect policy decision may be made if one of the constants is not changed. Making changes to these values will require code changes that may be difficult or impossible once the system is released to the field. In addition, these hard-coded values may become available to attackers if the code is ever disclosed.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Varies by Context, Quality Degradation, Reduce Maintainability.\n  - The existence of hardcoded constants could cause unexpected behavior and the introduction of weaknesses during code maintenance or when making changes to the code if all occurrences are not modified. The use of hardcoded constants is an indication of poor quality.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Avoid using hard-coded constants. Configuration files offer a more flexible solution."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/547.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Use of Hard-coded, Security-relevant Constants",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-1078"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-548",
              "name": "ExposureOfInformationThroughDirectoryListing",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product inappropriately exposes a directory listing with an index of all the resources located inside of the directory."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product inappropriately exposes a directory listing with an index of all the resources located inside of the directory.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product inappropriately exposes a directory listing with an index of all the resources located inside of the directory.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Files or Directories.\n  - Exposing the contents of a directory can lead to an attacker gaining access to source code or providing useful information for the attacker to devise exploits, such as creation times of files or any information that may be encoded in file names. The directory listing may also compromise private or confidential data.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design, System Configuration*. Recommendations include restricting access to important directories or files by adopting a need to know requirement for both the document and server root, and turning off features such as Automatic Directory Listings that could expose private files and provide information that could be utilized by an attacker when formulating or conducting an attack."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/548.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Exposure of Information Through Directory Listing",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-497"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-549",
              "name": "MissingPasswordFieldMasking",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not mask passwords during entry, increasing the potential for attackers to observe and capture passwords."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not mask passwords during entry, increasing the potential for attackers to observe and capture passwords.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not mask passwords during entry, increasing the potential for attackers to observe and capture passwords.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation, Requirements*. Recommendations include requiring all password fields in your web application be masked to prevent other users from seeing this information."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/549.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Missing Password Field Masking",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-522"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-550",
              "name": "ServerGeneratedErrorMessageContainingSensitiveInformation",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Certain conditions, such as network failure, will cause a server error message to be displayed."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "While error messages in and of themselves are not dangerous, per se, it is what an attacker can glean from them that might cause eventual problems."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Certain conditions, such as network failure, will cause a server error message to be displayed.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCertain conditions, such as network failure, will cause a server error message to be displayed.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nWhile error messages in and of themselves are not dangerous, per se, it is what an attacker can glean from them that might cause eventual problems.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design, System Configuration*. Recommendations include designing and adding consistent error handling mechanisms which are capable of handling any user input to your web application, providing meaningful detail to end-users, and preventing error messages that might provide information useful to an attacker from being displayed."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/550.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Server-generated Error Message Containing Sensitive Information",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-209"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-551",
              "name": "IncorrectBehaviorOrderAuthorizationBeforeParsingAndCanonicalization",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "If a web server does not fully parse requested URLs before it examines them for authorization, it may be possible for an attacker to bypass authorization protection."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "For instance, the character strings /./ and / both mean current directory. If /SomeDirectory is a protected directory and an attacker requests /./SomeDirectory, the attacker may be able to gain access to the resource if /./ is not converted to / before the authorization check is performed."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "If a web server does not fully parse requested URLs before it examines them for authorization, it may be possible for an attacker to bypass authorization protection.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIf a web server does not fully parse requested URLs before it examines them for authorization, it may be possible for an attacker to bypass authorization protection.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nFor instance, the character strings /./ and / both mean current directory. If /SomeDirectory is a protected directory and an attacker requests /./SomeDirectory, the attacker may be able to gain access to the resource if /./ is not converted to / before the authorization check is performed.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. URL Inputs should be decoded and canonicalized to the application's current internal representation before being validated and processed for authorization. Make sure that your application does not decode the same input twice. Such errors could be used to bypass allowlist schemes by introducing dangerous inputs after they have been checked."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/551.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Incorrect Behavior Order: Authorization Before Parsing and Canonicalization",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-863"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-552",
              "name": "FilesOrDirectoriesAccessibleToExternalParties",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product makes files or directories accessible to unauthorized actors, even though they should not be."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Web servers, FTP servers, and similar servers may store a set of files underneath a \"root\" directory that is accessible to the server's users. Applications may store sensitive files underneath this root without also using access control to limit which users may request those files, if any. Alternately, an application might package multiple files or directories into an archive file (e.g., ZIP or tar), but the application might not exclude sensitive files that are underneath those directories. In cloud technologies and containers, this weakness might present itself in the form of misconfigured storage accounts that can be read or written by a public or anonymous user."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product makes files or directories accessible to unauthorized actors, even though they should not be.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product makes files or directories accessible to unauthorized actors, even though they should not be.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nWeb servers, FTP servers, and similar servers may store a set of files underneath a \"root\" directory that is accessible to the server's users. Applications may store sensitive files underneath this root without also using access control to limit which users may request those files, if any. Alternately, an application might package multiple files or directories into an archive file (e.g., ZIP or tar), but the application might not exclude sensitive files that are underneath those directories. In cloud technologies and containers, this weakness might present itself in the form of misconfigured storage accounts that can be read or written by a public or anonymous user.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity. **Impact**: Read Files or Directories, Modify Files or Directories.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation, System Configuration, Operation*. When storing data in the cloud (e.g., S3 buckets, Azure blobs, Google Cloud Storage, etc.), use the provider's controls to disable public access."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/552.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Files or Directories Accessible to External Parties",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-668"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-553",
              "name": "CommandShellInExternallyAccessibleDirectory",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A possible shell file exists in /cgi-bin/ or other accessible directories."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "A possible shell file exists in /cgi-bin/ or other accessible directories. This is extremely dangerous and can be used by an attacker to execute commands on the web server.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA possible shell file exists in /cgi-bin/ or other accessible directories. This is extremely dangerous and can be used by an attacker to execute commands on the web server.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability. **Impact**: Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Installation, System Configuration*. Remove any Shells accessible under the web root folder and children directories."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/553.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Command Shell in Externally Accessible Directory",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-552"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-554",
              "name": "AspNetMisconfigurationNotUsingInputValidationFramework",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The ASP.NET application does not use an input validation framework."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The ASP.NET application does not use an input validation framework.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe ASP.NET application does not use an input validation framework.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Unexpected State.\n  - Unchecked input leads to cross-site scripting, process control, and SQL injection vulnerabilities, among others.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Use the ASP.NET validation framework to check all program input before it is processed by the application. Example uses of the validation framework include checking to ensure that: Phone number fields contain only valid characters in phone numbers Boolean values are only \"T\" or \"F\" Free-form strings are of a reasonable length and composition"
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/554.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "ASP.NET Misconfiguration: Not Using Input Validation Framework",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-1173"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-555",
              "name": "J2eeMisconfigurationPlaintextPasswordInConfigurationFile",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The J2EE application stores a plaintext password in a configuration file."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Storing a plaintext password in a configuration file allows anyone who can read the file to access the password-protected resource, making it an easy target for attackers."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The J2EE application stores a plaintext password in a configuration file.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe J2EE application stores a plaintext password in a configuration file.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nStoring a plaintext password in a configuration file allows anyone who can read the file to access the password-protected resource, making it an easy target for attackers.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Do not hardwire passwords into your software.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Use industry standard libraries to encrypt passwords before storage in configuration files."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/555.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "J2EE Misconfiguration: Plaintext Password in Configuration File",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-260"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-556",
              "name": "AspNetMisconfigurationUseOfIdentityImpersonation",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Configuring an ASP.NET application to run with impersonated credentials may give the application unnecessary privileges."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The use of impersonated credentials allows an ASP.NET application to run with either the privileges of the client on whose behalf it is executing or with arbitrary privileges granted in its configuration."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Configuring an ASP.NET application to run with impersonated credentials may give the application unnecessary privileges.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nConfiguring an ASP.NET application to run with impersonated credentials may give the application unnecessary privileges.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThe use of impersonated credentials allows an ASP.NET application to run with either the privileges of the client on whose behalf it is executing or with arbitrary privileges granted in its configuration.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Use the least privilege principle."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/556.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "ASP.NET Misconfiguration: Use of Identity Impersonation",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-266"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-558",
              "name": "UseOfGetloginInMultithreadedApplication",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses the getlogin() function in a multithreaded context, potentially causing it to return incorrect values."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The getlogin() function returns a pointer to a string that contains the name of the user associated with the calling process. The function is not reentrant, meaning that if it is called from another process, the contents are not locked out and the value of the string can be changed by another process. This makes it very risky to use because the username can be changed by other processes, so the results of the function cannot be trusted."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses the getlogin() function in a multithreaded context, potentially causing it to return incorrect values.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses the getlogin() function in a multithreaded context, potentially causing it to return incorrect values.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThe getlogin() function returns a pointer to a string that contains the name of the user associated with the calling process. The function is not reentrant, meaning that if it is called from another process, the contents are not locked out and the value of the string can be changed by another process. This makes it very risky to use because the username can be changed by other processes, so the results of the function cannot be trusted.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Access Control, Other. **Impact**: Modify Application Data, Bypass Protection Mechanism, Other.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Using names for security purposes is not advised. Names are easy to forge and can have overlapping user IDs, potentially causing confusion or impersonation.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Use getlogin_r() instead, which is reentrant, meaning that other processes are locked out from changing the username."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/558.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Use of getlogin() in Multithreaded Application",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-663"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-560",
              "name": "UseOfUmaskWithChmodStyleArgument",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product calls umask() with an incorrect argument that is specified as if it is an argument to chmod()."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product calls umask() with an incorrect argument that is specified as if it is an argument to chmod().",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product calls umask() with an incorrect argument that is specified as if it is an argument to chmod().\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity, Access Control. **Impact**: Read Files or Directories, Modify Files or Directories, Bypass Protection Mechanism.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Use umask() with the correct argument."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/560.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Use of umask() with chmod-style Argument",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-687"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-561",
              "name": "DeadCode",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product contains dead code, which can never be executed."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Dead code is code that can never be executed in a running program. The surrounding code makes it impossible for a section of code to ever be executed."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product contains dead code, which can never be executed.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product contains dead code, which can never be executed.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nDead code is code that can never be executed in a running program. The surrounding code makes it impossible for a section of code to ever be executed.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation.\n  - Dead code that results from code that can never be executed is an indication of problems with the source code that needs to be fixed and is an indication of poor quality.\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Reduce Maintainability.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Remove dead code before deploying the application."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/561.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Dead Code",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-1164"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-562",
              "name": "ReturnOfStackVariableAddress",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A function returns the address of a stack variable, which will cause unintended program behavior, typically in the form of a crash."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Because local variables are allocated on the stack, when a program returns a pointer to a local variable, it is returning a stack address. A subsequent function call is likely to re-use this same stack address, thereby overwriting the value of the pointer, which no longer corresponds to the same variable since a function's stack frame is invalidated when it returns. At best this will cause the value of the pointer to change unexpectedly. In many cases it causes the program to crash the next time the pointer is dereferenced."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "A function returns the address of a stack variable, which will cause unintended program behavior, typically in the form of a crash.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA function returns the address of a stack variable, which will cause unintended program behavior, typically in the form of a crash.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nBecause local variables are allocated on the stack, when a program returns a pointer to a local variable, it is returning a stack address. A subsequent function call is likely to re-use this same stack address, thereby overwriting the value of the pointer, which no longer corresponds to the same variable since a function's stack frame is invalidated when it returns. At best this will cause the value of the pointer to change unexpectedly. In many cases it causes the program to crash the next time the pointer is dereferenced.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Availability, Integrity, Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Memory, Modify Memory, Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands, DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart.\n  - If the returned stack buffer address is dereferenced after the return, then an attacker may be able to modify or read memory, depending on how the address is used. If the address is used for reading, then the address itself may be exposed, or the contents that the address points to. If the address is used for writing, this can lead to a crash and possibly code execution.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Fix the code so that it does not return a stack address."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/562.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Return of Stack Variable Address",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-758"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-563",
              "name": "AssignmentToVariableWithoutUse",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The variable's value is assigned but never used, making it a dead store."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "After the assignment, the variable is either assigned another value or goes out of scope. It is likely that the variable is simply vestigial, but it is also possible that the unused variable points out a bug."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The variable's value is assigned but never used, making it a dead store.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe variable's value is assigned but never used, making it a dead store.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nAfter the assignment, the variable is either assigned another value or goes out of scope. It is likely that the variable is simply vestigial, but it is also possible that the unused variable points out a bug.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation, Varies by Context.\n  - This weakness could be an indication of a bug in the program or a deprecated variable that was not removed and is an indication of poor quality. This could lead to further bugs and the introduction of weaknesses.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Remove unused variables from the code."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/563.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Assignment to Variable without Use",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-1164"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-564",
              "name": "SqlInjectionHibernate",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Using Hibernate to execute a dynamic SQL statement built with user-controlled input can allow an attacker to modify the statement's meaning or to execute arbitrary SQL commands."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Using Hibernate to execute a dynamic SQL statement built with user-controlled input can allow an attacker to modify the statement's meaning or to execute arbitrary SQL commands.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nUsing Hibernate to execute a dynamic SQL statement built with user-controlled input can allow an attacker to modify the statement's meaning or to execute arbitrary SQL commands.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity. **Impact**: Read Application Data, Modify Application Data.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Requirements*. A non-SQL style database which is not subject to this flaw may be chosen.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Follow the principle of least privilege when creating user accounts to a SQL database. Users should only have the minimum privileges necessary to use their account. If the requirements of the system indicate that a user can read and modify their own data, then limit their privileges so they cannot read/write others' data.\n3. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. For any security checks that are performed on the client side, ensure that these checks are duplicated on the server side, in order to avoid CWE-602. Attackers can bypass the client-side checks by modifying values after the checks have been performed, or by changing the client to remove the client-side checks entirely. Then, these modified values would be submitted to the server.\n4. *Phase: Implementation*. Implement SQL strings using prepared statements that bind variables. Prepared statements that do not bind variables can be vulnerable to attack.\n5. *Phase: Implementation*. Use vigorous allowlist style checking on any user input that may be used in a SQL command. Rather than escape meta-characters, it is safest to disallow them entirely. Reason: Later use of data that have been entered in the database may neglect to escape meta-characters before use. Narrowly define the set of safe characters based on the expected value of the parameter in the request."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/564.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "SQL Injection: Hibernate",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-89"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-565",
              "name": "RelianceOnCookiesWithoutValidationAndIntegrityChecking",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product relies on the existence or values of cookies when performing security-critical operations, but it does not properly ensure that the setting is valid for the associated user."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product relies on the existence or values of cookies when performing security-critical operations, but it does not properly ensure that the setting is valid for the associated user.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product relies on the existence or values of cookies when performing security-critical operations, but it does not properly ensure that the setting is valid for the associated user.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability. **Impact**: Modify Application Data, Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands.\n  - Attackers can easily modify cookies, within the browser or by implementing the client-side code outside of the browser. Reliance on cookies without detailed validation and integrity checking can allow attackers to bypass authentication, conduct injection attacks such as SQL injection and cross-site scripting, or otherwise modify inputs in unexpected ways.\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n  - It is dangerous to use cookies to set a user's privileges. The cookie can be manipulated to escalate an attacker's privileges to an administrative level.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Avoid using cookie data for a security-related decision.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Perform thorough input validation (i.e.: server side validation) on the cookie data if you're going to use it for a security related decision.\n3. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Add integrity checks to detect tampering.\n4. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Protect critical cookies from replay attacks, since cross-site scripting or other attacks may allow attackers to steal a strongly-encrypted cookie that also passes integrity checks. This mitigation applies to cookies that should only be valid during a single transaction or session. By enforcing timeouts, you may limit the scope of an attack. As part of your integrity check, use an unpredictable, server-side value that is not exposed to the client."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/565.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Reliance on Cookies without Validation and Integrity Checking",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-642"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-566",
              "name": "AuthorizationBypassThroughUserControlledSqlPrimaryKey",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses a database table that includes records that should not be accessible to an actor, but it executes a SQL statement with a primary key that can be controlled by that actor."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "When a user can set a primary key to any value, then the user can modify the key to point to unauthorized records. Database access control errors occur when: Data enters a program from an untrusted source. The data is used to specify the value of a primary key in a SQL query. The untrusted source does not have the permissions to be able to access all rows in the associated table."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses a database table that includes records that should not be accessible to an actor, but it executes a SQL statement with a primary key that can be controlled by that actor.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses a database table that includes records that should not be accessible to an actor, but it executes a SQL statement with a primary key that can be controlled by that actor.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nWhen a user can set a primary key to any value, then the user can modify the key to point to unauthorized records. Database access control errors occur when: Data enters a program from an untrusted source. The data is used to specify the value of a primary key in a SQL query. The untrusted source does not have the permissions to be able to access all rows in the associated table.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity, Access Control. **Impact**: Read Application Data, Modify Application Data, Bypass Protection Mechanism.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Assume all input is malicious. Use a standard input validation mechanism to validate all input for length, type, syntax, and business rules before accepting the data. Use an \"accept known good\" validation strategy.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Use a parameterized query AND make sure that the accepted values conform to the business rules. Construct your SQL statement accordingly."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/566.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Authorization Bypass Through User-Controlled SQL Primary Key",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-639"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-567",
              "name": "UnsynchronizedAccessToSharedDataInAMultithreadedContext",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not properly synchronize shared data, such as static variables across threads, which can lead to undefined behavior and unpredictable data changes."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Within servlets, shared static variables are not protected from concurrent access, but servlets are multithreaded. This is a typical programming mistake in J2EE applications, since the multithreading is handled by the framework. When a shared variable can be influenced by an attacker, one thread could wind up modifying the variable to contain data that is not valid for a different thread that is also using the data within the variable. Note that this weakness is not unique to servlets."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not properly synchronize shared data, such as static variables across threads, which can lead to undefined behavior and unpredictable data changes.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not properly synchronize shared data, such as static variables across threads, which can lead to undefined behavior and unpredictable data changes.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nWithin servlets, shared static variables are not protected from concurrent access, but servlets are multithreaded. This is a typical programming mistake in J2EE applications, since the multithreading is handled by the framework. When a shared variable can be influenced by an attacker, one thread could wind up modifying the variable to contain data that is not valid for a different thread that is also using the data within the variable. Note that this weakness is not unique to servlets.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability. **Impact**: Read Application Data, Modify Application Data, DoS: Instability, DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart.\n  - If the shared variable contains sensitive data, it may be manipulated or displayed in another user session. If this data is used to control the application, its value can be manipulated to cause the application to crash or perform poorly.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Remove the use of static variables used between servlets. If this cannot be avoided, use synchronized access for these variables."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/567.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Unsynchronized Access to Shared Data in a Multithreaded Context",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-820"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-568",
              "name": "FinalizeMethodWithoutSuperFinalize",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product contains a finalize() method that does not call super.finalize()."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The Java Language Specification states that it is a good practice for a finalize() method to call super.finalize()."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product contains a finalize() method that does not call super.finalize().",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product contains a finalize() method that does not call super.finalize().\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThe Java Language Specification states that it is a good practice for a finalize() method to call super.finalize().\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Call the super.finalize() method."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/568.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "finalize() Method Without super.finalize()",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-459"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-570",
              "name": "ExpressionIsAlwaysFalse",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product contains an expression that will always evaluate to false."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product contains an expression that will always evaluate to false.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product contains an expression that will always evaluate to false.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation, Varies by Context.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation; Strategy: Refactoring*. Consider refactoring the code, or determine if the code is not including a condition that could cause the expression to become false."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/570.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Expression is Always False",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-710"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-571",
              "name": "ExpressionIsAlwaysTrue",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product contains an expression that will always evaluate to true."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product contains an expression that will always evaluate to true.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product contains an expression that will always evaluate to true.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation, Varies by Context.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation; Strategy: Refactoring*. Consider refactoring the code, or determine if the code is not including a condition that could cause the expression to become false."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/571.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Expression is Always True",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-710"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-572",
              "name": "CallToThreadRunInsteadOfStart",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product calls a thread's run() method instead of calling start(), which causes the code to run in the thread of the caller instead of the callee."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In most cases a direct call to a Thread object's run() method is a bug. The programmer intended to begin a new thread of control, but accidentally called run() instead of start(), so the run() method will execute in the caller's thread of control."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product calls a thread's run() method instead of calling start(), which causes the code to run in the thread of the caller instead of the callee.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product calls a thread's run() method instead of calling start(), which causes the code to run in the thread of the caller instead of the callee.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIn most cases a direct call to a Thread object's run() method is a bug. The programmer intended to begin a new thread of control, but accidentally called run() instead of start(), so the run() method will execute in the caller's thread of control.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation, Varies by Context.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Use the start() method instead of the run() method."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/572.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Call to Thread run() instead of start()",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-821"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-573",
              "name": "ImproperFollowingOfSpecificationByCaller",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not follow or incorrectly follows the specifications as required by the implementation language, environment, framework, protocol, or platform."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "When leveraging external functionality, such as an API, it is important that the caller does so in accordance with the requirements of the external functionality or else unintended behaviors may result, possibly leaving the system vulnerable to any number of exploits."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not follow or incorrectly follows the specifications as required by the implementation language, environment, framework, protocol, or platform.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not follow or incorrectly follows the specifications as required by the implementation language, environment, framework, protocol, or platform.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nWhen leveraging external functionality, such as an API, it is important that the caller does so in accordance with the requirements of the external functionality or else unintended behaviors may result, possibly leaving the system vulnerable to any number of exploits.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation, Varies by Context."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/573.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Improper Following of Specification by Caller",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-710"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-574",
              "name": "EjbBadPracticesUseOfSynchronizationPrimitives",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product violates the Enterprise JavaBeans (EJB) specification by using thread synchronization primitives."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The Enterprise JavaBeans specification requires that every bean provider follow a set of programming guidelines designed to ensure that the bean will be portable and behave consistently in any EJB container. In this case, the product violates the following EJB guideline: \"An enterprise bean must not use thread synchronization primitives to synchronize execution of multiple instances.\" The specification justifies this requirement in the following way: \"This rule is required to ensure consistent runtime semantics because while some EJB containers may use a single JVM to execute all enterprise bean's instances, others may distribute the instances across multiple JVMs.\""
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product violates the Enterprise JavaBeans (EJB) specification by using thread synchronization primitives.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product violates the Enterprise JavaBeans (EJB) specification by using thread synchronization primitives.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThe Enterprise JavaBeans specification requires that every bean provider follow a set of programming guidelines designed to ensure that the bean will be portable and behave consistently in any EJB container. In this case, the product violates the following EJB guideline: \"An enterprise bean must not use thread synchronization primitives to synchronize execution of multiple instances.\" The specification justifies this requirement in the following way: \"This rule is required to ensure consistent runtime semantics because while some EJB containers may use a single JVM to execute all enterprise bean's instances, others may distribute the instances across multiple JVMs.\"\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Do not use Synchronization Primitives when writing EJBs."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/574.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "EJB Bad Practices: Use of Synchronization Primitives",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-821"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-575",
              "name": "EjbBadPracticesUseOfAwtSwing",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product violates the Enterprise JavaBeans (EJB) specification by using AWT/Swing."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The Enterprise JavaBeans specification requires that every bean provider follow a set of programming guidelines designed to ensure that the bean will be portable and behave consistently in any EJB container. In this case, the product violates the following EJB guideline: \"An enterprise bean must not use the AWT functionality to attempt to output information to a display, or to input information from a keyboard.\" The specification justifies this requirement in the following way: \"Most servers do not allow direct interaction between an application program and a keyboard/display attached to the server system.\""
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product violates the Enterprise JavaBeans (EJB) specification by using AWT/Swing.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product violates the Enterprise JavaBeans (EJB) specification by using AWT/Swing.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThe Enterprise JavaBeans specification requires that every bean provider follow a set of programming guidelines designed to ensure that the bean will be portable and behave consistently in any EJB container. In this case, the product violates the following EJB guideline: \"An enterprise bean must not use the AWT functionality to attempt to output information to a display, or to input information from a keyboard.\" The specification justifies this requirement in the following way: \"Most servers do not allow direct interaction between an application program and a keyboard/display attached to the server system.\"\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Do not use AWT/Swing when writing EJBs."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/575.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "EJB Bad Practices: Use of AWT Swing",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-695"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-576",
              "name": "EjbBadPracticesUseOfJavaIO",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product violates the Enterprise JavaBeans (EJB) specification by using the java.io package."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The Enterprise JavaBeans specification requires that every bean provider follow a set of programming guidelines designed to ensure that the bean will be portable and behave consistently in any EJB container. In this case, the product violates the following EJB guideline: \"An enterprise bean must not use the java.io package to attempt to access files and directories in the file system.\" The specification justifies this requirement in the following way: \"The file system APIs are not well-suited for business components to access data. Business components should use a resource manager API, such as JDBC, to store data.\""
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product violates the Enterprise JavaBeans (EJB) specification by using the java.io package.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product violates the Enterprise JavaBeans (EJB) specification by using the java.io package.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThe Enterprise JavaBeans specification requires that every bean provider follow a set of programming guidelines designed to ensure that the bean will be portable and behave consistently in any EJB container. In this case, the product violates the following EJB guideline: \"An enterprise bean must not use the java.io package to attempt to access files and directories in the file system.\" The specification justifies this requirement in the following way: \"The file system APIs are not well-suited for business components to access data. Business components should use a resource manager API, such as JDBC, to store data.\"\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Do not use Java I/O when writing EJBs."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/576.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "EJB Bad Practices: Use of Java I/O",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-695"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-577",
              "name": "EjbBadPracticesUseOfSockets",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product violates the Enterprise JavaBeans (EJB) specification by using sockets."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The Enterprise JavaBeans specification requires that every bean provider follow a set of programming guidelines designed to ensure that the bean will be portable and behave consistently in any EJB container. In this case, the product violates the following EJB guideline: \"An enterprise bean must not attempt to listen on a socket, accept connections on a socket, or use a socket for multicast.\" The specification justifies this requirement in the following way: \"The EJB architecture allows an enterprise bean instance to be a network socket client, but it does not allow it to be a network server. Allowing the instance to become a network server would conflict with the basic function of the enterprise bean-- to serve the EJB clients.\""
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product violates the Enterprise JavaBeans (EJB) specification by using sockets.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product violates the Enterprise JavaBeans (EJB) specification by using sockets.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThe Enterprise JavaBeans specification requires that every bean provider follow a set of programming guidelines designed to ensure that the bean will be portable and behave consistently in any EJB container. In this case, the product violates the following EJB guideline: \"An enterprise bean must not attempt to listen on a socket, accept connections on a socket, or use a socket for multicast.\" The specification justifies this requirement in the following way: \"The EJB architecture allows an enterprise bean instance to be a network socket client, but it does not allow it to be a network server. Allowing the instance to become a network server would conflict with the basic function of the enterprise bean-- to serve the EJB clients.\"\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Implementation*. Do not use Sockets when writing EJBs."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/577.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "EJB Bad Practices: Use of Sockets",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-573"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-578",
              "name": "EjbBadPracticesUseOfClassLoader",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product violates the Enterprise JavaBeans (EJB) specification by using the class loader."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The Enterprise JavaBeans specification requires that every bean provider follow a set of programming guidelines designed to ensure that the bean will be portable and behave consistently in any EJB container. In this case, the product violates the following EJB guideline: \"The enterprise bean must not attempt to create a class loader; obtain the current class loader; set the context class loader; set security manager; create a new security manager; stop the JVM; or change the input, output, and error streams.\" The specification justifies this requirement in the following way: \"These functions are reserved for the EJB container. Allowing the enterprise bean to use these functions could compromise security and decrease the container's ability to properly manage the runtime environment.\""
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product violates the Enterprise JavaBeans (EJB) specification by using the class loader.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product violates the Enterprise JavaBeans (EJB) specification by using the class loader.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThe Enterprise JavaBeans specification requires that every bean provider follow a set of programming guidelines designed to ensure that the bean will be portable and behave consistently in any EJB container. In this case, the product violates the following EJB guideline: \"The enterprise bean must not attempt to create a class loader; obtain the current class loader; set the context class loader; set security manager; create a new security manager; stop the JVM; or change the input, output, and error streams.\" The specification justifies this requirement in the following way: \"These functions are reserved for the EJB container. Allowing the enterprise bean to use these functions could compromise security and decrease the container's ability to properly manage the runtime environment.\"\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability, Other. **Impact**: Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands, Varies by Context.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Implementation*. Do not use the Class Loader when writing EJBs."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/578.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "EJB Bad Practices: Use of Class Loader",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-573"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-579",
              "name": "J2eeBadPracticesNonSerializableObjectStoredInSession",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product stores a non-serializable object as an HttpSession attribute, which can hurt reliability."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "A J2EE application can make use of multiple JVMs in order to improve application reliability and performance. In order to make the multiple JVMs appear as a single application to the end user, the J2EE container can replicate an HttpSession object across multiple JVMs so that if one JVM becomes unavailable another can step in and take its place without disrupting the flow of the application. This is only possible if all session data is serializable, allowing the session to be duplicated between the JVMs."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product stores a non-serializable object as an HttpSession attribute, which can hurt reliability.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product stores a non-serializable object as an HttpSession attribute, which can hurt reliability.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nA J2EE application can make use of multiple JVMs in order to improve application reliability and performance. In order to make the multiple JVMs appear as a single application to the end user, the J2EE container can replicate an HttpSession object across multiple JVMs so that if one JVM becomes unavailable another can step in and take its place without disrupting the flow of the application. This is only possible if all session data is serializable, allowing the session to be duplicated between the JVMs.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. In order for session replication to work, the values the product stores as attributes in the session must implement the Serializable interface."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/579.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "J2EE Bad Practices: Non-serializable Object Stored in Session",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-573"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-580",
              "name": "CloneMethodWithoutSuperClone",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product contains a clone() method that does not call super.clone() to obtain the new object."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "All implementations of clone() should obtain the new object by calling super.clone(). If a class does not follow this convention, a subclass's clone() method will return an object of the wrong type."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product contains a clone() method that does not call super.clone() to obtain the new object.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product contains a clone() method that does not call super.clone() to obtain the new object.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nAll implementations of clone() should obtain the new object by calling super.clone(). If a class does not follow this convention, a subclass's clone() method will return an object of the wrong type.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Unexpected State, Quality Degradation.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Call super.clone() within your clone() method, when obtaining a new object.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. In some cases, you can eliminate the clone method altogether and use copy constructors."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/580.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "clone() Method Without super.clone()",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-664"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-581",
              "name": "ObjectModelViolationJustOneOfEqualsAndHashcodeDefined",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not maintain equal hashcodes for equal objects."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Java objects are expected to obey a number of invariants related to equality. One of these invariants is that equal objects must have equal hashcodes. In other words, if a.equals(b) == true then a.hashCode() == b.hashCode()."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not maintain equal hashcodes for equal objects.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not maintain equal hashcodes for equal objects.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nJava objects are expected to obey a number of invariants related to equality. One of these invariants is that equal objects must have equal hashcodes. In other words, if a.equals(b) == true then a.hashCode() == b.hashCode().\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Other.\n  - If this invariant is not upheld, it is likely to cause trouble if objects of this class are stored in a collection. If the objects of the class in question are used as a key in a Hashtable or if they are inserted into a Map or Set, it is critical that equal objects have equal hashcodes.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Both Equals() and Hashcode() should be defined."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/581.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Object Model Violation: Just One of Equals and Hashcode Defined",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-573"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-582",
              "name": "ArrayDeclaredPublicFinalAndStatic",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product declares an array public, final, and static, which is not sufficient to prevent the array's contents from being modified."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Because arrays are mutable objects, the final constraint requires that the array object itself be assigned only once, but makes no guarantees about the values of the array elements. Since the array is public, a malicious program can change the values stored in the array. As such, in most cases an array declared public, final and static is a bug."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product declares an array public, final, and static, which is not sufficient to prevent the array's contents from being modified.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product declares an array public, final, and static, which is not sufficient to prevent the array's contents from being modified.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nBecause arrays are mutable objects, the final constraint requires that the array object itself be assigned only once, but makes no guarantees about the values of the array elements. Since the array is public, a malicious program can change the values stored in the array. As such, in most cases an array declared public, final and static is a bug.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Modify Application Data.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. In most situations the array should be made private."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/582.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Array Declared Public, Final, and Static",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-668"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-583",
              "name": "FinalizeMethodDeclaredPublic",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product violates secure coding principles for mobile code by declaring a finalize() method public."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "A product should never call finalize explicitly, except to call super.finalize() inside an implementation of finalize(). In mobile code situations, the otherwise error prone practice of manual garbage collection can become a security threat if an attacker can maliciously invoke a finalize() method because it is declared with public access."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product violates secure coding principles for mobile code by declaring a finalize() method public.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product violates secure coding principles for mobile code by declaring a finalize() method public.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nA product should never call finalize explicitly, except to call super.finalize() inside an implementation of finalize(). In mobile code situations, the otherwise error prone practice of manual garbage collection can become a security threat if an attacker can maliciously invoke a finalize() method because it is declared with public access.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability. **Impact**: Alter Execution Logic, Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands, Modify Application Data.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. If you are using finalize() as it was designed, there is no reason to declare finalize() with anything other than protected access."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/583.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "finalize() Method Declared Public",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-668"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-584",
              "name": "ReturnInsideFinallyBlock",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The code has a return statement inside a finally block, which will cause any thrown exception in the try block to be discarded."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The code has a return statement inside a finally block, which will cause any thrown exception in the try block to be discarded.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code has a return statement inside a finally block, which will cause any thrown exception in the try block to be discarded.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Alter Execution Logic.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Do not use a return statement inside the finally block. The finally block should have \"cleanup\" code."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/584.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Return Inside Finally Block",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-705"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-585",
              "name": "EmptySynchronizedBlock",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product contains an empty synchronized block."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "An empty synchronized block does not actually accomplish any synchronization and may indicate a troubled section of code. An empty synchronized block can occur because code no longer needed within the synchronized block is commented out without removing the synchronized block."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product contains an empty synchronized block.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product contains an empty synchronized block.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nAn empty synchronized block does not actually accomplish any synchronization and may indicate a troubled section of code. An empty synchronized block can occur because code no longer needed within the synchronized block is commented out without removing the synchronized block.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Other.\n  - An empty synchronized block will wait until nobody else is using the synchronizer being specified. While this may be part of the desired behavior, because you haven't protected the subsequent code by placing it inside the synchronized block, nothing is stopping somebody else from modifying whatever it was you were waiting for while you run the subsequent code.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. When you come across an empty synchronized statement, or a synchronized statement in which the code has been commented out, try to determine what the original intentions were and whether or not the synchronized block is still necessary."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/585.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Empty Synchronized Block",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-1071"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-586",
              "name": "ExplicitCallToFinalize",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product makes an explicit call to the finalize() method from outside the finalizer."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "While the Java Language Specification allows an object's finalize() method to be called from outside the finalizer, doing so is usually a bad idea. For example, calling finalize() explicitly means that finalize() will be called more than once: the first time will be the explicit call and the last time will be the call that is made after the object is garbage collected."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product makes an explicit call to the finalize() method from outside the finalizer.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product makes an explicit call to the finalize() method from outside the finalizer.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nWhile the Java Language Specification allows an object's finalize() method to be called from outside the finalizer, doing so is usually a bad idea. For example, calling finalize() explicitly means that finalize() will be called more than once: the first time will be the explicit call and the last time will be the call that is made after the object is garbage collected.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Unexpected State, Quality Degradation.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Do not make explicit calls to finalize()."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/586.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Explicit Call to Finalize()",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-1076"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-587",
              "name": "AssignmentOfAFixedAddressToAPointer",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product sets a pointer to a specific address other than NULL or 0."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Using a fixed address is not portable, because that address will probably not be valid in all environments or platforms."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product sets a pointer to a specific address other than NULL or 0.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product sets a pointer to a specific address other than NULL or 0.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nUsing a fixed address is not portable, because that address will probably not be valid in all environments or platforms.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Confidentiality, Availability. **Impact**: Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands.\n  - If one executes code at a known location, an attacker might be able to inject code there beforehand.\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart, Reduce Maintainability, Reduce Reliability.\n  - If the code is ported to another platform or environment, the pointer is likely to be invalid and cause a crash.\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity. **Impact**: Read Memory, Modify Memory.\n  - The data at a known pointer location can be easily read or influenced by an attacker.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Never set a pointer to a fixed address."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/587.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Assignment of a Fixed Address to a Pointer",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-758"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-588",
              "name": "AttemptToAccessChildOfANonStructurePointer",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Casting a non-structure type to a structure type and accessing a field can lead to memory access errors or data corruption."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Casting a non-structure type to a structure type and accessing a field can lead to memory access errors or data corruption.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCasting a non-structure type to a structure type and accessing a field can lead to memory access errors or data corruption.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Modify Memory.\n  - Adjacent variables in memory may be corrupted by assignments performed on fields after the cast.\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart.\n  - Execution may end due to a memory access error.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Requirements*. The choice could be made to use a language that is not susceptible to these issues.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Review of type casting operations can identify locations where incompatible types are cast."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/588.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Attempt to Access Child of a Non-structure Pointer",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-704"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-589",
              "name": "CallToNonUbiquitousApi",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses an API function that does not exist on all versions of the target platform."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Some functions that offer security features supported by the OS are not available on all versions of the OS in common use. Likewise, functions are often deprecated or made obsolete for security reasons and should not be used."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses an API function that does not exist on all versions of the target platform. This could cause portability problems or inconsistencies that allow denial of service or other consequences.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses an API function that does not exist on all versions of the target platform. This could cause portability problems or inconsistencies that allow denial of service or other consequences.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nSome functions that offer security features supported by the OS are not available on all versions of the OS in common use. Likewise, functions are often deprecated or made obsolete for security reasons and should not be used.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Always test your code on any platform on which it is targeted to run on.\n2. *Phase: Testing*. Test your code on the newest and oldest platform on which it is targeted to run on.\n3. *Phase: Testing*. Develop a system to test for API functions that are not portable."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/589.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Call to Non-ubiquitous API",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-474"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-590",
              "name": "FreeOfMemoryNotOnTheHeap",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product calls free() on a pointer to memory that was not allocated using associated heap allocation functions such as malloc(), calloc(), or realloc()."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "When free() is called on an invalid pointer, the program's memory management data structures may become corrupted. This corruption can cause the program to crash or, in some circumstances, an attacker may be able to cause free() to operate on controllable memory locations to modify critical program variables or execute code."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product calls free() on a pointer to memory that was not allocated using associated heap allocation functions such as malloc(), calloc(), or realloc().",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product calls free() on a pointer to memory that was not allocated using associated heap allocation functions such as malloc(), calloc(), or realloc().\n\n## Extended Description\n\nWhen free() is called on an invalid pointer, the program's memory management data structures may become corrupted. This corruption can cause the program to crash or, in some circumstances, an attacker may be able to cause free() to operate on controllable memory locations to modify critical program variables or execute code.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Confidentiality, Availability. **Impact**: Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands, Modify Memory.\n  - There is the potential for arbitrary code execution with privileges of the vulnerable program via a \"write, what where\" primitive. If pointers to memory which hold user information are freed, a malicious user will be able to write 4 bytes anywhere in memory.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Only free pointers that you have called malloc on previously. This is the recommended solution. Keep track of which pointers point at the beginning of valid chunks and free them only once.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Before freeing a pointer, the programmer should make sure that the pointer was previously allocated on the heap and that the memory belongs to the programmer. Freeing an unallocated pointer will cause undefined behavior in the program.\n3. *Phase: Architecture and Design; Strategy: Libraries or Frameworks*. Use a vetted library or framework that does not allow this weakness to occur or provides constructs that make this weakness easier to avoid. For example, glibc in Linux provides protection against free of invalid pointers.\n4. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Use a language that provides abstractions for memory allocation and deallocation."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/590.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Free of Memory not on the Heap",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-762"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-591",
              "name": "SensitiveDataStorageInImproperlyLockedMemory",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product stores sensitive data in memory that is not locked, or that has been incorrectly locked, which might cause the memory to be written to swap files on disk by the virtual memory manager."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "On Windows systems the VirtualLock function can lock a page of memory to ensure that it will remain present in memory and not be swapped to disk. However, on older versions of Windows, such as 95, 98, or Me, the VirtualLock() function is only a stub and provides no protection. On POSIX systems the mlock() call ensures that a page will stay resident in memory but does not guarantee that the page will not appear in the swap. Therefore, it is unsuitable for use as a protection mechanism for sensitive data. Some platforms, in particular Linux, do make the guarantee that the page will not be swapped, but this is non-standard and is not portable. Calls to mlock() also require supervisor privilege. Return values for both of these calls must be checked to ensure that the lock operation was actually successful."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product stores sensitive data in memory that is not locked, or that has been incorrectly locked, which might cause the memory to be written to swap files on disk by the virtual memory manager. This can make the data more accessible to external actors.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product stores sensitive data in memory that is not locked, or that has been incorrectly locked, which might cause the memory to be written to swap files on disk by the virtual memory manager. This can make the data more accessible to external actors.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nOn Windows systems the VirtualLock function can lock a page of memory to ensure that it will remain present in memory and not be swapped to disk. However, on older versions of Windows, such as 95, 98, or Me, the VirtualLock() function is only a stub and provides no protection. On POSIX systems the mlock() call ensures that a page will stay resident in memory but does not guarantee that the page will not appear in the swap. Therefore, it is unsuitable for use as a protection mechanism for sensitive data. Some platforms, in particular Linux, do make the guarantee that the page will not be swapped, but this is non-standard and is not portable. Calls to mlock() also require supervisor privilege. Return values for both of these calls must be checked to ensure that the lock operation was actually successful.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data, Read Memory.\n  - Sensitive data that is written to a swap file may be exposed.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Identify data that needs to be protected from swapping and choose platform-appropriate protection mechanisms.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Check return values to ensure locking operations are successful."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/591.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Sensitive Data Storage in Improperly Locked Memory",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-413"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-592",
              "name": "DeprecatedAuthenticationBypassIssues",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "This weakness has been deprecated because it covered redundant concepts already described in CWE-287."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "This weakness has been deprecated because it covered redundant concepts already described in CWE-287.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis weakness has been deprecated because it covered redundant concepts already described in CWE-287."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/592.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "DEPRECATED: Authentication Bypass Issues",
                "cwe/status": "Deprecated",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-593",
              "name": "AuthenticationBypassOpensslCtxObjectModifiedAfterSslObjectsAreCreated",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product modifies the SSL context after connection creation has begun."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "If the program modifies the SSL_CTX object after creating SSL objects from it, there is the possibility that older SSL objects created from the original context could all be affected by that change."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product modifies the SSL context after connection creation has begun.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product modifies the SSL context after connection creation has begun.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIf the program modifies the SSL_CTX object after creating SSL objects from it, there is the possibility that older SSL objects created from the original context could all be affected by that change.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism.\n  - No authentication takes place in this process, bypassing an assumed protection of encryption.\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - The encrypted communication between a user and a trusted host may be subject to a sniffing attack.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Use a language or a library that provides a cryptography framework at a higher level of abstraction.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Most SSL_CTX functions have SSL counterparts that act on SSL-type objects.\n3. *Phase: Implementation*. Applications should set up an SSL_CTX completely, before creating SSL objects from it."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/593.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Authentication Bypass: OpenSSL CTX Object Modified after SSL Objects are Created",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-666"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-594",
              "name": "J2eeFrameworkSavingUnserializableObjectsToDisk",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "When the J2EE container attempts to write unserializable objects to disk there is no guarantee that the process will complete successfully."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In heavy load conditions, most J2EE application frameworks flush objects to disk to manage memory requirements of incoming requests. For example, session scoped objects, and even application scoped objects, are written to disk when required. While these application frameworks do the real work of writing objects to disk, they do not enforce that those objects be serializable, thus leaving the web application vulnerable to crashes induced by serialization failure. An attacker may be able to mount a denial of service attack by sending enough requests to the server to force the web application to save objects to disk."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "When the J2EE container attempts to write unserializable objects to disk there is no guarantee that the process will complete successfully.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nWhen the J2EE container attempts to write unserializable objects to disk there is no guarantee that the process will complete successfully.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIn heavy load conditions, most J2EE application frameworks flush objects to disk to manage memory requirements of incoming requests. For example, session scoped objects, and even application scoped objects, are written to disk when required. While these application frameworks do the real work of writing objects to disk, they do not enforce that those objects be serializable, thus leaving the web application vulnerable to crashes induced by serialization failure. An attacker may be able to mount a denial of service attack by sending enough requests to the server to force the web application to save objects to disk.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Modify Application Data.\n  - Data represented by unserializable objects can be corrupted.\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart.\n  - Non-serializability of objects can lead to system crash.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Implementation*. All objects that become part of session and application scope must implement the java.io.Serializable interface to ensure serializability of containing objects."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/594.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "J2EE Framework: Saving Unserializable Objects to Disk",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-1076"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-595",
              "name": "ComparisonOfObjectReferencesInsteadOfObjectContents",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product compares object references instead of the contents of the objects themselves, preventing it from detecting equivalent objects."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "For example, in Java, comparing objects using == usually produces deceptive results, since the == operator compares object references rather than values; often, this means that using == for strings is actually comparing the strings' references, not their values."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product compares object references instead of the contents of the objects themselves, preventing it from detecting equivalent objects.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product compares object references instead of the contents of the objects themselves, preventing it from detecting equivalent objects.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nFor example, in Java, comparing objects using == usually produces deceptive results, since the == operator compares object references rather than values; often, this means that using == for strings is actually comparing the strings' references, not their values.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Varies by Context.\n  - This weakness can lead to erroneous results that can cause unexpected application behaviors.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. In Java, use the equals() method to compare objects instead of the == operator. If using ==, it is important for performance reasons that your objects are created by a static factory, not by a constructor."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/595.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Comparison of Object References Instead of Object Contents",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-1025"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-596",
              "name": "DeprecatedIncorrectSemanticObjectComparison",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "This weakness has been deprecated."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "This weakness has been deprecated. It was poorly described and difficult to distinguish from other entries. It was also inappropriate to assign a separate ID solely because of domain-specific considerations. Its closest equivalent is CWE-1023.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis weakness has been deprecated. It was poorly described and difficult to distinguish from other entries. It was also inappropriate to assign a separate ID solely because of domain-specific considerations. Its closest equivalent is CWE-1023."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/596.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "DEPRECATED: Incorrect Semantic Object Comparison",
                "cwe/status": "Deprecated",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-597",
              "name": "UseOfWrongOperatorInStringComparison",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses the wrong operator when comparing a string, such as using \"==\" when the .equals() method should be used instead."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Java, using == or != to compare two strings for equality actually compares two objects for equality rather than their string values for equality. Chances are good that the two references will never be equal. While this weakness often only affects program correctness, if the equality is used for a security decision, the unintended comparison result could be leveraged to affect program security."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses the wrong operator when comparing a string, such as using \"==\" when the .equals() method should be used instead.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses the wrong operator when comparing a string, such as using \"==\" when the .equals() method should be used instead.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIn Java, using == or != to compare two strings for equality actually compares two objects for equality rather than their string values for equality. Chances are good that the two references will never be equal. While this weakness often only affects program correctness, if the equality is used for a security decision, the unintended comparison result could be leveraged to affect program security.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Other.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Within Java, use .equals() to compare string values. Within JavaScript, use == to compare string values. Within PHP, use == to compare a numeric value to a string value. (PHP converts the string to a number.)"
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/597.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Use of Wrong Operator in String Comparison",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-595"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-598",
              "name": "UseOfHttpRequestWithSensitiveQueryString",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The web application uses an HTTP method to process a request, but the request includes sensitive information in the query string."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The web application uses an HTTP method to process a request, but the request includes sensitive information in the query string.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe web application uses an HTTP method to process a request, but the request includes sensitive information in the query string.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - At a minimum, attackers can garner information from query strings that can be utilized in escalating their method of attack, such as information about the internal workings of the application or database column names. Successful exploitation of query string parameter vulnerabilities could lead to an attacker impersonating a legitimate user, obtaining proprietary data, or simply executing actions not intended by the application developers. Examples of sensitive information may include secrets such as session identifiers, passwords, access tokens, or API keys; Personally Identifiable Information (PII) such as email addresses or phone numbers; records or logs of private activities; communications that are expected to be private; etc. Successful exploitation of query string parameter vulnerabilities could lead to an attacker impersonating a legitimate user, obtaining proprietary data, or simply executing actions not intended by the application developers.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. When sending sensitive information, only include it in the request body or request headers instead of the query string. This may require avoiding use of GET requests."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/598.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Use of HTTP Request With Sensitive Query String",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-201"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-599",
              "name": "MissingValidationOfOpensslCertificate",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses OpenSSL and trusts or uses a certificate without using the SSL_get_verify_result() function to ensure that the certificate satisfies all necessary security requirements."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses OpenSSL and trusts or uses a certificate without using the SSL_get_verify_result() function to ensure that the certificate satisfies all necessary security requirements.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses OpenSSL and trusts or uses a certificate without using the SSL_get_verify_result() function to ensure that the certificate satisfies all necessary security requirements.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - The data read may not be properly secured - it might be viewed by an attacker.\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism, Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n  - Trust afforded to the system in question may allow for spoofing or redirection attacks.\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n  - If the certificate is not checked, it may be possible for a redirection or spoofing attack to allow a malicious host with a valid certificate to provide data under the guise of a trusted host. While the attacker in question may have a valid certificate, it may simply be a valid certificate for a different site. This could allow an attacker to use an invalid certificate to claim to be a trusted host, use expired certificates, or conduct other attacks that could be detected if the certificate is properly validated. In order to ensure data integrity, we must check that the certificate is valid, and that it pertains to the site we wish to access.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Ensure that proper authentication is included in the system design.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Understand and properly implement all checks necessary to ensure the identity of entities involved in encrypted communications."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/599.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Missing Validation of OpenSSL Certificate",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-295"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-600",
              "name": "UncaughtExceptionInServlet",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The Servlet does not catch all exceptions, which may reveal sensitive debugging information."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "When a Servlet throws an exception, the default error response the Servlet container sends back to the user typically includes debugging information. This information is of great value to an attacker. For example, a stack trace might show the attacker a malformed SQL query string, the type of database being used, and the version of the application container. This information enables the attacker to target known vulnerabilities in these components."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The Servlet does not catch all exceptions, which may reveal sensitive debugging information.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe Servlet does not catch all exceptions, which may reveal sensitive debugging information.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nWhen a Servlet throws an exception, the default error response the Servlet container sends back to the user typically includes debugging information. This information is of great value to an attacker. For example, a stack trace might show the attacker a malformed SQL query string, the type of database being used, and the version of the application container. This information enables the attacker to target known vulnerabilities in these components.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Availability. **Impact**: Read Application Data, DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Implement Exception blocks to handle all types of Exceptions."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/600.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Uncaught Exception in Servlet",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-248"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-601",
              "name": "OpenRedirect",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The web application accepts a user-controlled input that specifies a link to an external site, and uses that link in a redirect."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The web application accepts a user-controlled input that specifies a link to an external site, and uses that link in a redirect.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe web application accepts a user-controlled input that specifies a link to an external site, and uses that link in a redirect.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism, Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n  - The user may be redirected to an untrusted page that contains malware which may then compromise the user's system. In some cases, an open redirect can also enable the immediate download of a file without the user's permission, because the redirection to an external site may lead to endpoints on those sites that automatically trigger a download action (\"drive-by download\" [REF-1478]). This will expose the user to extensive risk. The user's interaction with the web server may also be compromised if the malware conducts keylogging or other attacks that steal credentials, personally identifiable information (PII), or other important data.\n- **Scope**: Access Control, Confidentiality, Other. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism, Gain Privileges or Assume Identity, Other.\n  - By modifying the URL value to a malicious site, an attacker may successfully launch a phishing scam. The user may be subjected to phishing attacks by being redirected to an untrusted page. The phishing attack may point to an attacker controlled web page that appears to be a trusted web site. The phishers may then steal the user's credentials and then use these credentials to access the legitimate web site. Because the server name in the modified link is identical to the original site, phishing attempts have a more trustworthy appearance.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation; Strategy: Input Validation*. Assume all input is malicious. Use an \"accept known good\" input validation strategy, i.e., use a list of acceptable inputs that strictly conform to specifications. Reject any input that does not strictly conform to specifications, or transform it into something that does. When performing input validation, consider all potentially relevant properties, including length, type of input, the full range of acceptable values, missing or extra inputs, syntax, consistency across related fields, and conformance to business rules. As an example of business rule logic, \"boat\" may be syntactically valid because it only contains alphanumeric characters, but it is not valid if the input is only expected to contain colors such as \"red\" or \"blue.\" Do not rely exclusively on looking for malicious or malformed inputs. This is likely to miss at least one undesirable input, especially if the code's environment changes. This can give attackers enough room to bypass the intended validation. However, denylists can be useful for detecting potential attacks or determining which inputs are so malformed that they should be rejected outright. Use a list of approved URLs or domains to be used for redirection.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Use an intermediate disclaimer page that provides the user with a clear warning that they are leaving the current site. Implement a long timeout before the redirect occurs, or force the user to click on the link. Be careful to avoid XSS problems (CWE-79) when generating the disclaimer page.\n3. *Phase: Architecture and Design; Strategy: Enforcement by Conversion*. When the set of acceptable objects, such as filenames or URLs, is limited or known, create a mapping from a set of fixed input values (such as numeric IDs) to the actual filenames or URLs, and reject all other inputs. For example, ID 1 could map to \"/login.asp\" and ID 2 could map to \"http://www.example.com/\". Features such as the ESAPI AccessReferenceMap [REF-45] provide this capability.\n4. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Ensure that no externally-supplied requests are honored by requiring that all redirect requests include a unique nonce generated by the application [REF-483]. Be sure that the nonce is not predictable (CWE-330).\n5. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Implementation; Strategy: Attack Surface Reduction*. Understand all the potential areas where untrusted inputs can enter your software: parameters or arguments, cookies, anything read from the network, environment variables, reverse DNS lookups, query results, request headers, URL components, e-mail, files, filenames, databases, and any external systems that provide data to the application. Remember that such inputs may be obtained indirectly through API calls. Many open redirect problems occur because the programmer assumed that certain inputs could not be modified, such as cookies and hidden form fields.\n6. *Phase: Operation; Strategy: Firewall*. Use an application firewall that can detect attacks against this weakness. It can be beneficial in cases in which the code cannot be fixed (because it is controlled by a third party), as an emergency prevention measure while more comprehensive software assurance measures are applied, or to provide defense in depth [REF-1481]."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/601.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "URL Redirection to Untrusted Site ('Open Redirect')",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-610"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-602",
              "name": "ClientSideEnforcementOfServerSideSecurity",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product is composed of a server that relies on the client to implement a mechanism that is intended to protect the server."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "When the server relies on protection mechanisms placed on the client side, an attacker can modify the client-side behavior to bypass the protection mechanisms, resulting in potentially unexpected interactions between the client and server. The consequences will vary, depending on what the mechanisms are trying to protect."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product is composed of a server that relies on the client to implement a mechanism that is intended to protect the server.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product is composed of a server that relies on the client to implement a mechanism that is intended to protect the server.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nWhen the server relies on protection mechanisms placed on the client side, an attacker can modify the client-side behavior to bypass the protection mechanisms, resulting in potentially unexpected interactions between the client and server. The consequences will vary, depending on what the mechanisms are trying to protect.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control, Availability. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism, DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart.\n  - Client-side validation checks can be easily bypassed, allowing malformed or unexpected input to pass into the application, potentially as trusted data. This may lead to unexpected states, behaviors and possibly a resulting crash.\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism, Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n  - Client-side checks for authentication can be easily bypassed, allowing clients to escalate their access levels and perform unintended actions.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. For any security checks that are performed on the client side, ensure that these checks are duplicated on the server side. Attackers can bypass the client-side checks by modifying values after the checks have been performed, or by changing the client to remove the client-side checks entirely. Then, these modified values would be submitted to the server. Even though client-side checks provide minimal benefits with respect to server-side security, they are still useful. First, they can support intrusion detection. If the server receives input that should have been rejected by the client, then it may be an indication of an attack. Second, client-side error-checking can provide helpful feedback to the user about the expectations for valid input. Third, there may be a reduction in server-side processing time for accidental input errors, although this is typically a small savings.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. If some degree of trust is required between the two entities, then use integrity checking and strong authentication to ensure that the inputs are coming from a trusted source. Design the product so that this trust is managed in a centralized fashion, especially if there are complex or numerous communication channels, in order to reduce the risks that the implementer will mistakenly omit a check in a single code path."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/602.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Client-Side Enforcement of Server-Side Security",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-693"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-603",
              "name": "UseOfClientSideAuthentication",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A client/server product performs authentication within client code but not in server code, allowing server-side authentication to be bypassed via a modified client that omits the authentication check."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Client-side authentication is extremely weak and may be breached easily. Any attacker may read the source code and reverse-engineer the authentication mechanism to access parts of the application which would otherwise be protected."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "A client/server product performs authentication within client code but not in server code, allowing server-side authentication to be bypassed via a modified client that omits the authentication check.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA client/server product performs authentication within client code but not in server code, allowing server-side authentication to be bypassed via a modified client that omits the authentication check.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nClient-side authentication is extremely weak and may be breached easily. Any attacker may read the source code and reverse-engineer the authentication mechanism to access parts of the application which would otherwise be protected.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism, Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Do not rely on client side data. Always perform server side authentication."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/603.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Use of Client-Side Authentication",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-1390"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-605",
              "name": "MultipleBindsToTheSamePort",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "When multiple sockets are allowed to bind to the same port, other services on that port may be stolen or spoofed."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "On most systems, a combination of setting the SO_REUSEADDR socket option, and a call to bind() allows any process to bind to a port to which a previous process has bound with INADDR_ANY. This allows a user to bind to the specific address of a server bound to INADDR_ANY on an unprivileged port, and steal its UDP packets/TCP connection."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "When multiple sockets are allowed to bind to the same port, other services on that port may be stolen or spoofed.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nWhen multiple sockets are allowed to bind to the same port, other services on that port may be stolen or spoofed.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nOn most systems, a combination of setting the SO_REUSEADDR socket option, and a call to bind() allows any process to bind to a port to which a previous process has bound with INADDR_ANY. This allows a user to bind to the specific address of a server bound to INADDR_ANY on an unprivileged port, and steal its UDP packets/TCP connection.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - Packets from a variety of network services may be stolen or the services spoofed.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Policy*. Restrict server socket address to known local addresses."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/605.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Multiple Binds to the Same Port",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-675"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-606",
              "name": "UncheckedInputForLoopCondition",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not properly check inputs that are used for loop conditions, potentially leading to a denial of service or other consequences because of excessive looping."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not properly check inputs that are used for loop conditions, potentially leading to a denial of service or other consequences because of excessive looping.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not properly check inputs that are used for loop conditions, potentially leading to a denial of service or other consequences because of excessive looping.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Resource Consumption (CPU).\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Do not use user-controlled data for loop conditions.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Perform input validation."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/606.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Unchecked Input for Loop Condition",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-1284"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-607",
              "name": "PublicStaticFinalFieldReferencesMutableObject",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A public or protected static final field references a mutable object, which allows the object to be changed by malicious code, or accidentally from another package."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "A public or protected static final field references a mutable object, which allows the object to be changed by malicious code, or accidentally from another package.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA public or protected static final field references a mutable object, which allows the object to be changed by malicious code, or accidentally from another package.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Modify Application Data.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Protect mutable objects by making them private. Restrict access to the getter and setter as well."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/607.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Public Static Final Field References Mutable Object",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-471"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-608",
              "name": "StrutsNonPrivateFieldInActionformClass",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "An ActionForm class contains a field that has not been declared private, which can be accessed without using a setter or getter."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "An ActionForm class contains a field that has not been declared private, which can be accessed without using a setter or getter.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nAn ActionForm class contains a field that has not been declared private, which can be accessed without using a setter or getter.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Confidentiality. **Impact**: Modify Application Data, Read Application Data.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Make all fields private. Use getter to get the value of the field. Setter should be used only by the framework; setting an action form field from other actions is bad practice and should be avoided."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/608.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Struts: Non-private Field in ActionForm Class",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-668"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-609",
              "name": "DoubleCheckedLocking",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses double-checked locking to access a resource without the overhead of explicit synchronization, but the locking is insufficient."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Double-checked locking refers to the situation where a programmer checks to see if a resource has been initialized, grabs a lock, checks again to see if the resource has been initialized, and then performs the initialization if it has not occurred yet. This should not be done, as it is not guaranteed to work in all languages and on all architectures. In summary, other threads may not be operating inside the synchronous block and are not guaranteed to see the operations execute in the same order as they would appear inside the synchronous block."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses double-checked locking to access a resource without the overhead of explicit synchronization, but the locking is insufficient.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses double-checked locking to access a resource without the overhead of explicit synchronization, but the locking is insufficient.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nDouble-checked locking refers to the situation where a programmer checks to see if a resource has been initialized, grabs a lock, checks again to see if the resource has been initialized, and then performs the initialization if it has not occurred yet. This should not be done, as it is not guaranteed to work in all languages and on all architectures. In summary, other threads may not be operating inside the synchronous block and are not guaranteed to see the operations execute in the same order as they would appear inside the synchronous block.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Modify Application Data, Alter Execution Logic.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. While double-checked locking can be achieved in some languages, it is inherently flawed in Java before 1.5, and cannot be achieved without compromising platform independence. Before Java 1.5, only use of the synchronized keyword is known to work. Beginning in Java 1.5, use of the \"volatile\" keyword allows double-checked locking to work successfully, although there is some debate as to whether it achieves sufficient performance gains. See references."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/609.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Double-Checked Locking",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-667"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-610",
              "name": "ExternallyControlledReferenceToAResourceInAnotherSphere",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses an externally controlled name or reference that resolves to a resource that is outside of the intended control sphere."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses an externally controlled name or reference that resolves to a resource that is outside of the intended control sphere.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses an externally controlled name or reference that resolves to a resource that is outside of the intended control sphere.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity. **Impact**: Read Application Data, Modify Application Data.\n  - An adversary could read or modify data, depending on how the resource is intended to be used.\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n  - An adversary that can supply a reference to an unintended resource can potentially access a resource that they do not have privileges for, thus bypassing existing access control mechanisms."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/610.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Externally Controlled Reference to a Resource in Another Sphere",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-664"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-611",
              "name": "ImproperRestrictionOfXmlExternalEntityReference",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product processes an XML document that can contain XML entities with URIs that resolve to documents outside of the intended sphere of control, causing the product to embed incorrect documents into its output."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product processes an XML document that can contain XML entities with URIs that resolve to documents outside of the intended sphere of control, causing the product to embed incorrect documents into its output.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product processes an XML document that can contain XML entities with URIs that resolve to documents outside of the intended sphere of control, causing the product to embed incorrect documents into its output.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data, Read Files or Directories.\n  - If the attacker is able to include a crafted DTD and a default entity resolver is enabled, the attacker may be able to access arbitrary files on the system. By submitting an XML file that defines an external entity with a file:// URI, an attacker can cause the processing application to read the contents of a local file. For example, a URI such as \"file:///c:/winnt/win.ini\" designates (in Windows) the file C:\\Winnt\\win.ini, or file:///etc/passwd designates the password file in Unix-based systems. Once the content of the URI is read, it is fed back into the application that is processing the XML. This application may echo back the data (e.g., in an error message), thereby exposing the file contents.\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism.\n  - An attacker may supply a crafted DTD using URIs with schemes such as http://, forcing the application to make outgoing HTTP requests to servers that the attacker cannot reach directly, which can be used to bypass firewall restrictions; hide the source of attacks such as port scanning; or otherwise leverage the server's trust relationship with other entities.\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Resource Consumption (CPU), DoS: Resource Consumption (Memory).\n  - The product could consume excessive CPU cycles or memory using a URI that points to a large file, or a device that always returns data such as /dev/random. Alternately, the URI could reference a file that contains many nested or recursive entity references to further slow down parsing.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation, System Configuration*. Many XML parsers and validators can be configured to disable external entity expansion."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/611.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Improper Restriction of XML External Entity Reference",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-610"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-612",
              "name": "ImproperAuthorizationOfIndexContainingSensitiveInformation",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product creates a search index of private or sensitive documents, but it does not properly limit index access to actors who are authorized to see the original information."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Web sites and other document repositories may apply an indexing routine against a group of private documents to facilitate search. If the index's results are available to parties who do not have access to the documents being indexed, then attackers could obtain portions of the documents by conducting targeted searches and reading the results. The risk is especially dangerous if search results include surrounding text that was not part of the search query. This issue can appear in search engines that are not configured (or implemented) to ignore critical files that should remain hidden; even without permissions to download these files directly, the remote user could read them."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product creates a search index of private or sensitive documents, but it does not properly limit index access to actors who are authorized to see the original information.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product creates a search index of private or sensitive documents, but it does not properly limit index access to actors who are authorized to see the original information.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nWeb sites and other document repositories may apply an indexing routine against a group of private documents to facilitate search. If the index's results are available to parties who do not have access to the documents being indexed, then attackers could obtain portions of the documents by conducting targeted searches and reading the results. The risk is especially dangerous if search results include surrounding text that was not part of the search query. This issue can appear in search engines that are not configured (or implemented) to ignore critical files that should remain hidden; even without permissions to download these files directly, the remote user could read them.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/612.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Improper Authorization of Index Containing Sensitive Information",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-1230"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-613",
              "name": "InsufficientSessionExpiration",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "According to WASC, \"Insufficient Session Expiration is when a web site permits an attacker to reuse old session credentials or session IDs for authorization.\""
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "According to WASC, \"Insufficient Session Expiration is when a web site permits an attacker to reuse old session credentials or session IDs for authorization.\"",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nAccording to WASC, \"Insufficient Session Expiration is when a web site permits an attacker to reuse old session credentials or session IDs for authorization.\"\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Set sessions/credentials expiration date."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/613.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Insufficient Session Expiration",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-672"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-614",
              "name": "SensitiveCookieInHttpsSessionWithoutSecureAttribute",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The Secure attribute for sensitive cookies in HTTPS sessions is not set."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The Secure attribute for sensitive cookies in HTTPS sessions is not set.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe Secure attribute for sensitive cookies in HTTPS sessions is not set.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - Omitting the secure flag makes it possible for the user agent to send the cookies in plaintext over an HTTP session.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Always set the secure attribute when the cookie should be sent via HTTPS only."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-319"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-615",
              "name": "InclusionOfSensitiveInformationInSourceCodeComments",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "While adding general comments is very useful, some programmers tend to leave important data, such as: filenames related to the web application, old links or links which were not meant to be browsed by users, old code fragments, etc."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "An attacker who finds these comments can map the application's structure and files, expose hidden parts of the site, and study the fragments of code to reverse engineer the application, which may help develop further attacks against the site."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "While adding general comments is very useful, some programmers tend to leave important data, such as: filenames related to the web application, old links or links which were not meant to be browsed by users, old code fragments, etc.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nWhile adding general comments is very useful, some programmers tend to leave important data, such as: filenames related to the web application, old links or links which were not meant to be browsed by users, old code fragments, etc.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nAn attacker who finds these comments can map the application's structure and files, expose hidden parts of the site, and study the fragments of code to reverse engineer the application, which may help develop further attacks against the site.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Distribution*. Remove comments which have sensitive information about the design/implementation of the application. Some of the comments may be exposed to the user and affect the security posture of the application."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/615.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Inclusion of Sensitive Information in Source Code Comments",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-540"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-616",
              "name": "IncompleteIdentificationOfUploadedFileVariablesPhp",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The PHP application uses an old method for processing uploaded files by referencing the four global variables that are set for each file (e.g."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "These global variables could be overwritten by POST requests, cookies, or other methods of populating or overwriting these variables. This could be used to read or process arbitrary files by providing values such as \"/etc/passwd\"."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The PHP application uses an old method for processing uploaded files by referencing the four global variables that are set for each file (e.g. $varname, $varname_size, $varname_name, $varname_type). These variables could be overwritten by attackers, causing the application to process unauthorized files.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe PHP application uses an old method for processing uploaded files by referencing the four global variables that are set for each file (e.g. $varname, $varname_size, $varname_name, $varname_type). These variables could be overwritten by attackers, causing the application to process unauthorized files.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThese global variables could be overwritten by POST requests, cookies, or other methods of populating or overwriting these variables. This could be used to read or process arbitrary files by providing values such as \"/etc/passwd\".\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity. **Impact**: Read Files or Directories, Modify Files or Directories.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Use PHP 4 or later.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. If you must support older PHP versions, write your own version of is_uploaded_file() and run it against $HTTP_POST_FILES['userfile']))\n3. *Phase: Implementation*. For later PHP versions, reference uploaded files using the $HTTP_POST_FILES or $_FILES variables, and use is_uploaded_file() or move_uploaded_file() to ensure that you are dealing with an uploaded file."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/616.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Incomplete Identification of Uploaded File Variables (PHP)",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-345"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-617",
              "name": "ReachableAssertion",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product contains an assert() or similar statement that can be triggered by an attacker, which leads to an application exit or other behavior that is more severe than necessary."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "While assertion is good for catching logic errors and reducing the chances of reaching more serious vulnerability conditions, it can still lead to a denial of service. For example, if a server handles multiple simultaneous connections, and an assert() occurs in one single connection that causes all other connections to be dropped, this is a reachable assertion that leads to a denial of service."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product contains an assert() or similar statement that can be triggered by an attacker, which leads to an application exit or other behavior that is more severe than necessary.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product contains an assert() or similar statement that can be triggered by an attacker, which leads to an application exit or other behavior that is more severe than necessary.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nWhile assertion is good for catching logic errors and reducing the chances of reaching more serious vulnerability conditions, it can still lead to a denial of service. For example, if a server handles multiple simultaneous connections, and an assert() occurs in one single connection that causes all other connections to be dropped, this is a reachable assertion that leads to a denial of service.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart.\n  - An attacker that can trigger an assert statement can still lead to a denial of service if the relevant code can be triggered by an attacker, and if the scope of the assert() extends beyond the attacker's own session.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Make sensitive open/close operation non reachable by directly user-controlled data (e.g. open/close resources)\n2. *Phase: Implementation; Strategy: Input Validation*. Perform input validation on user data."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/617.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Reachable Assertion",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-705"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-618",
              "name": "ExposedUnsafeActivexMethod",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "An ActiveX control is intended for use in a web browser, but it exposes dangerous methods that perform actions that are outside of the browser's security model (e.g."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "ActiveX controls can exercise far greater control over the operating system than typical Java or javascript. Exposed methods can be subject to various vulnerabilities, depending on the implemented behaviors of those methods, and whether input validation is performed on the provided arguments. If there is no integrity checking or origin validation, this method could be invoked by attackers."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "An ActiveX control is intended for use in a web browser, but it exposes dangerous methods that perform actions that are outside of the browser's security model (e.g. the zone or domain).",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nAn ActiveX control is intended for use in a web browser, but it exposes dangerous methods that perform actions that are outside of the browser's security model (e.g. the zone or domain).\n\n## Extended Description\n\nActiveX controls can exercise far greater control over the operating system than typical Java or javascript. Exposed methods can be subject to various vulnerabilities, depending on the implemented behaviors of those methods, and whether input validation is performed on the provided arguments. If there is no integrity checking or origin validation, this method could be invoked by attackers.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Other.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. If you must expose a method, make sure to perform input validation on all arguments, and protect against all possible vulnerabilities.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Use code signing, although this does not protect against any weaknesses that are already in the control.\n3. *Phase: Architecture and Design, System Configuration*. Where possible, avoid marking the control as safe for scripting."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/618.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Exposed Unsafe ActiveX Method",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-749"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-619",
              "name": "CursorInjection",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "If a database cursor is not closed properly, then it could become accessible to other users while retaining the same privileges that were originally assigned, leaving the cursor \"dangling.\""
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "For example, an improper dangling cursor could arise from unhandled exceptions. The impact of the issue depends on the cursor's role, but SQL injection attacks are commonly possible."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "If a database cursor is not closed properly, then it could become accessible to other users while retaining the same privileges that were originally assigned, leaving the cursor \"dangling.\"",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIf a database cursor is not closed properly, then it could become accessible to other users while retaining the same privileges that were originally assigned, leaving the cursor \"dangling.\"\n\n## Extended Description\n\nFor example, an improper dangling cursor could arise from unhandled exceptions. The impact of the issue depends on the cursor's role, but SQL injection attacks are commonly possible.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity. **Impact**: Read Application Data, Modify Application Data.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Close cursors immediately after access to them is complete. Ensure that you close cursors if exceptions occur."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/619.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Dangling Database Cursor ('Cursor Injection')",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-402"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-620",
              "name": "UnverifiedPasswordChange",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "When setting a new password for a user, the product does not require knowledge of the original password, or using another form of authentication."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "This could be used by an attacker to change passwords for another user, thus gaining the privileges associated with that user."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "When setting a new password for a user, the product does not require knowledge of the original password, or using another form of authentication.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nWhen setting a new password for a user, the product does not require knowledge of the original password, or using another form of authentication.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThis could be used by an attacker to change passwords for another user, thus gaining the privileges associated with that user.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism, Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. When prompting for a password change, force the user to provide the original password in addition to the new password.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Do not use \"forgotten password\" functionality. But if you must, ensure that you are only providing information to the actual user, e.g. by using an email address or challenge question that the legitimate user already provided in the past; do not allow the current user to change this identity information until the correct password has been provided."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/620.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Unverified Password Change",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-1390"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-621",
              "name": "VariableExtractionError",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses external input to determine the names of variables into which information is extracted, without verifying that the names of the specified variables are valid."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "For example, in PHP, extraction can be used to provide functionality similar to register_globals, a dangerous functionality that is frequently disabled in production systems. Calling extract() or import_request_variables() without the proper arguments could allow arbitrary global variables to be overwritten, including superglobals. Similar functionality is possible in other interpreted languages, including custom languages."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses external input to determine the names of variables into which information is extracted, without verifying that the names of the specified variables are valid. This could cause the program to overwrite unintended variables.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses external input to determine the names of variables into which information is extracted, without verifying that the names of the specified variables are valid. This could cause the program to overwrite unintended variables.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nFor example, in PHP, extraction can be used to provide functionality similar to register_globals, a dangerous functionality that is frequently disabled in production systems. Calling extract() or import_request_variables() without the proper arguments could allow arbitrary global variables to be overwritten, including superglobals. Similar functionality is possible in other interpreted languages, including custom languages.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Modify Application Data.\n  - An attacker could modify sensitive data or program variables.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation; Strategy: Input Validation*. Use allowlists of variable names that can be extracted.\n2. *Phase: Implementation; Strategy: Refactoring*. Consider refactoring your code to avoid extraction routines altogether.\n3. *Phase: Implementation*. In PHP, call extract() with options such as EXTR_SKIP and EXTR_PREFIX_ALL; call import_request_variables() with a prefix argument. Note that these capabilities are not present in all PHP versions."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/621.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Variable Extraction Error",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-914"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-622",
              "name": "ImproperValidationOfFunctionHookArguments",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product adds hooks to user-accessible API functions, but it does not properly validate the arguments."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Such hooks can be used in defensive software that runs with privileges, such as anti-virus or firewall, which hooks kernel calls. When the arguments are not validated, they could be used to bypass the protection scheme or attack the product itself."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product adds hooks to user-accessible API functions, but it does not properly validate the arguments. This could lead to resultant vulnerabilities.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product adds hooks to user-accessible API functions, but it does not properly validate the arguments. This could lead to resultant vulnerabilities.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nSuch hooks can be used in defensive software that runs with privileges, such as anti-virus or firewall, which hooks kernel calls. When the arguments are not validated, they could be used to bypass the protection scheme or attack the product itself.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Unexpected State.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Ensure that all arguments are verified, as defined by the API you are protecting.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Drop privileges before invoking such functions, if possible."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/622.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Improper Validation of Function Hook Arguments",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-20"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-623",
              "name": "UnsafeActivexControlMarkedSafeForScripting",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "An ActiveX control is intended for restricted use, but it has been marked as safe-for-scripting."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "This might allow attackers to use dangerous functionality via a web page that accesses the control, which can lead to different resultant vulnerabilities, depending on the control's behavior."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "An ActiveX control is intended for restricted use, but it has been marked as safe-for-scripting.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nAn ActiveX control is intended for restricted use, but it has been marked as safe-for-scripting.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThis might allow attackers to use dangerous functionality via a web page that accesses the control, which can lead to different resultant vulnerabilities, depending on the control's behavior.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability. **Impact**: Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. During development, do not mark it as safe for scripting.\n2. *Phase: System Configuration*. After distribution, you can set the kill bit for the control so that it is not accessible from Internet Explorer."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/623.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Unsafe ActiveX Control Marked Safe For Scripting",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-267"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-624",
              "name": "ExecutableRegularExpressionError",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses a regular expression that either (1) contains an executable component with user-controlled inputs, or (2) allows a user to enable execution by inserting pattern modifiers."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Case (2) is possible in the PHP preg_replace() function, and possibly in other languages when a user-controlled input is inserted into a string that is later parsed as a regular expression."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses a regular expression that either (1) contains an executable component with user-controlled inputs, or (2) allows a user to enable execution by inserting pattern modifiers.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses a regular expression that either (1) contains an executable component with user-controlled inputs, or (2) allows a user to enable execution by inserting pattern modifiers.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nCase (2) is possible in the PHP preg_replace() function, and possibly in other languages when a user-controlled input is inserted into a string that is later parsed as a regular expression.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability. **Impact**: Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. The regular expression feature in some languages allows inputs to be quoted or escaped before insertion, such as \\Q and \\E in Perl."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/624.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Executable Regular Expression Error",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-77"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-625",
              "name": "PermissiveRegularExpression",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses a regular expression that does not sufficiently restrict the set of allowed values."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "This effectively causes the regexp to accept substrings that match the pattern, which produces a partial comparison to the target. In some cases, this can lead to other weaknesses. Common errors include: not identifying the beginning and end of the target string using wildcards instead of acceptable character ranges others"
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses a regular expression that does not sufficiently restrict the set of allowed values.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses a regular expression that does not sufficiently restrict the set of allowed values.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThis effectively causes the regexp to accept substrings that match the pattern, which produces a partial comparison to the target. In some cases, this can lead to other weaknesses. Common errors include: not identifying the beginning and end of the target string using wildcards instead of acceptable character ranges others\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. When applicable, ensure that the regular expression marks beginning and ending string patterns, such as \"/^string$/\" for Perl."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/625.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Permissive Regular Expression",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-185"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-626",
              "name": "NullByteInteractionErrorPoisonNullByte",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not properly handle null bytes or NUL characters when passing data between different representations or components."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "A null byte (NUL character) can have different meanings across representations or languages. For example, it is a string terminator in standard C libraries, but Perl and PHP strings do not treat it as a terminator. When two representations are crossed - such as when Perl or PHP invokes underlying C functionality - this can produce an interaction error with unexpected results. Similar issues have been reported for ASP. Other interpreters written in C might also be affected. The poison null byte is frequently useful in path traversal attacks by terminating hard-coded extensions that are added to a filename. It can play a role in regular expression processing in PHP."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not properly handle null bytes or NUL characters when passing data between different representations or components.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not properly handle null bytes or NUL characters when passing data between different representations or components.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nA null byte (NUL character) can have different meanings across representations or languages. For example, it is a string terminator in standard C libraries, but Perl and PHP strings do not treat it as a terminator. When two representations are crossed - such as when Perl or PHP invokes underlying C functionality - this can produce an interaction error with unexpected results. Similar issues have been reported for ASP. Other interpreters written in C might also be affected. The poison null byte is frequently useful in path traversal attacks by terminating hard-coded extensions that are added to a filename. It can play a role in regular expression processing in PHP.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Unexpected State.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Remove null bytes from all incoming strings."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/626.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Null Byte Interaction Error (Poison Null Byte)",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-147"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-627",
              "name": "DynamicVariableEvaluation",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "In a language where the user can influence the name of a variable at runtime, if the variable names are not controlled, an attacker can read or write to arbitrary variables, or access arbitrary functions."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The resultant vulnerabilities depend on the behavior of the application, both at the crossover point and in any control/data flow that is reachable by the related variables or functions."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "In a language where the user can influence the name of a variable at runtime, if the variable names are not controlled, an attacker can read or write to arbitrary variables, or access arbitrary functions.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn a language where the user can influence the name of a variable at runtime, if the variable names are not controlled, an attacker can read or write to arbitrary variables, or access arbitrary functions.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThe resultant vulnerabilities depend on the behavior of the application, both at the crossover point and in any control/data flow that is reachable by the related variables or functions.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability. **Impact**: Modify Application Data, Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands.\n  - An attacker could gain unauthorized access to internal program variables and execute arbitrary code.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation; Strategy: Refactoring*. Refactor the code to avoid dynamic variable evaluation whenever possible.\n2. *Phase: Implementation; Strategy: Input Validation*. Use only allowlists of acceptable variable or function names.\n3. *Phase: Implementation*. For function names, ensure that you are only calling functions that accept the proper number of arguments, to avoid unexpected null arguments."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/627.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Dynamic Variable Evaluation",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-914"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-628",
              "name": "FunctionCallWithIncorrectlySpecifiedArguments",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product calls a function, procedure, or routine with arguments that are not correctly specified, leading to always-incorrect behavior and resultant weaknesses."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "There are multiple ways in which this weakness can be introduced, including: the wrong variable or reference; an incorrect number of arguments; incorrect order of arguments; wrong type of arguments; or wrong value."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product calls a function, procedure, or routine with arguments that are not correctly specified, leading to always-incorrect behavior and resultant weaknesses.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product calls a function, procedure, or routine with arguments that are not correctly specified, leading to always-incorrect behavior and resultant weaknesses.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThere are multiple ways in which this weakness can be introduced, including: the wrong variable or reference; an incorrect number of arguments; incorrect order of arguments; wrong type of arguments; or wrong value.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other, Access Control. **Impact**: Quality Degradation, Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n  - This weakness can cause unintended behavior and can lead to additional weaknesses such as allowing an attacker to gain unintended access to system resources.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Build and Compilation*. Once found, these issues are easy to fix. Use code inspection tools and relevant compiler features to identify potential violations. Pay special attention to code that is not likely to be exercised heavily during QA.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Make sure your API's are stable before you use them in production code."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/628.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Function Call with Incorrectly Specified Arguments",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-573"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-636",
              "name": "FailingOpen",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "When the product encounters an error condition or failure, its design requires it to fall back to a state that is less secure than other options that are available, such as selecting the weakest encryption algorithm or using the most permissive access control restrictions."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "By entering a less secure state, the product inherits the weaknesses associated with that state, making it easier to compromise. At the least, it causes administrators to have a false sense of security. This weakness typically occurs as a result of wanting to \"fail functional\" to minimize administration and support costs, instead of \"failing safe.\""
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "When the product encounters an error condition or failure, its design requires it to fall back to a state that is less secure than other options that are available, such as selecting the weakest encryption algorithm or using the most permissive access control restrictions.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nWhen the product encounters an error condition or failure, its design requires it to fall back to a state that is less secure than other options that are available, such as selecting the weakest encryption algorithm or using the most permissive access control restrictions.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nBy entering a less secure state, the product inherits the weaknesses associated with that state, making it easier to compromise. At the least, it causes administrators to have a false sense of security. This weakness typically occurs as a result of wanting to \"fail functional\" to minimize administration and support costs, instead of \"failing safe.\"\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism.\n  - Intended access restrictions can be bypassed, which is often contradictory to what the product's administrator expects.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Subdivide and allocate resources and components so that a failure in one part does not affect the entire product."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/636.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Not Failing Securely ('Failing Open')",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-657"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-637",
              "name": "UnnecessaryComplexityInProtectionMechanismNotUsingEconomyOfMechanism",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses a more complex mechanism than necessary, which could lead to resultant weaknesses when the mechanism is not correctly understood, modeled, configured, implemented, or used."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Security mechanisms should be as simple as possible. Complex security mechanisms may engender partial implementations and compatibility problems, with resulting mismatches in assumptions and implemented security. A corollary of this principle is that data specifications should be as simple as possible, because complex data specifications result in complex validation code. Complex tasks and systems may also need to be guarded by complex security checks, so simple systems should be preferred."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses a more complex mechanism than necessary, which could lead to resultant weaknesses when the mechanism is not correctly understood, modeled, configured, implemented, or used.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses a more complex mechanism than necessary, which could lead to resultant weaknesses when the mechanism is not correctly understood, modeled, configured, implemented, or used.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nSecurity mechanisms should be as simple as possible. Complex security mechanisms may engender partial implementations and compatibility problems, with resulting mismatches in assumptions and implemented security. A corollary of this principle is that data specifications should be as simple as possible, because complex data specifications result in complex validation code. Complex tasks and systems may also need to be guarded by complex security checks, so simple systems should be preferred.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Other.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Avoid complex security mechanisms when simpler ones would meet requirements. Avoid complex data models, and unnecessarily complex operations. Adopt architectures that provide guarantees, simplify understanding through elegance and abstraction, and that can be implemented similarly. Modularize, isolate and do not trust complex code, and apply other secure programming principles on these modules (e.g., least privilege) to mitigate vulnerabilities."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/637.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Unnecessary Complexity in Protection Mechanism (Not Using 'Economy of Mechanism')",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-657"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-638",
              "name": "NotUsingCompleteMediation",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not perform access checks on a resource every time the resource is accessed by an entity, which can create resultant weaknesses if that entity's rights or privileges change over time."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not perform access checks on a resource every time the resource is accessed by an entity, which can create resultant weaknesses if that entity's rights or privileges change over time.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not perform access checks on a resource every time the resource is accessed by an entity, which can create resultant weaknesses if that entity's rights or privileges change over time.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Confidentiality, Availability, Access Control, Other. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity, Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands, Bypass Protection Mechanism, Read Application Data, Other.\n  - A user might retain access to a critical resource even after privileges have been revoked, possibly allowing access to privileged functionality or sensitive information, depending on the role of the resource.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Invalidate cached privileges, file handles or descriptors, or other access credentials whenever identities, processes, policies, roles, capabilities or permissions change. Perform complete authentication checks before accepting, caching and reusing data, dynamic content and code (scripts). Avoid caching access control decisions as much as possible.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Identify all possible code paths that might access sensitive resources. If possible, create and use a single interface that performs the access checks, and develop code standards that require use of this interface."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/638.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Not Using Complete Mediation",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-657"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-639",
              "name": "AuthorizationBypassThroughUserControlledKey",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The system's authorization functionality does not prevent one user from gaining access to another user's data or record by modifying the key value identifying the data."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Retrieval of a user record occurs in the system based on some key value that is under user control. The key would typically identify a user-related record stored in the system and would be used to lookup that record for presentation to the user. It is likely that an attacker would have to be an authenticated user in the system. However, the authorization process would not properly check the data access operation to ensure that the authenticated user performing the operation has sufficient entitlements to perform the requested data access, hence bypassing any other authorization checks present in the system. For example, attackers can look at places where user specific data is retrieved (e.g. search screens) and determine whether the key for the item being looked up is controllable externally. The key may be a hidden field in the HTML form field, might be passed as a URL parameter or as an unencrypted cookie variable, then in each of these cases it will be possible to tamper with the key value. One manifestation of this weakness is when a system uses sequential or otherwise easily-guessable session IDs that would allow one user to easily switch to another user's session and read/modify their data."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The system's authorization functionality does not prevent one user from gaining access to another user's data or record by modifying the key value identifying the data.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe system's authorization functionality does not prevent one user from gaining access to another user's data or record by modifying the key value identifying the data.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nRetrieval of a user record occurs in the system based on some key value that is under user control. The key would typically identify a user-related record stored in the system and would be used to lookup that record for presentation to the user. It is likely that an attacker would have to be an authenticated user in the system. However, the authorization process would not properly check the data access operation to ensure that the authenticated user performing the operation has sufficient entitlements to perform the requested data access, hence bypassing any other authorization checks present in the system. For example, attackers can look at places where user specific data is retrieved (e.g. search screens) and determine whether the key for the item being looked up is controllable externally. The key may be a hidden field in the HTML form field, might be passed as a URL parameter or as an unencrypted cookie variable, then in each of these cases it will be possible to tamper with the key value. One manifestation of this weakness is when a system uses sequential or otherwise easily-guessable session IDs that would allow one user to easily switch to another user's session and read/modify their data.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism.\n  - Access control checks for specific user data or functionality can be bypassed.\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n  - Horizontal escalation of privilege is possible (one user can view/modify information of another user).\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n  - Vertical escalation of privilege is possible if the user-controlled key is actually a flag that indicates administrator status, allowing the attacker to gain administrative access.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. For each and every data access, ensure that the user has sufficient privilege to access the record that is being requested.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design, Implementation*. Make sure that the key that is used in the lookup of a specific user's record is not controllable externally by the user or that any tampering can be detected.\n3. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Use encryption in order to make it more difficult to guess other legitimate values of the key or associate a digital signature with the key so that the server can verify that there has been no tampering."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/639.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Authorization Bypass Through User-Controlled Key",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-863"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-640",
              "name": "WeakPasswordRecoveryMechanismForForgottenPassword",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product contains a mechanism for users to recover or change their passwords without knowing the original password, but the mechanism is weak."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "It is common for an application to have a mechanism that provides a means for a user to gain access to their account in the event they forget their password. Very often the password recovery mechanism is weak, which has the effect of making it more likely that it would be possible for a person other than the legitimate system user to gain access to that user's account. Weak password recovery schemes completely undermine a strong password authentication scheme. This weakness may be that the security question is too easy to guess or find an answer to (e.g. because the question is too common, or the answers can be found using social media). Or there might be an implementation weakness in the password recovery mechanism code that may for instance trick the system into e-mailing the new password to an e-mail account other than that of the user. There might be no throttling done on the rate of password resets so that a legitimate user can be denied service by an attacker if an attacker tries to recover their password in a rapid succession. The system may send the original password to the user rather than generating a new temporary password. In summary, password recovery functionality, if not carefully designed and implemented can often become the system's weakest link that can be misused in a way that would allow an attacker to gain unauthorized access to the system."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product contains a mechanism for users to recover or change their passwords without knowing the original password, but the mechanism is weak.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product contains a mechanism for users to recover or change their passwords without knowing the original password, but the mechanism is weak.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIt is common for an application to have a mechanism that provides a means for a user to gain access to their account in the event they forget their password. Very often the password recovery mechanism is weak, which has the effect of making it more likely that it would be possible for a person other than the legitimate system user to gain access to that user's account. Weak password recovery schemes completely undermine a strong password authentication scheme. This weakness may be that the security question is too easy to guess or find an answer to (e.g. because the question is too common, or the answers can be found using social media). Or there might be an implementation weakness in the password recovery mechanism code that may for instance trick the system into e-mailing the new password to an e-mail account other than that of the user. There might be no throttling done on the rate of password resets so that a legitimate user can be denied service by an attacker if an attacker tries to recover their password in a rapid succession. The system may send the original password to the user rather than generating a new temporary password. In summary, password recovery functionality, if not carefully designed and implemented can often become the system's weakest link that can be misused in a way that would allow an attacker to gain unauthorized access to the system.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n  - An attacker could gain unauthorized access to the system by retrieving legitimate user's authentication credentials.\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Resource Consumption (Other).\n  - An attacker could deny service to legitimate system users by launching a brute force attack on the password recovery mechanism using user ids of legitimate users.\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Other. **Impact**: Other.\n  - The system's security functionality is turned against the system by the attacker.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Make sure that all input supplied by the user to the password recovery mechanism is thoroughly filtered and validated.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Do not use standard weak security questions and use several security questions.\n3. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Make sure that there is throttling on the number of incorrect answers to a security question. Disable the password recovery functionality after a certain (small) number of incorrect guesses.\n4. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Require that the user properly answers the security question prior to resetting their password and sending the new password to the e-mail address of record.\n5. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Never allow the user to control what e-mail address the new password will be sent to in the password recovery mechanism.\n6. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Assign a new temporary password rather than revealing the original password."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/640.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Weak Password Recovery Mechanism for Forgotten Password",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-1390"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-641",
              "name": "ImproperRestrictionOfNamesForFilesAndOtherResources",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product constructs the name of a file or other resource using input from an upstream component, but it does not restrict or incorrectly restricts the resulting name."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "This may produce resultant weaknesses. For instance, if the names of these resources contain scripting characters, it is possible that a script may get executed in the client's browser if the application ever displays the name of the resource on a dynamically generated web page. Alternately, if the resources are consumed by some application parser, a specially crafted name can exploit some vulnerability internal to the parser, potentially resulting in execution of arbitrary code on the server machine. The problems will vary based on the context of usage of such malformed resource names and whether vulnerabilities are present in or assumptions are made by the targeted technology that would make code execution possible."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product constructs the name of a file or other resource using input from an upstream component, but it does not restrict or incorrectly restricts the resulting name.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product constructs the name of a file or other resource using input from an upstream component, but it does not restrict or incorrectly restricts the resulting name.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThis may produce resultant weaknesses. For instance, if the names of these resources contain scripting characters, it is possible that a script may get executed in the client's browser if the application ever displays the name of the resource on a dynamically generated web page. Alternately, if the resources are consumed by some application parser, a specially crafted name can exploit some vulnerability internal to the parser, potentially resulting in execution of arbitrary code on the server machine. The problems will vary based on the context of usage of such malformed resource names and whether vulnerabilities are present in or assumptions are made by the targeted technology that would make code execution possible.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Confidentiality, Availability. **Impact**: Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands.\n  - Execution of arbitrary code in the context of usage of the resources with dangerous names.\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Availability. **Impact**: Read Application Data, DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart.\n  - Crash of the consumer code of these resources resulting in information leakage or denial of service.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Do not allow users to control names of resources used on the server side.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Perform allowlist input validation at entry points and also before consuming the resources. Reject bad file names rather than trying to cleanse them.\n3. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Make sure that technologies consuming the resources are not vulnerable (e.g. buffer overflow, format string, etc.) in a way that would allow code execution if the name of the resource is malformed."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/641.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Improper Restriction of Names for Files and Other Resources",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-99"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-642",
              "name": "ExternalControlOfCriticalStateData",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product stores security-critical state information about its users, or the product itself, in a location that is accessible to unauthorized actors."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "If an attacker can modify the state information without detection, then it could be used to perform unauthorized actions or access unexpected resources, since the application programmer does not expect that the state can be changed. State information can be stored in various locations such as a cookie, in a hidden web form field, input parameter or argument, an environment variable, a database record, within a settings file, etc. All of these locations have the potential to be modified by an attacker. When this state information is used to control security or determine resource usage, then it may create a vulnerability. For example, an application may perform authentication, then save the state in an \"authenticated=true\" cookie. An attacker may simply create this cookie in order to bypass the authentication."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product stores security-critical state information about its users, or the product itself, in a location that is accessible to unauthorized actors.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product stores security-critical state information about its users, or the product itself, in a location that is accessible to unauthorized actors.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIf an attacker can modify the state information without detection, then it could be used to perform unauthorized actions or access unexpected resources, since the application programmer does not expect that the state can be changed. State information can be stored in various locations such as a cookie, in a hidden web form field, input parameter or argument, an environment variable, a database record, within a settings file, etc. All of these locations have the potential to be modified by an attacker. When this state information is used to control security or determine resource usage, then it may create a vulnerability. For example, an application may perform authentication, then save the state in an \"authenticated=true\" cookie. An attacker may simply create this cookie in order to bypass the authentication.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism, Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n  - An attacker could potentially modify the state in malicious ways. If the state is related to the privileges or level of authentication that the user has, then state modification might allow the user to bypass authentication or elevate privileges.\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - The state variables may contain sensitive information that should not be known by the client.\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart.\n  - By modifying state variables, the attacker could violate the application's expectations for the contents of the state, leading to a denial of service due to an unexpected error condition.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Understand all the potential locations that are accessible to attackers. For example, some programmers assume that cookies and hidden form fields cannot be modified by an attacker, or they may not consider that environment variables can be modified before a privileged program is invoked.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design; Strategy: Attack Surface Reduction*. Store state information and sensitive data on the server side only. Ensure that the system definitively and unambiguously keeps track of its own state and user state and has rules defined for legitimate state transitions. Do not allow any application user to affect state directly in any way other than through legitimate actions leading to state transitions. If information must be stored on the client, do not do so without encryption and integrity checking, or otherwise having a mechanism on the server side to catch tampering. Use a message authentication code (MAC) algorithm, such as Hash Message Authentication Code (HMAC) [REF-529]. Apply this against the state or sensitive data that has to be exposed, which can guarantee the integrity of the data - i.e., that the data has not been modified. Ensure that a strong hash function is used (CWE-328).\n3. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Store state information on the server side only. Ensure that the system definitively and unambiguously keeps track of its own state and user state and has rules defined for legitimate state transitions. Do not allow any application user to affect state directly in any way other than through legitimate actions leading to state transitions.\n4. *Phase: Architecture and Design; Strategy: Libraries or Frameworks*. Use a vetted library or framework that does not allow this weakness to occur or provides constructs that make this weakness easier to avoid [REF-1482]. With a stateless protocol such as HTTP, use some frameworks can maintain the state for you. Examples include ASP.NET View State and the OWASP ESAPI Session Management feature. Be careful of language features that provide state support, since these might be provided as a convenience to the programmer and may not be considering security.\n5. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. For any security checks that are performed on the client side, ensure that these checks are duplicated on the server side, in order to avoid CWE-602. Attackers can bypass the client-side checks by modifying values after the checks have been performed, or by changing the client to remove the client-side checks entirely. Then, these modified values would be submitted to the server.\n6. *Phase: Operation, Implementation; Strategy: Environment Hardening*. When using PHP, configure the application so that it does not use register_globals. During implementation, develop the application so that it does not rely on this feature, but be wary of implementing a register_globals emulation that is subject to weaknesses such as CWE-95, CWE-621, and similar issues."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/642.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "External Control of Critical State Data",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-668"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-643",
              "name": "XpathInjection",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses external input to dynamically construct an XPath expression used to retrieve data from an XML database, but it does not neutralize or incorrectly neutralizes that input."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The net effect is that the attacker will have control over the information selected from the XML database and may use that ability to control application flow, modify logic, retrieve unauthorized data, or bypass important checks (e.g. authentication)."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses external input to dynamically construct an XPath expression used to retrieve data from an XML database, but it does not neutralize or incorrectly neutralizes that input. This allows an attacker to control the structure of the query.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses external input to dynamically construct an XPath expression used to retrieve data from an XML database, but it does not neutralize or incorrectly neutralizes that input. This allows an attacker to control the structure of the query.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThe net effect is that the attacker will have control over the information selected from the XML database and may use that ability to control application flow, modify logic, retrieve unauthorized data, or bypass important checks (e.g. authentication).\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism.\n  - Controlling application flow (e.g. bypassing authentication).\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - The attacker could read restricted XML content.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Use parameterized XPath queries (e.g. using XQuery). This will help ensure separation between data plane and control plane.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Properly validate user input. Reject data where appropriate, filter where appropriate and escape where appropriate. Make sure input that will be used in XPath queries is safe in that context."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/643.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Improper Neutralization of Data within XPath Expressions ('XPath Injection')",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-943"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-644",
              "name": "ImproperNeutralizationOfHttpHeadersForScriptingSyntax",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not neutralize or incorrectly neutralizes web scripting syntax in HTTP headers that can be used by web browser components that can process raw headers, such as Flash."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "An attacker may be able to conduct cross-site scripting and other attacks against users who have these components enabled. If a product does not neutralize user controlled data being placed in the header of an HTTP response coming from the server, the header may contain a script that will get executed in the client's browser context, potentially resulting in a cross site scripting vulnerability or possibly an HTTP response splitting attack. It is important to carefully control data that is being placed both in HTTP response header and in the HTTP response body to ensure that no scripting syntax is present, taking various encodings into account."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not neutralize or incorrectly neutralizes web scripting syntax in HTTP headers that can be used by web browser components that can process raw headers, such as Flash.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not neutralize or incorrectly neutralizes web scripting syntax in HTTP headers that can be used by web browser components that can process raw headers, such as Flash.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nAn attacker may be able to conduct cross-site scripting and other attacks against users who have these components enabled. If a product does not neutralize user controlled data being placed in the header of an HTTP response coming from the server, the header may contain a script that will get executed in the client's browser context, potentially resulting in a cross site scripting vulnerability or possibly an HTTP response splitting attack. It is important to carefully control data that is being placed both in HTTP response header and in the HTTP response body to ensure that no scripting syntax is present, taking various encodings into account.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Confidentiality, Availability. **Impact**: Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands.\n  - Run arbitrary code.\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - Attackers may be able to obtain sensitive information.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Perform output validation in order to filter/escape/encode unsafe data that is being passed from the server in an HTTP response header.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Disable script execution functionality in the clients' browser."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/644.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Improper Neutralization of HTTP Headers for Scripting Syntax",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-116"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-645",
              "name": "OverlyRestrictiveAccountLockoutMechanism",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product contains an account lockout protection mechanism, but the mechanism is too restrictive and can be triggered too easily, which allows attackers to deny service to legitimate users by causing their accounts to be locked out."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Account lockout is a security feature often present in applications as a countermeasure to the brute force attack on the password based authentication mechanism of the system. After a certain number of failed login attempts, the users' account may be disabled for a certain period of time or until it is unlocked by an administrator. Other security events may also possibly trigger account lockout. However, an attacker may use this very security feature to deny service to legitimate system users. It is therefore important to ensure that the account lockout security mechanism is not overly restrictive."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product contains an account lockout protection mechanism, but the mechanism is too restrictive and can be triggered too easily, which allows attackers to deny service to legitimate users by causing their accounts to be locked out.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product contains an account lockout protection mechanism, but the mechanism is too restrictive and can be triggered too easily, which allows attackers to deny service to legitimate users by causing their accounts to be locked out.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nAccount lockout is a security feature often present in applications as a countermeasure to the brute force attack on the password based authentication mechanism of the system. After a certain number of failed login attempts, the users' account may be disabled for a certain period of time or until it is unlocked by an administrator. Other security events may also possibly trigger account lockout. However, an attacker may use this very security feature to deny service to legitimate system users. It is therefore important to ensure that the account lockout security mechanism is not overly restrictive.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Resource Consumption (Other).\n  - Users could be locked out of accounts.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Implement more intelligent password throttling mechanisms such as those which take IP address into account, in addition to the login name.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Implement a lockout timeout that grows as the number of incorrect login attempts goes up, eventually resulting in a complete lockout.\n3. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Consider alternatives to account lockout that would still be effective against password brute force attacks, such as presenting the user machine with a puzzle to solve (makes it do some computation)."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/645.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Overly Restrictive Account Lockout Mechanism",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-287"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-646",
              "name": "RelianceOnFileNameOrExtensionOfExternallySuppliedFile",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product allows a file to be uploaded, but it relies on the file name or extension of the file to determine the appropriate behaviors."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "An application might use the file name or extension of a user-supplied file to determine the proper course of action, such as selecting the correct process to which control should be passed, deciding what data should be made available, or what resources should be allocated. If the attacker can cause the code to misclassify the supplied file, then the wrong action could occur. For example, an attacker could supply a file that ends in a \".php.gif\" extension that appears to be a GIF image, but would be processed as PHP code. In extreme cases, code execution is possible, but the attacker could also cause exhaustion of resources, denial of service, exposure of debug or system data (including application source code), or being bound to a particular server side process. This weakness may be due to a vulnerability in any of the technologies used by the web and application servers, due to misconfiguration, or resultant from another flaw in the application itself."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product allows a file to be uploaded, but it relies on the file name or extension of the file to determine the appropriate behaviors. This could be used by attackers to cause the file to be misclassified and processed in a dangerous fashion.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product allows a file to be uploaded, but it relies on the file name or extension of the file to determine the appropriate behaviors. This could be used by attackers to cause the file to be misclassified and processed in a dangerous fashion.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nAn application might use the file name or extension of a user-supplied file to determine the proper course of action, such as selecting the correct process to which control should be passed, deciding what data should be made available, or what resources should be allocated. If the attacker can cause the code to misclassify the supplied file, then the wrong action could occur. For example, an attacker could supply a file that ends in a \".php.gif\" extension that appears to be a GIF image, but would be processed as PHP code. In extreme cases, code execution is possible, but the attacker could also cause exhaustion of resources, denial of service, exposure of debug or system data (including application source code), or being bound to a particular server side process. This weakness may be due to a vulnerability in any of the technologies used by the web and application servers, due to misconfiguration, or resultant from another flaw in the application itself.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - An attacker may be able to read sensitive data.\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart.\n  - An attacker may be able to cause a denial of service.\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n  - An attacker may be able to gain privileges.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Make decisions on the server side based on file content and not on file name or extension."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/646.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Reliance on File Name or Extension of Externally-Supplied File",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-345"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-647",
              "name": "UseOfNonCanonicalUrlPathsForAuthorizationDecisions",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product defines policy namespaces and makes authorization decisions based on the assumption that a URL is canonical."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "If an application defines policy namespaces and makes authorization decisions based on the URL, but it does not require or convert to a canonical URL before making the authorization decision, then it opens the application to attack. For example, if the application only wants to allow access to http://www.example.com/mypage, then the attacker might be able to bypass this restriction using equivalent URLs such as: http://WWW.EXAMPLE.COM/mypage http://www.example.com/%6Dypage (alternate encoding) http://192.168.1.1/mypage (IP address) http://www.example.com/mypage/ (trailing /) http://www.example.com:80/mypage Therefore it is important to specify access control policy that is based on the path information in some canonical form with all alternate encodings rejected (which can be accomplished by a default deny rule)."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product defines policy namespaces and makes authorization decisions based on the assumption that a URL is canonical. This can allow a non-canonical URL to bypass the authorization.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product defines policy namespaces and makes authorization decisions based on the assumption that a URL is canonical. This can allow a non-canonical URL to bypass the authorization.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIf an application defines policy namespaces and makes authorization decisions based on the URL, but it does not require or convert to a canonical URL before making the authorization decision, then it opens the application to attack. For example, if the application only wants to allow access to http://www.example.com/mypage, then the attacker might be able to bypass this restriction using equivalent URLs such as: http://WWW.EXAMPLE.COM/mypage http://www.example.com/%6Dypage (alternate encoding) http://192.168.1.1/mypage (IP address) http://www.example.com/mypage/ (trailing /) http://www.example.com:80/mypage Therefore it is important to specify access control policy that is based on the path information in some canonical form with all alternate encodings rejected (which can be accomplished by a default deny rule).\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism.\n  - An attacker may be able to bypass the authorization mechanism to gain access to the otherwise-protected URL.\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Files or Directories.\n  - If a non-canonical URL is used, the server may choose to return the contents of the file, instead of pre-processing the file (e.g. as a program).\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Make access control policy based on path information in canonical form. Use very restrictive regular expressions to validate that the path is in the expected form.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Reject all alternate path encodings that are not in the expected canonical form."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/647.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Use of Non-Canonical URL Paths for Authorization Decisions",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-863"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-648",
              "name": "IncorrectUseOfPrivilegedApis",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not conform to the API requirements for a function call that requires extra privileges."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "When a product contains certain functions that perform operations requiring an elevated level of privilege, the caller of a privileged API must be careful to: ensure that assumptions made by the APIs are valid, such as validity of arguments account for known weaknesses in the design/implementation of the API call the API from a safe context If the caller of the API does not follow these requirements, then it may allow a malicious user or process to elevate their privilege, hijack the process, or steal sensitive data. For instance, it is important to know if privileged APIs do not shed their privileges before returning to the caller or if the privileged function might make certain assumptions about the data, context or state information passed to it by the caller. It is important to always know when and how privileged APIs can be called in order to ensure that their elevated level of privilege cannot be exploited."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not conform to the API requirements for a function call that requires extra privileges. This could allow attackers to gain privileges by causing the function to be called incorrectly.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not conform to the API requirements for a function call that requires extra privileges. This could allow attackers to gain privileges by causing the function to be called incorrectly.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nWhen a product contains certain functions that perform operations requiring an elevated level of privilege, the caller of a privileged API must be careful to: ensure that assumptions made by the APIs are valid, such as validity of arguments account for known weaknesses in the design/implementation of the API call the API from a safe context If the caller of the API does not follow these requirements, then it may allow a malicious user or process to elevate their privilege, hijack the process, or steal sensitive data. For instance, it is important to know if privileged APIs do not shed their privileges before returning to the caller or if the privileged function might make certain assumptions about the data, context or state information passed to it by the caller. It is important to always know when and how privileged APIs can be called in order to ensure that their elevated level of privilege cannot be exploited.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n  - An attacker may be able to elevate privileges.\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - An attacker may be able to obtain sensitive information.\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Confidentiality, Availability. **Impact**: Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands.\n  - An attacker may be able to execute code.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Before calling privileged APIs, always ensure that the assumptions made by the privileged code hold true prior to making the call.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Know architecture and implementation weaknesses of the privileged APIs and make sure to account for these weaknesses before calling the privileged APIs to ensure that they can be called safely.\n3. *Phase: Implementation*. If privileged APIs make certain assumptions about data, context or state validity that are passed by the caller, the calling code must ensure that these assumptions have been validated prior to making the call.\n4. *Phase: Implementation*. If privileged APIs do not shed their privilege prior to returning to the calling code, then calling code needs to shed these privileges immediately and safely right after the call to the privileged APIs. In particular, the calling code needs to ensure that a privileged thread of execution will never be returned to the user or made available to user-controlled processes.\n5. *Phase: Implementation*. Only call privileged APIs from safe, consistent and expected state.\n6. *Phase: Implementation*. Ensure that a failure or an error will not leave a system in a state where privileges are not properly shed and privilege escalation is possible (i.e. fail securely with regards to handling of privileges)."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/648.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Incorrect Use of Privileged APIs",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-269"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-649",
              "name": "RelianceOnObfuscationOrEncryptionOfSecurityRelevantInputsWithoutIntegrityChecking",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses obfuscation or encryption of inputs that should not be mutable by an external actor, but the product does not use integrity checks to detect if those inputs have been modified."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "When an application relies on obfuscation or incorrectly applied / weak encryption to protect client-controllable tokens or parameters, that may have an effect on the user state, system state, or some decision made on the server. Without protecting the tokens/parameters for integrity, the application is vulnerable to an attack where an adversary traverses the space of possible values of the said token/parameter in order to attempt to gain an advantage. The goal of the attacker is to find another admissible value that will somehow elevate their privileges in the system, disclose information or change the behavior of the system in some way beneficial to the attacker. If the application does not protect these critical tokens/parameters for integrity, it will not be able to determine that these values have been tampered with. Measures that are used to protect data for confidentiality should not be relied upon to provide the integrity service."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses obfuscation or encryption of inputs that should not be mutable by an external actor, but the product does not use integrity checks to detect if those inputs have been modified.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses obfuscation or encryption of inputs that should not be mutable by an external actor, but the product does not use integrity checks to detect if those inputs have been modified.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nWhen an application relies on obfuscation or incorrectly applied / weak encryption to protect client-controllable tokens or parameters, that may have an effect on the user state, system state, or some decision made on the server. Without protecting the tokens/parameters for integrity, the application is vulnerable to an attack where an adversary traverses the space of possible values of the said token/parameter in order to attempt to gain an advantage. The goal of the attacker is to find another admissible value that will somehow elevate their privileges in the system, disclose information or change the behavior of the system in some way beneficial to the attacker. If the application does not protect these critical tokens/parameters for integrity, it will not be able to determine that these values have been tampered with. Measures that are used to protect data for confidentiality should not be relied upon to provide the integrity service.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Unexpected State.\n  - The inputs could be modified without detection, causing the product to have unexpected system state or make incorrect security decisions.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Protect important client controllable tokens/parameters for integrity using PKI methods (i.e. digital signatures) or other means, and checks for integrity on the server side.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Repeated requests from a particular user that include invalid values of tokens/parameters (those that should not be changed manually by users) should result in the user account lockout.\n3. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Client side tokens/parameters should not be such that it would be easy/predictable to guess another valid state.\n4. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Obfuscation should not be relied upon. If encryption is used, it needs to be properly applied (i.e. proven algorithm and implementation, use padding, use random initialization vector, user proper encryption mode). Even with proper encryption where the ciphertext does not leak information about the plaintext or reveal its structure, compromising integrity is possible (although less likely) without the provision of the integrity service."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/649.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Reliance on Obfuscation or Encryption of Security-Relevant Inputs without Integrity Checking",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-345"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-650",
              "name": "TrustingHttpPermissionMethodsOnTheServerSide",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The server contains a protection mechanism that assumes that any URI that is accessed using HTTP GET will not cause a state change to the associated resource."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The HTTP GET method and some other methods are designed to retrieve resources and not to alter the state of the application or resources on the server side. Furthermore, the HTTP specification requires that GET requests (and other requests) should not have side effects. Believing that it will be enough to prevent unintended resource alterations, an application may disallow the HTTP requests to perform DELETE, PUT and POST operations on the resource representation. However, there is nothing in the HTTP protocol itself that actually prevents the HTTP GET method from performing more than just query of the data. Developers can easily code programs that accept a HTTP GET request that do in fact create, update or delete data on the server. For instance, it is a common practice with REST based Web Services to have HTTP GET requests modifying resources on the server side. However, whenever that happens, the access control needs to be properly enforced in the application. No assumptions should be made that only HTTP DELETE, PUT, POST, and other methods have the power to alter the representation of the resource being accessed in the request."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The server contains a protection mechanism that assumes that any URI that is accessed using HTTP GET will not cause a state change to the associated resource. This might allow attackers to bypass intended access restrictions and conduct resource modification and deletion attacks, since some applications allow GET to modify state.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe server contains a protection mechanism that assumes that any URI that is accessed using HTTP GET will not cause a state change to the associated resource. This might allow attackers to bypass intended access restrictions and conduct resource modification and deletion attacks, since some applications allow GET to modify state.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThe HTTP GET method and some other methods are designed to retrieve resources and not to alter the state of the application or resources on the server side. Furthermore, the HTTP specification requires that GET requests (and other requests) should not have side effects. Believing that it will be enough to prevent unintended resource alterations, an application may disallow the HTTP requests to perform DELETE, PUT and POST operations on the resource representation. However, there is nothing in the HTTP protocol itself that actually prevents the HTTP GET method from performing more than just query of the data. Developers can easily code programs that accept a HTTP GET request that do in fact create, update or delete data on the server. For instance, it is a common practice with REST based Web Services to have HTTP GET requests modifying resources on the server side. However, whenever that happens, the access control needs to be properly enforced in the application. No assumptions should be made that only HTTP DELETE, PUT, POST, and other methods have the power to alter the representation of the resource being accessed in the request.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n  - An attacker could escalate privileges.\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Modify Application Data.\n  - An attacker could modify resources.\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - An attacker could obtain sensitive information.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: System Configuration*. Configure ACLs on the server side to ensure that proper level of access control is defined for each accessible resource representation."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/650.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Trusting HTTP Permission Methods on the Server Side",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-436"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-651",
              "name": "ExposureOfWsdlFileContainingSensitiveInformation",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The Web services architecture may require exposing a Web Service Definition Language (WSDL) file that contains information on the publicly accessible services and how callers of these services should interact with them (e.g."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "An information exposure may occur if any of the following apply: The WSDL file is accessible to a wider audience than intended. The WSDL file contains information on the methods/services that should not be publicly accessible or information about deprecated methods. This problem is made more likely due to the WSDL often being automatically generated from the code. Information in the WSDL file helps guess names/locations of methods/resources that should not be publicly accessible."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The Web services architecture may require exposing a Web Service Definition Language (WSDL) file that contains information on the publicly accessible services and how callers of these services should interact with them (e.g. what parameters they expect and what types they return).",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe Web services architecture may require exposing a Web Service Definition Language (WSDL) file that contains information on the publicly accessible services and how callers of these services should interact with them (e.g. what parameters they expect and what types they return).\n\n## Extended Description\n\nAn information exposure may occur if any of the following apply: The WSDL file is accessible to a wider audience than intended. The WSDL file contains information on the methods/services that should not be publicly accessible or information about deprecated methods. This problem is made more likely due to the WSDL often being automatically generated from the code. Information in the WSDL file helps guess names/locations of methods/resources that should not be publicly accessible.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - The attacker may find sensitive information located in the WSDL file.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Limit access to the WSDL file as much as possible. If services are provided only to a limited number of entities, it may be better to provide WSDL privately to each of these entities than to publish WSDL publicly.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design; Strategy: Separation of Privilege*. Make sure that WSDL does not describe methods that should not be publicly accessible. Make sure to protect service methods that should not be publicly accessible with access controls.\n3. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Do not use method names in WSDL that might help an adversary guess names of private methods/resources used by the service."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/651.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Exposure of WSDL File Containing Sensitive Information",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-538"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-652",
              "name": "XqueryInjection",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses external input to dynamically construct an XQuery expression used to retrieve data from an XML database, but it does not neutralize or incorrectly neutralizes that input."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The net effect is that the attacker will have control over the information selected from the XML database and may use that ability to control application flow, modify logic, retrieve unauthorized data, or bypass important checks (e.g. authentication)."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses external input to dynamically construct an XQuery expression used to retrieve data from an XML database, but it does not neutralize or incorrectly neutralizes that input. This allows an attacker to control the structure of the query.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses external input to dynamically construct an XQuery expression used to retrieve data from an XML database, but it does not neutralize or incorrectly neutralizes that input. This allows an attacker to control the structure of the query.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThe net effect is that the attacker will have control over the information selected from the XML database and may use that ability to control application flow, modify logic, retrieve unauthorized data, or bypass important checks (e.g. authentication).\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - An attacker might be able to read sensitive information from the XML database.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Use parameterized queries. This will help ensure separation between data plane and control plane.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Properly validate user input. Reject data where appropriate, filter where appropriate and escape where appropriate. Make sure input that will be used in XQL queries is safe in that context."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/652.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Improper Neutralization of Data within XQuery Expressions ('XQuery Injection')",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-943"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-653",
              "name": "ImproperIsolationOrCompartmentalization",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not properly compartmentalize or isolate functionality, processes, or resources that require different privilege levels, rights, or permissions."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "When a weakness occurs in functionality that is accessible by lower-privileged users, then without strong boundaries, an attack might extend the scope of the damage to higher-privileged users."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not properly compartmentalize or isolate functionality, processes, or resources that require different privilege levels, rights, or permissions.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not properly compartmentalize or isolate functionality, processes, or resources that require different privilege levels, rights, or permissions.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nWhen a weakness occurs in functionality that is accessible by lower-privileged users, then without strong boundaries, an attack might extend the scope of the damage to higher-privileged users.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity, Bypass Protection Mechanism.\n  - The exploitation of a weakness in low-privileged areas of the software can be leveraged to reach higher-privileged areas without having to overcome any additional obstacles.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Break up privileges between different modules, objects, or entities. Minimize the interfaces between modules and require strong access control between them."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/653.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Improper Isolation or Compartmentalization",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-657"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-654",
              "name": "RelianceOnASingleFactorInASecurityDecision",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A protection mechanism relies exclusively, or to a large extent, on the evaluation of a single condition or the integrity of a single object or entity in order to make a decision about granting access to restricted resources or functionality."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "A protection mechanism relies exclusively, or to a large extent, on the evaluation of a single condition or the integrity of a single object or entity in order to make a decision about granting access to restricted resources or functionality.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA protection mechanism relies exclusively, or to a large extent, on the evaluation of a single condition or the integrity of a single object or entity in order to make a decision about granting access to restricted resources or functionality.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n  - If the single factor is compromised (e.g. by theft or spoofing), then the integrity of the entire security mechanism can be violated with respect to the user that is identified by that factor.\n- **Scope**: Non-Repudiation. **Impact**: Hide Activities.\n  - It can become difficult or impossible for the product to be able to distinguish between legitimate activities by the entity who provided the factor, versus illegitimate activities by an attacker.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Use multiple simultaneous checks before granting access to critical operations or granting critical privileges. A weaker but helpful mitigation is to use several successive checks (multiple layers of security).\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Use redundant access rules on different choke points (e.g., firewalls)."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/654.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Reliance on a Single Factor in a Security Decision",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-657"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-655",
              "name": "InsufficientPsychologicalAcceptability",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product has a protection mechanism that is too difficult or inconvenient to use, encouraging non-malicious users to disable or bypass the mechanism, whether by accident or on purpose."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product has a protection mechanism that is too difficult or inconvenient to use, encouraging non-malicious users to disable or bypass the mechanism, whether by accident or on purpose.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product has a protection mechanism that is too difficult or inconvenient to use, encouraging non-malicious users to disable or bypass the mechanism, whether by accident or on purpose.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism.\n  - By bypassing the security mechanism, a user might leave the system in a less secure state than intended by the administrator, making it more susceptible to compromise.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Testing*. Where possible, perform human factors and usability studies to identify where your product's security mechanisms are difficult to use, and why.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Make the security mechanism as seamless as possible, while also providing the user with sufficient details when a security decision produces unexpected results."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/655.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Insufficient Psychological Acceptability",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-657"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-656",
              "name": "RelianceOnSecurityThroughObscurity",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses a protection mechanism whose strength depends heavily on its obscurity, such that knowledge of its algorithms or key data is sufficient to defeat the mechanism."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "This reliance on \"security through obscurity\" can produce resultant weaknesses if an attacker is able to reverse engineer the inner workings of the mechanism. Note that obscurity can be one small part of defense in depth, since it can create more work for an attacker; however, it is a significant risk if used as the primary means of protection."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses a protection mechanism whose strength depends heavily on its obscurity, such that knowledge of its algorithms or key data is sufficient to defeat the mechanism.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses a protection mechanism whose strength depends heavily on its obscurity, such that knowledge of its algorithms or key data is sufficient to defeat the mechanism.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThis reliance on \"security through obscurity\" can produce resultant weaknesses if an attacker is able to reverse engineer the inner workings of the mechanism. Note that obscurity can be one small part of defense in depth, since it can create more work for an attacker; however, it is a significant risk if used as the primary means of protection.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability, Other. **Impact**: Other.\n  - The security mechanism can be bypassed easily.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Always consider whether knowledge of your code or design is sufficient to break it. Reverse engineering is a highly successful discipline, and financially feasible for motivated adversaries. Black-box techniques are established for binary analysis of executables that use obfuscation, runtime analysis of proprietary protocols, inferring file formats, and others.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. When available, use publicly-vetted algorithms and procedures, as these are more likely to undergo more extensive security analysis and testing. This is especially the case with encryption and authentication."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/656.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Reliance on Security Through Obscurity",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-657"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-657",
              "name": "ViolationOfSecureDesignPrinciples",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product violates well-established principles for secure design."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "This can introduce resultant weaknesses or make it easier for developers to introduce related weaknesses during implementation. Because code is centered around design, it can be resource-intensive to fix design problems."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product violates well-established principles for secure design.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product violates well-established principles for secure design.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThis can introduce resultant weaknesses or make it easier for developers to introduce related weaknesses during implementation. Because code is centered around design, it can be resource-intensive to fix design problems.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Other."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/657.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Violation of Secure Design Principles",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-710"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-662",
              "name": "ImproperSynchronization",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product utilizes multiple threads, processes, components, or systems to allow temporary access to a shared resource that can only be exclusive to one process at a time, but it does not properly synchronize these actions, which might cause simultaneous accesses of this resource by multiple threads or processes."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Synchronization refers to a variety of behaviors and mechanisms that allow two or more independently-operating processes or threads to ensure that they operate on shared resources in predictable ways that do not interfere with each other. Some shared resource operations cannot be executed atomically; that is, multiple steps must be guaranteed to execute sequentially, without any interference by other processes. Synchronization mechanisms vary widely, but they may include locking, mutexes, and semaphores. When a multi-step operation on a shared resource cannot be guaranteed to execute independent of interference, then the resulting behavior can be unpredictable. Improper synchronization could lead to data or memory corruption, denial of service, etc."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product utilizes multiple threads, processes, components, or systems to allow temporary access to a shared resource that can only be exclusive to one process at a time, but it does not properly synchronize these actions, which might cause simultaneous accesses of this resource by multiple threads or processes.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product utilizes multiple threads, processes, components, or systems to allow temporary access to a shared resource that can only be exclusive to one process at a time, but it does not properly synchronize these actions, which might cause simultaneous accesses of this resource by multiple threads or processes.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nSynchronization refers to a variety of behaviors and mechanisms that allow two or more independently-operating processes or threads to ensure that they operate on shared resources in predictable ways that do not interfere with each other. Some shared resource operations cannot be executed atomically; that is, multiple steps must be guaranteed to execute sequentially, without any interference by other processes. Synchronization mechanisms vary widely, but they may include locking, mutexes, and semaphores. When a multi-step operation on a shared resource cannot be guaranteed to execute independent of interference, then the resulting behavior can be unpredictable. Improper synchronization could lead to data or memory corruption, denial of service, etc.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Confidentiality, Other. **Impact**: Modify Application Data, Read Application Data, Alter Execution Logic.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Use industry standard APIs to synchronize your code."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/662.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Improper Synchronization",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-664"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-663",
              "name": "UseOfANonReentrantFunctionInAConcurrentContext",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product calls a non-reentrant function in a concurrent context in which a competing code sequence (e.g."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product calls a non-reentrant function in a concurrent context in which a competing code sequence (e.g. thread or signal handler) may have an opportunity to call the same function or otherwise influence its state.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product calls a non-reentrant function in a concurrent context in which a competing code sequence (e.g. thread or signal handler) may have an opportunity to call the same function or otherwise influence its state.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Confidentiality, Other. **Impact**: Modify Memory, Read Memory, Modify Application Data, Read Application Data, Alter Execution Logic.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Use reentrant functions if available.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Add synchronization to your non-reentrant function.\n3. *Phase: Implementation*. In Java, use the ReentrantLock Class."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/663.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Use of a Non-reentrant Function in a Concurrent Context",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-662"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-664",
              "name": "ImproperControlOfAResourceThroughItsLifetime",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not maintain or incorrectly maintains control over a resource throughout its lifetime of creation, use, and release."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Resources often have explicit instructions on how to be created, used and destroyed. When code does not follow these instructions, it can lead to unexpected behaviors and potentially exploitable states. Even without explicit instructions, various principles are expected to be adhered to, such as \"Do not use an object until after its creation is complete,\" or \"do not use an object after it has been slated for destruction.\""
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not maintain or incorrectly maintains control over a resource throughout its lifetime of creation, use, and release.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not maintain or incorrectly maintains control over a resource throughout its lifetime of creation, use, and release.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nResources often have explicit instructions on how to be created, used and destroyed. When code does not follow these instructions, it can lead to unexpected behaviors and potentially exploitable states. Even without explicit instructions, various principles are expected to be adhered to, such as \"Do not use an object until after its creation is complete,\" or \"do not use an object after it has been slated for destruction.\"\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Other."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/664.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Improper Control of a Resource Through its Lifetime",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Pillar"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-665",
              "name": "ImproperInitialization",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not initialize or incorrectly initializes a resource, which might leave the resource in an unexpected state when it is accessed or used."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "This can have security implications when the associated resource is expected to have certain properties or values, such as a variable that determines whether a user has been authenticated or not."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not initialize or incorrectly initializes a resource, which might leave the resource in an unexpected state when it is accessed or used.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not initialize or incorrectly initializes a resource, which might leave the resource in an unexpected state when it is accessed or used.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThis can have security implications when the associated resource is expected to have certain properties or values, such as a variable that determines whether a user has been authenticated or not.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Memory, Read Application Data.\n  - When reusing a resource such as memory or a program variable, the original contents of that resource may not be cleared before it is sent to an untrusted party.\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism.\n  - If security-critical decisions rely on a variable having a \"0\" or equivalent value, and the programming language performs this initialization on behalf of the programmer, then a bypass of security may occur.\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart.\n  - The uninitialized data may contain values that cause program flow to change in ways that the programmer did not intend. For example, if an uninitialized variable is used as an array index in C, then its previous contents may produce an index that is outside the range of the array, possibly causing a crash or an exit in other environments.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Requirements; Strategy: Language Selection*. Use a language that does not allow this weakness to occur or provides constructs that make this weakness easier to avoid. For example, in Java, if the programmer does not explicitly initialize a variable, then the code could produce a compile-time error (if the variable is local) or automatically initialize the variable to the default value for the variable's type. In Perl, if explicit initialization is not performed, then a default value of undef is assigned, which is interpreted as 0, false, or an equivalent value depending on the context in which the variable is accessed.\n2. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Identify all variables and data stores that receive information from external sources, and apply input validation to make sure that they are only initialized to expected values.\n3. *Phase: Implementation*. Explicitly initialize all your variables and other data stores, either during declaration or just before the first usage.\n4. *Phase: Implementation*. Pay close attention to complex conditionals that affect initialization, since some conditions might not perform the initialization.\n5. *Phase: Implementation*. Avoid race conditions (CWE-362) during initialization routines.\n6. *Phase: Build and Compilation*. Run or compile your product with settings that generate warnings about uninitialized variables or data."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/665.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Improper Initialization",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-664"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-666",
              "name": "OperationOnResourceInWrongPhaseOfLifetime",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product performs an operation on a resource at the wrong phase of the resource's lifecycle, which can lead to unexpected behaviors."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "A resource's lifecycle includes several phases: initialization, use, and release. For each phase, it is important to follow the specifications outlined for how to operate on the resource and to ensure that the resource is in the expected phase. Otherwise, if a resource is in one phase but the operation is not valid for that phase (i.e., an incorrect phase of the resource's lifetime), then this can produce resultant weaknesses. For example, using a resource before it has been fully initialized could cause corruption or incorrect data to be used."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product performs an operation on a resource at the wrong phase of the resource's lifecycle, which can lead to unexpected behaviors.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product performs an operation on a resource at the wrong phase of the resource's lifecycle, which can lead to unexpected behaviors.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nA resource's lifecycle includes several phases: initialization, use, and release. For each phase, it is important to follow the specifications outlined for how to operate on the resource and to ensure that the resource is in the expected phase. Otherwise, if a resource is in one phase but the operation is not valid for that phase (i.e., an incorrect phase of the resource's lifetime), then this can produce resultant weaknesses. For example, using a resource before it has been fully initialized could cause corruption or incorrect data to be used.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Other.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Follow the resource's lifecycle from creation to release."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/666.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Operation on Resource in Wrong Phase of Lifetime",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-664"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-667",
              "name": "ImproperLocking",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not properly acquire or release a lock on a resource, leading to unexpected resource state changes and behaviors."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Locking is a type of synchronization behavior that ensures that multiple independently-operating processes or threads do not interfere with each other when accessing the same resource. All processes/threads are expected to follow the same steps for locking. If these steps are not followed precisely - or if no locking is done at all - then another process/thread could modify the shared resource in a way that is not visible or predictable to the original process. This can lead to data or memory corruption, denial of service, etc."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not properly acquire or release a lock on a resource, leading to unexpected resource state changes and behaviors.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not properly acquire or release a lock on a resource, leading to unexpected resource state changes and behaviors.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nLocking is a type of synchronization behavior that ensures that multiple independently-operating processes or threads do not interfere with each other when accessing the same resource. All processes/threads are expected to follow the same steps for locking. If these steps are not followed precisely - or if no locking is done at all - then another process/thread could modify the shared resource in a way that is not visible or predictable to the original process. This can lead to data or memory corruption, denial of service, etc.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Resource Consumption (CPU).\n  - Inconsistent locking discipline can lead to deadlock.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation; Strategy: Libraries or Frameworks*. Use industry standard APIs to implement locking mechanism."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/667.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Improper Locking",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-662"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-668",
              "name": "ExposureOfResourceToWrongSphere",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product exposes a resource to the wrong control sphere, providing unintended actors with inappropriate access to the resource."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Resources such as files and directories may be inadvertently exposed through mechanisms such as insecure permissions, or when a program accidentally operates on the wrong object. For example, a program may intend that private files can only be provided to a specific user. This effectively defines a control sphere that is intended to prevent attackers from accessing these private files. If the file permissions are insecure, then parties other than the user will be able to access those files. A separate control sphere might effectively require that the user can only access the private files, but not any other files on the system. If the program does not ensure that the user is only requesting private files, then the user might be able to access other files on the system. In either case, the end result is that a resource has been exposed to the wrong party."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product exposes a resource to the wrong control sphere, providing unintended actors with inappropriate access to the resource.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product exposes a resource to the wrong control sphere, providing unintended actors with inappropriate access to the resource.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nResources such as files and directories may be inadvertently exposed through mechanisms such as insecure permissions, or when a program accidentally operates on the wrong object. For example, a program may intend that private files can only be provided to a specific user. This effectively defines a control sphere that is intended to prevent attackers from accessing these private files. If the file permissions are insecure, then parties other than the user will be able to access those files. A separate control sphere might effectively require that the user can only access the private files, but not any other files on the system. If the program does not ensure that the user is only requesting private files, then the user might be able to access other files on the system. In either case, the end result is that a resource has been exposed to the wrong party.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - An adversary that gains access to a resource exposed to a wrong sphere could potentially retrieve private data from that resource, thus breaking the intended confidentiality of that data.\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Modify Application Data.\n  - An adversary that gains access to a resource exposed to a wrong sphere could potentially modify data held within that resource, thus breaking the intended integrity of that data and causing the system relying on that resource to make unintended decisions.\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Varies by Context.\n  - The consequences may vary widely depending on how the product uses the affected resource."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/668.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Exposure of Resource to Wrong Sphere",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-664"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-669",
              "name": "IncorrectResourceTransferBetweenSpheres",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not properly transfer a resource/behavior to another sphere, or improperly imports a resource/behavior from another sphere, in a manner that provides unintended control over that resource."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not properly transfer a resource/behavior to another sphere, or improperly imports a resource/behavior from another sphere, in a manner that provides unintended control over that resource.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not properly transfer a resource/behavior to another sphere, or improperly imports a resource/behavior from another sphere, in a manner that provides unintended control over that resource.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity. **Impact**: Read Application Data, Modify Application Data, Unexpected State."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/669.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Incorrect Resource Transfer Between Spheres",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-664"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-670",
              "name": "AlwaysIncorrectControlFlowImplementation",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The code contains a control flow path that does not reflect the algorithm that the path is intended to implement, leading to incorrect behavior any time this path is navigated."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "This weakness captures cases in which a particular code segment is always incorrect with respect to the algorithm that it is implementing. For example, if a C programmer intends to include multiple statements in a single block but does not include the enclosing braces (CWE-483), then the logic is always incorrect. This issue is in contrast to most weaknesses in which the code usually behaves correctly, except when it is externally manipulated in malicious ways."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The code contains a control flow path that does not reflect the algorithm that the path is intended to implement, leading to incorrect behavior any time this path is navigated.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code contains a control flow path that does not reflect the algorithm that the path is intended to implement, leading to incorrect behavior any time this path is navigated.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThis weakness captures cases in which a particular code segment is always incorrect with respect to the algorithm that it is implementing. For example, if a C programmer intends to include multiple statements in a single block but does not include the enclosing braces (CWE-483), then the logic is always incorrect. This issue is in contrast to most weaknesses in which the code usually behaves correctly, except when it is externally manipulated in malicious ways.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Other, Alter Execution Logic."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/670.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Always-Incorrect Control Flow Implementation",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-691"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-671",
              "name": "LackOfAdministratorControlOverSecurity",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses security features in a way that prevents the product's administrator from tailoring security settings to reflect the environment in which the product is being used."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "If the product's administrator does not have the ability to manage security-related decisions at all times, then protecting the product from outside threats - including the product's developer - can become impossible. For example, a hard-coded account name and password cannot be changed by the administrator, thus exposing that product to attacks that the administrator can not prevent."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses security features in a way that prevents the product's administrator from tailoring security settings to reflect the environment in which the product is being used. This introduces resultant weaknesses or prevents it from operating at a level of security that is desired by the administrator.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses security features in a way that prevents the product's administrator from tailoring security settings to reflect the environment in which the product is being used. This introduces resultant weaknesses or prevents it from operating at a level of security that is desired by the administrator.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIf the product's administrator does not have the ability to manage security-related decisions at all times, then protecting the product from outside threats - including the product's developer - can become impossible. For example, a hard-coded account name and password cannot be changed by the administrator, thus exposing that product to attacks that the administrator can not prevent.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Varies by Context."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/671.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Lack of Administrator Control over Security",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-657"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-672",
              "name": "OperationOnAResourceAfterExpirationOrRelease",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses, accesses, or otherwise operates on a resource after that resource has been expired, released, or revoked."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses, accesses, or otherwise operates on a resource after that resource has been expired, released, or revoked.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses, accesses, or otherwise operates on a resource after that resource has been expired, released, or revoked.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Confidentiality. **Impact**: Modify Application Data, Read Application Data.\n  - If a released resource is subsequently reused or reallocated, then an attempt to use the original resource might allow access to sensitive data that is associated with a different user or entity.\n- **Scope**: Other, Availability. **Impact**: Other, DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart.\n  - When a resource is released it might not be in an expected state, later attempts to access the resource may lead to resultant errors that may lead to a crash."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/672.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Operation on a Resource after Expiration or Release",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-666"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-673",
              "name": "ExternalInfluenceOfSphereDefinition",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not prevent the definition of control spheres from external actors."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Typically, a product defines its control sphere within the code itself, or through configuration by the product's administrator. In some cases, an external party can change the definition of the control sphere. This is typically a resultant weakness."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not prevent the definition of control spheres from external actors.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not prevent the definition of control spheres from external actors.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nTypically, a product defines its control sphere within the code itself, or through configuration by the product's administrator. In some cases, an external party can change the definition of the control sphere. This is typically a resultant weakness.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Other."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/673.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "External Influence of Sphere Definition",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-664"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-674",
              "name": "UncontrolledRecursion",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not properly control the amount of recursion that takes place, consuming excessive resources, such as allocated memory or the program stack."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not properly control the amount of recursion that takes place, consuming excessive resources, such as allocated memory or the program stack.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not properly control the amount of recursion that takes place, consuming excessive resources, such as allocated memory or the program stack.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Resource Consumption (CPU), DoS: Resource Consumption (Memory).\n  - Resources including CPU, memory, and stack memory could be rapidly consumed or exhausted, eventually leading to an exit or crash.\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality. **Impact**: Read Application Data.\n  - In some cases, an application's interpreter might kill a process or thread that appears to be consuming too much resources, such as with PHP's memory_limit setting. When the interpreter kills the process/thread, it might report an error containing detailed information such as the application's installation path.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Ensure that an end condition will be reached under all logic conditions. The end condition may include checking against the depth of recursion and exiting with an error if the recursion goes too deep. The complexity of the end condition contributes to the effectiveness of this action.\n2. *Phase: Implementation*. Increase the stack size."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/674.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Uncontrolled Recursion",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-834"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-675",
              "name": "MultipleOperationsOnResourceInSingleOperationContext",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product performs the same operation on a resource two or more times, when the operation should only be applied once."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product performs the same operation on a resource two or more times, when the operation should only be applied once.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product performs the same operation on a resource two or more times, when the operation should only be applied once.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Other."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/675.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Multiple Operations on Resource in Single-Operation Context",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-573"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-676",
              "name": "UseOfPotentiallyDangerousFunction",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product invokes a potentially dangerous function that could introduce a vulnerability if it is used incorrectly, but the function can also be used safely."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product invokes a potentially dangerous function that could introduce a vulnerability if it is used incorrectly, but the function can also be used safely.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product invokes a potentially dangerous function that could introduce a vulnerability if it is used incorrectly, but the function can also be used safely.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Varies by Context, Quality Degradation, Unexpected State.\n  - If the function is used incorrectly, then it could result in security problems.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Build and Compilation, Implementation*. Identify a list of prohibited API functions and prohibit developers from using these functions, providing safer alternatives. In some cases, automatic code analysis tools or the compiler can be instructed to spot use of prohibited functions, such as the \"banned.h\" include file from Microsoft's SDL. [REF-554] [REF-1009] [REF-7]"
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/676.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Use of Potentially Dangerous Function",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-1177"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-680",
              "name": "IntegerOverflowToBufferOverflow",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product performs a calculation to determine how much memory to allocate, but an integer overflow can occur that causes less memory to be allocated than expected, leading to a buffer overflow."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product performs a calculation to determine how much memory to allocate, but an integer overflow can occur that causes less memory to be allocated than expected, leading to a buffer overflow.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product performs a calculation to determine how much memory to allocate, but an integer overflow can occur that causes less memory to be allocated than expected, leading to a buffer overflow.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Availability, Confidentiality. **Impact**: Modify Memory, DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart, Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/680.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Integer Overflow to Buffer Overflow",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Compound",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-190"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-681",
              "name": "IncorrectConversionBetweenNumericTypes",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "When converting from one data type to another, such as long to integer, data can be omitted or translated in a way that produces unexpected values."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "When converting from one data type to another, such as long to integer, data can be omitted or translated in a way that produces unexpected values. If the resulting values are used in a sensitive context, then dangerous behaviors may occur.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nWhen converting from one data type to another, such as long to integer, data can be omitted or translated in a way that produces unexpected values. If the resulting values are used in a sensitive context, then dangerous behaviors may occur.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other, Integrity. **Impact**: Unexpected State, Quality Degradation.\n  - The program could wind up using the wrong number and generate incorrect results. If the number is used to allocate resources or make a security decision, then this could introduce a vulnerability.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Avoid making conversion between numeric types. Always check for the allowed ranges."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/681.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Incorrect Conversion between Numeric Types",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-704"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-682",
              "name": "IncorrectCalculation",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product performs a calculation that generates incorrect or unintended results that are later used in security-critical decisions or resource management."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "When product performs a security-critical calculation incorrectly, it might lead to incorrect resource allocations, incorrect privilege assignments, or failed comparisons among other things. Many of the direct results of an incorrect calculation can lead to even larger problems such as failed protection mechanisms or even arbitrary code execution."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product performs a calculation that generates incorrect or unintended results that are later used in security-critical decisions or resource management.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product performs a calculation that generates incorrect or unintended results that are later used in security-critical decisions or resource management.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nWhen product performs a security-critical calculation incorrectly, it might lead to incorrect resource allocations, incorrect privilege assignments, or failed comparisons among other things. Many of the direct results of an incorrect calculation can lead to even larger problems such as failed protection mechanisms or even arbitrary code execution.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart.\n  - If the incorrect calculation causes the program to move into an unexpected state, it may lead to a crash or impairment of service.\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Confidentiality, Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart, DoS: Resource Consumption (Other), Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands.\n  - If the incorrect calculation is used in the context of resource allocation, it could lead to an out-of-bounds operation (CWE-119) leading to a crash or even arbitrary code execution. Alternatively, it may result in an integer overflow (CWE-190) and / or a resource consumption problem (CWE-400).\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Gain Privileges or Assume Identity.\n  - In the context of privilege or permissions assignment, an incorrect calculation can provide an attacker with access to sensitive resources.\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism.\n  - If the incorrect calculation leads to an insufficient comparison (CWE-697), it may compromise a protection mechanism such as a validation routine and allow an attacker to bypass the security-critical code.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Understand your programming language's underlying representation and how it interacts with numeric calculation. Pay close attention to byte size discrepancies, precision, signed/unsigned distinctions, truncation, conversion and casting between types, \"not-a-number\" calculations, and how your language handles numbers that are too large or too small for its underlying representation.\n2. *Phase: Implementation; Strategy: Input Validation*. Perform input validation on any numeric input by ensuring that it is within the expected range. Enforce that the input meets both the minimum and maximum requirements for the expected range.\n3. *Phase: Implementation*. Use the appropriate type for the desired action. For example, in C/C++, only use unsigned types for values that could never be negative, such as height, width, or other numbers related to quantity.\n4. *Phase: Architecture and Design; Strategy: Language Selection*. Use languages, libraries, or frameworks that make it easier to handle numbers without unexpected consequences. Examples include safe integer handling packages such as SafeInt (C++) or IntegerLib (C or C++).\n5. *Phase: Architecture and Design; Strategy: Libraries or Frameworks*. Use languages, libraries, or frameworks that make it easier to handle numbers without unexpected consequences. Examples include safe integer handling packages such as SafeInt (C++) or IntegerLib (C or C++).\n6. *Phase: Implementation; Strategy: Compilation or Build Hardening*. Examine compiler warnings closely and eliminate problems with potential security implications, such as signed / unsigned mismatch in memory operations, or use of uninitialized variables. Even if the weakness is rarely exploitable, a single failure may lead to the compromise of the entire system."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/682.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Incorrect Calculation",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Pillar"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-683",
              "name": "FunctionCallWithIncorrectOrderOfArguments",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product calls a function, procedure, or routine, but the caller specifies the arguments in an incorrect order, leading to resultant weaknesses."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "While this weakness might be caught by the compiler in some languages, it can occur more frequently in cases in which the called function accepts variable numbers or types of arguments, such as format strings in C. It also can occur in languages or environments that do not enforce strong typing."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product calls a function, procedure, or routine, but the caller specifies the arguments in an incorrect order, leading to resultant weaknesses.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product calls a function, procedure, or routine, but the caller specifies the arguments in an incorrect order, leading to resultant weaknesses.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nWhile this weakness might be caught by the compiler in some languages, it can occur more frequently in cases in which the called function accepts variable numbers or types of arguments, such as format strings in C. It also can occur in languages or environments that do not enforce strong typing.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Use the function, procedure, or routine as specified."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/683.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Function Call With Incorrect Order of Arguments",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-628"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-684",
              "name": "IncorrectProvisionOfSpecifiedFunctionality",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The code does not function according to its published specifications, potentially leading to incorrect usage."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "When providing functionality to an external party, it is important that the product behaves in accordance with the details specified. When requirements of nuances are not documented, the functionality may produce unintended behaviors for the caller, possibly leading to an exploitable state."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The code does not function according to its published specifications, potentially leading to incorrect usage.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code does not function according to its published specifications, potentially leading to incorrect usage.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nWhen providing functionality to an external party, it is important that the product behaves in accordance with the details specified. When requirements of nuances are not documented, the functionality may produce unintended behaviors for the caller, possibly leading to an exploitable state.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Ensure that your code strictly conforms to specifications."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/684.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Incorrect Provision of Specified Functionality",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-710"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-685",
              "name": "FunctionCallWithIncorrectNumberOfArguments",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product calls a function, procedure, or routine, but the caller specifies too many arguments, or too few arguments, which may lead to undefined behavior and resultant weaknesses."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product calls a function, procedure, or routine, but the caller specifies too many arguments, or too few arguments, which may lead to undefined behavior and resultant weaknesses.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product calls a function, procedure, or routine, but the caller specifies too many arguments, or too few arguments, which may lead to undefined behavior and resultant weaknesses.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Testing*. Because this function call often produces incorrect behavior it will usually be detected during testing or normal operation of the product. During testing exercise all possible control paths will typically expose this weakness except in rare cases when the incorrect function call accidentally produces the correct results or if the provided argument type is very similar to the expected argument type."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/685.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Function Call With Incorrect Number of Arguments",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-628"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-686",
              "name": "FunctionCallWithIncorrectArgumentType",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product calls a function, procedure, or routine, but the caller specifies an argument that is the wrong data type, which may lead to resultant weaknesses."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "This weakness is most likely to occur in loosely typed languages, or in strongly typed languages in which the types of variable arguments cannot be enforced at compilation time, or where there is implicit casting."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product calls a function, procedure, or routine, but the caller specifies an argument that is the wrong data type, which may lead to resultant weaknesses.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product calls a function, procedure, or routine, but the caller specifies an argument that is the wrong data type, which may lead to resultant weaknesses.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThis weakness is most likely to occur in loosely typed languages, or in strongly typed languages in which the types of variable arguments cannot be enforced at compilation time, or where there is implicit casting.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/686.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Function Call With Incorrect Argument Type",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-628"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-687",
              "name": "FunctionCallWithIncorrectlySpecifiedArgumentValue",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product calls a function, procedure, or routine, but the caller specifies an argument that contains the wrong value, which may lead to resultant weaknesses."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product calls a function, procedure, or routine, but the caller specifies an argument that contains the wrong value, which may lead to resultant weaknesses.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product calls a function, procedure, or routine, but the caller specifies an argument that contains the wrong value, which may lead to resultant weaknesses.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/687.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Function Call With Incorrectly Specified Argument Value",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-628"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-688",
              "name": "FunctionCallWithIncorrectVariableOrReferenceAsArgument",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product calls a function, procedure, or routine, but the caller specifies the wrong variable or reference as one of the arguments, which may lead to undefined behavior and resultant weaknesses."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product calls a function, procedure, or routine, but the caller specifies the wrong variable or reference as one of the arguments, which may lead to undefined behavior and resultant weaknesses.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product calls a function, procedure, or routine, but the caller specifies the wrong variable or reference as one of the arguments, which may lead to undefined behavior and resultant weaknesses.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Testing*. Because this function call often produces incorrect behavior it will usually be detected during testing or normal operation of the product. During testing exercise all possible control paths will typically expose this weakness except in rare cases when the incorrect function call accidentally produces the correct results or if the provided argument type is very similar to the expected argument type."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/688.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Function Call With Incorrect Variable or Reference as Argument",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Variant",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-628"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-689",
              "name": "PermissionRaceConditionDuringResourceCopy",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product, while copying or cloning a resource, does not set the resource's permissions or access control until the copy is complete, leaving the resource exposed to other spheres while the copy is taking place."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product, while copying or cloning a resource, does not set the resource's permissions or access control until the copy is complete, leaving the resource exposed to other spheres while the copy is taking place.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product, while copying or cloning a resource, does not set the resource's permissions or access control until the copy is complete, leaving the resource exposed to other spheres while the copy is taking place.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity. **Impact**: Read Application Data, Modify Application Data."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/689.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Permission Race Condition During Resource Copy",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Compound",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-362"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-690",
              "name": "UncheckedReturnValueToNullPointerDereference",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not check for an error after calling a function that can return with a NULL pointer if the function fails, which leads to a resultant NULL pointer dereference."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "While unchecked return value weaknesses are not limited to returns of NULL pointers (see the examples in CWE-252), functions often return NULL to indicate an error status. When this error condition is not checked, a NULL pointer dereference can occur."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not check for an error after calling a function that can return with a NULL pointer if the function fails, which leads to a resultant NULL pointer dereference.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not check for an error after calling a function that can return with a NULL pointer if the function fails, which leads to a resultant NULL pointer dereference.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nWhile unchecked return value weaknesses are not limited to returns of NULL pointers (see the examples in CWE-252), functions often return NULL to indicate an error status. When this error condition is not checked, a NULL pointer dereference can occur.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Availability. **Impact**: DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart.\n- **Scope**: Integrity, Confidentiality, Availability. **Impact**: Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands, Read Memory, Modify Memory.\n  - In rare circumstances, when NULL is equivalent to the 0x0 memory address and privileged code can access it, then writing or reading memory is possible, which may lead to code execution."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/690.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Unchecked Return Value to NULL Pointer Dereference",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Compound",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-252"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-691",
              "name": "InsufficientControlFlowManagement",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The code does not sufficiently manage its control flow during execution, creating conditions in which the control flow can be modified in unexpected ways."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The code does not sufficiently manage its control flow during execution, creating conditions in which the control flow can be modified in unexpected ways.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code does not sufficiently manage its control flow during execution, creating conditions in which the control flow can be modified in unexpected ways.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Alter Execution Logic."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/691.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Insufficient Control Flow Management",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Pillar"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-692",
              "name": "IncompleteDenylistToCrossSiteScripting",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses a denylist-based protection mechanism to defend against XSS attacks, but the denylist is incomplete, allowing XSS variants to succeed."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "While XSS might seem simple to prevent, web browsers vary so widely in how they parse web pages, that a denylist cannot keep track of all the variations. The \"XSS Cheat Sheet\" [REF-714] contains a large number of attacks that are intended to bypass incomplete denylists."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses a denylist-based protection mechanism to defend against XSS attacks, but the denylist is incomplete, allowing XSS variants to succeed.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses a denylist-based protection mechanism to defend against XSS attacks, but the denylist is incomplete, allowing XSS variants to succeed.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nWhile XSS might seem simple to prevent, web browsers vary so widely in how they parse web pages, that a denylist cannot keep track of all the variations. The \"XSS Cheat Sheet\" [REF-714] contains a large number of attacks that are intended to bypass incomplete denylists.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability. **Impact**: Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/692.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Incomplete Denylist to Cross-Site Scripting",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Compound",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-184"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-693",
              "name": "ProtectionMechanismFailure",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not use or incorrectly uses a protection mechanism that provides sufficient defense against directed attacks against the product."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "This weakness covers three distinct situations. A \"missing\" protection mechanism occurs when the application does not define any mechanism against a certain class of attack. An \"insufficient\" protection mechanism might provide some defenses - for example, against the most common attacks - but it does not protect against everything that is intended. Finally, an \"ignored\" mechanism occurs when a mechanism is available and in active use within the product, but the developer has not applied it in some code path."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not use or incorrectly uses a protection mechanism that provides sufficient defense against directed attacks against the product.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not use or incorrectly uses a protection mechanism that provides sufficient defense against directed attacks against the product.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThis weakness covers three distinct situations. A \"missing\" protection mechanism occurs when the application does not define any mechanism against a certain class of attack. An \"insufficient\" protection mechanism might provide some defenses - for example, against the most common attacks - but it does not protect against everything that is intended. Finally, an \"ignored\" mechanism occurs when a mechanism is available and in active use within the product, but the developer has not applied it in some code path.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/693.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Protection Mechanism Failure",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Pillar"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-694",
              "name": "UseOfMultipleResourcesWithDuplicateIdentifier",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses multiple resources that can have the same identifier, in a context in which unique identifiers are required."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "If the product assumes that each resource has a unique identifier, the product could operate on the wrong resource if attackers can cause multiple resources to be associated with the same identifier."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses multiple resources that can have the same identifier, in a context in which unique identifiers are required.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses multiple resources that can have the same identifier, in a context in which unique identifiers are required.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIf the product assumes that each resource has a unique identifier, the product could operate on the wrong resource if attackers can cause multiple resources to be associated with the same identifier.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Access Control. **Impact**: Bypass Protection Mechanism.\n  - If unique identifiers are assumed when protecting sensitive resources, then duplicate identifiers might allow attackers to bypass the protection.\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Quality Degradation.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Architecture and Design*. Where possible, use unique identifiers. If non-unique identifiers are detected, then do not operate any resource with a non-unique identifier and report the error appropriately."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/694.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Use of Multiple Resources with Duplicate Identifier",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-99"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-695",
              "name": "UseOfLowLevelFunctionality",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product uses low-level functionality that is explicitly prohibited by the framework or specification under which the product is supposed to operate."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The use of low-level functionality can violate the specification in unexpected ways that effectively disable built-in protection mechanisms, introduce exploitable inconsistencies, or otherwise expose the functionality to attack."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product uses low-level functionality that is explicitly prohibited by the framework or specification under which the product is supposed to operate.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product uses low-level functionality that is explicitly prohibited by the framework or specification under which the product is supposed to operate.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThe use of low-level functionality can violate the specification in unexpected ways that effectively disable built-in protection mechanisms, introduce exploitable inconsistencies, or otherwise expose the functionality to attack.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Other."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/695.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Use of Low-Level Functionality",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-573"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-696",
              "name": "IncorrectBehaviorOrder",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product performs multiple related behaviors, but the behaviors are performed in the wrong order in ways that may produce resultant weaknesses."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product performs multiple related behaviors, but the behaviors are performed in the wrong order in ways that may produce resultant weaknesses.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product performs multiple related behaviors, but the behaviors are performed in the wrong order in ways that may produce resultant weaknesses.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Alter Execution Logic."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/696.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Incorrect Behavior Order",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-691"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-697",
              "name": "IncorrectComparison",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product compares two entities in a security-relevant context, but the comparison is incorrect."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "This Pillar covers several possibilities: the comparison checks one factor incorrectly; the comparison should consider multiple factors, but it does not check at least one of those factors at all; the comparison checks the wrong factor."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product compares two entities in a security-relevant context, but the comparison is incorrect.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product compares two entities in a security-relevant context, but the comparison is incorrect.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nThis Pillar covers several possibilities: the comparison checks one factor incorrectly; the comparison should consider multiple factors, but it does not check at least one of those factors at all; the comparison checks the wrong factor.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Varies by Context.\n  - When the comparison is incorrect, it may lead to resultant weaknesses."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/697.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Incorrect Comparison",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Pillar"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-698",
              "name": "ExecutionAfterRedirectEar",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The web application sends a redirect to another location, but instead of exiting, it executes additional code."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The web application sends a redirect to another location, but instead of exiting, it executes additional code.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe web application sends a redirect to another location, but instead of exiting, it executes additional code.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other, Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability. **Impact**: Alter Execution Logic, Execute Unauthorized Code or Commands.\n  - This weakness could affect the control flow of the application and allow execution of untrusted code."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/698.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Execution After Redirect (EAR)",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-705"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-703",
              "name": "ImproperCheckOrHandlingOfExceptionalConditions",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not properly anticipate or handle exceptional conditions that rarely occur during normal operation of the product."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not properly anticipate or handle exceptional conditions that rarely occur during normal operation of the product.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not properly anticipate or handle exceptional conditions that rarely occur during normal operation of the product.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Confidentiality, Availability, Integrity. **Impact**: Read Application Data, DoS: Crash, Exit, or Restart, Unexpected State."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/703.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Improper Check or Handling of Exceptional Conditions",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
