            {
              "id": "CWE-1164",
              "name": "IrrelevantCode",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product contains code that is not essential for execution, i.e. makes no state changes and has no side effects that alter data or control flow, such that removal of the code would have no impact to functionality or correctness."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Irrelevant code could include dead code, initialization that is not used, empty blocks, code that could be entirely removed due to optimization, etc."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product contains code that is not essential for execution, i.e. makes no state changes and has no side effects that alter data or control flow, such that removal of the code would have no impact to functionality or correctness.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product contains code that is not essential for execution, i.e. makes no state changes and has no side effects that alter data or control flow, such that removal of the code would have no impact to functionality or correctness.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nIrrelevant code could include dead code, initialization that is not used, empty blocks, code that could be entirely removed due to optimization, etc.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Reduce Reliability.\n- **Scope**: Other. **Impact**: Reduce Performance."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/1164.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Irrelevant Code",
                "cwe/status": "Incomplete",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Class",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-710"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-1173",
              "name": "ImproperUseOfValidationFramework",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The product does not use, or incorrectly uses, an input validation framework that is provided by the source language or an independent library."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Many modern coding languages provide developers with input validation frameworks to make the task of input validation easier and less error-prone. These frameworks will automatically check all input against specified criteria and direct execution to error handlers when invalid input is received. The improper use (i.e., an incorrect implementation or missing altogether) of these frameworks is not directly exploitable, but can lead to an exploitable condition if proper input validation is not performed later in the product. Not using provided input validation frameworks can also hurt the maintainability of code as future developers may not recognize the downstream input validation being used in the place of the validation framework."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The product does not use, or incorrectly uses, an input validation framework that is provided by the source language or an independent library.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe product does not use, or incorrectly uses, an input validation framework that is provided by the source language or an independent library.\n\n## Extended Description\n\nMany modern coding languages provide developers with input validation frameworks to make the task of input validation easier and less error-prone. These frameworks will automatically check all input against specified criteria and direct execution to error handlers when invalid input is received. The improper use (i.e., an incorrect implementation or missing altogether) of these frameworks is not directly exploitable, but can lead to an exploitable condition if proper input validation is not performed later in the product. Not using provided input validation frameworks can also hurt the maintainability of code as future developers may not recognize the downstream input validation being used in the place of the validation framework.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Unexpected State.\n  - Unchecked input leads to cross-site scripting, process control, and SQL injection vulnerabilities, among others.\n\n## Potential Mitigations\n\n1. *Phase: Implementation*. Properly use provided input validation frameworks."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/1173.html",
              "properties": {
                "cwe/title": "Improper Use of Validation Framework",
                "cwe/status": "Draft",
                "cwe/abstraction": "Base",
                "cwe/parent": "CWE-20"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CWE-1174",
              "name": "AspNetMisconfigurationImproperModelValidation",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The ASP.NET application does not use, or incorrectly uses, the model validation framework."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The ASP.NET application does not use, or incorrectly uses, the model validation framework.",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe ASP.NET application does not use, or incorrectly uses, the model validation framework.\n\n## Common Consequences\n\n- **Scope**: Integrity. **Impact**: Unexpected State.\n  - Unchecked input leads to cross-site scripting, process control, and SQL injection vulnerabilities, among others."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/1174.html",
